ory:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Democrats]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Republicans]]\n[[Category:Mayors of New York City]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n[[Category:Jewish American people in New York (state) politics]]\n[[Category:Jewish American presidential candidates]]\n", "name_user": "Pickle Mon", "label": "safe", "comment": "A little under 5 months isn't really \"brief.\" Scott Walker is brief, Eric Swalwell is brief.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Bloomberg"}
{"title_page": "Westworld (film)", "text_new": "{{About|the 1973 film|the 2016 HBO TV series|Westworld (TV series)}}\n{{short description|1973 science fiction film directed by Michael Crichton}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Westworld\n| image          = Westworld ver2.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[Neal Adams]]\n| director       = [[Michael Crichton]]\n| producer       = [[Paul N. Lazarus III]]\n| writer         = Michael Crichton\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Yul Brynner]]\n* [[Richard Benjamin]]\n* [[James Brolin]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Fred Karlin]]\n| cinematography = [[Gene Polito]]\n| editing        = [[David Bretherton]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1973|08|17}}<ref name=AFI>{{AFI film|id=54403}}</ref>\n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.2 million<ref name=\"Crichton p x\">Crichton p x</ref>\n| gross          = $10 million<ref name=\"los\"/>\n}}\n'''''Westworld''''' is a 1973 American [[Science fiction film|science-fiction]] [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[thriller film]] written and directed by [[Michael Crichton]]. Its plot concerns amusement park [[Android (robot)|android]]s that malfunction and begin killing visitors. It stars [[Yul Brynner]] as an android in a futuristic [[American Old West|Western]]-themed amusement park, and [[Richard Benjamin]] and [[James Brolin]] as guests of the park.\n\nThe film was from an original screenplay by Crichton, and served as his [[List of directorial debuts|feature directorial debut]].<ref name=\"tcm.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=12461&mainArticleId=245816 |title=Westworld |website=tcm.com |publisher=TCM |access-date=April 29, 2012}}</ref> It was also the first feature film to use [[#Digital image processing|digital image processing]] to [[pixellate]] photography to simulate an android point of view.<ref name=yaeger>[http://www.beanblossom.in.us/larryy/cgi.html A Brief, Early History of Computer Graphics in Film] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717074134/http://www.beanblossom.in.us/larryy/cgi.html |date=July 17, 2012 }}, [[Larry Yaeger]], August 16, 2002 (last update). Retrieved March 24, 2010</ref> The film was nominated for [[Hugo Award|Hugo]], [[Nebula Award|Nebula]], and [[Saturn Awards|Saturn]] awards.\n\n''Westworld'' was followed by a sequel, ''[[Futureworld]]'' (1976), and a short-lived television series, ''[[Beyond Westworld]]'' (1980). [[Westworld (TV series)|A television series]] based on the film debuted in 2016 on [[HBO]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn the then-future year of 1983, a high-tech, highly realistic adult [[amusement park]] called Delos features three themed \"worlds\": Western World (the [[American Old West]]), Medieval World ([[medieval Europe]]), and Roman World (the [[ancient Roman]] city of [[Pompeii]]). The resort's three \"worlds\" are populated with lifelike [[Android (robot)|android]]s that are practically indistinguishable from human beings, each programmed in character for their assigned historical environment. For $1,000 per day, guests may indulge in any adventure with the android population of the park, including sexual encounters and a simulated fight to the death. Delos's tagline in its advertising promises \"Boy, have we got a vacation for you!\"\n\nPeter Martin, a first-time Delos visitor, and his friend John Blane, on a repeat visit, go to Westworld. One of the attractions is the [[Gunfighter|Gunslinger]], an android programmed to instigate gunfights. The firearms issued to the park guests have temperature sensors that prevent them from shooting anything with a high body temperature, such as humans, but allow them to \"kill\" the cold-blooded androids. The Gunslinger's programming allows guests to draw their guns and kill it, with the android always returning the next day for another duel.\n\nThe technicians running Delos notice problems beginning to [[Computer virus|spread like an infection among the androids]]: the androids in Roman World and Medieval World begin experiencing an increasing number of breakdowns and systemic failures, which are said to have spread to Westworld. When one of the supervising computer scientists scoffs at the \"analogy of an infectious disease\", he is told by the chief supervisor \"We aren't dealing with ordinary machines here. These are highly complicated pieces of equipment, almost as complicated as living organisms. In some cases, they've been [[Computer-aided engineering|designed by other computers]]. We don't know exactly how they work.\"\n\nThe malfunctions become more serious when a robotic rattlesnake bites Blane in Westworld, and, against its programming, an android refuses a guest's advances in Medieval World. The failures escalate until Medieval World's [[Black knight|Black Knight]] android kills a guest in a [[Swordsmanship|sword fight]]. The resort's supervisors try to regain control by shutting down power to the entire park. However, the shutdown traps them in central control when the doors automatically lock, unable to turn the power back on and escape. Meanwhile, the androids in all three worlds run amok, operating on reserve power.\n\nMartin and Blane, recovering from a drunken bar-room brawl, wake up in Westworld's [[brothel]], unaware of the park's massive breakdown. When the Gunslinger challenges the men to a showdown, Blane treats the confrontation as an amusement until the android outdraws and shoots, killing him. Martin runs for his life and the android implacably follows.\n\nMartin flees to the other areas of the park, but finds only dead guests, damaged androids, and a panicked technician attempting to escape Delos, who is shortly thereafter shot by the Gunslinger. Martin climbs down through a manhole in Roman World into the underground control complex and discovers that the resort's computer technicians suffocated in the control room when the ventilation system shut down. The Gunslinger stalks him through the underground corridors, so he runs away until he enters an android-repair laboratory. When the Gunslinger enters the room, Martin pretends to be an android, throws acid into the Gunslinger's face, and flees, returning to the surface inside the Medieval World castle.\n\nWith its optical inputs damaged by the acid, the Gunslinger is unable to track Martin visually and tries to find Martin using its [[infrared]] scanners. Martin stands beneath the flaming torches of the Great Hall to mask his presence from the android, before setting it on fire with one of the torches. The burned shell of the Gunslinger attacks him on the dungeon steps before succumbing to its damage. Martin sits on the dungeon steps in a state of near-exhaustion and shock, as the irony of Delos' slogan resonates: \"Boy, have we got a vacation for you!\"\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Yul Brynner]] as the Gunslinger\n* [[Richard Benjamin]] as Peter Martin\n* [[James Brolin]] as John Blane\n* [[Alan Oppenheimer]] as the Chief Supervisor\n* [[Victoria Shaw (actress)|Victoria Shaw]] as the Medieval Queen\n* [[Dick Van Patten]] as the Banker\n* [[Linda Gaye Scott|Linda Scott]] as Arlette, the French prostitute\n* [[Steve Franken]] as the Delos technician shot dead by the Gunslinger\n* Michael Mikler as the Black Knight\n* [[Terry Wilson (actor)|Terry Wilson]] as the Sheriff\n* [[Majel Barrett]] as Miss Carrie, madame of the Westworld bordello\n* [[Anne Randall]] as Daphne, the serving-maid who refuses the Medieval Knight's advances\n* [[Nora Marlowe]] as the Hostess\n* [[Charles Seel]] as the Bellhop\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Screenplay===\nCrichton said he did not wish to make his feature directorial debut (after one TV film) with science fiction but \"That's the only way I could get the studio to let me direct. People think I'm good at it I guess.\"<ref name=\"los\">Author of 'Terminal Man' Building Nonterminal Career: CRICHTON; GELMIS, JOSEPH. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] January 4, 1974: d12.</ref>\n\nCrichton's agent introduced him to producer [[Paul N. Lazarus III]]; they became friends and decided to make a film together.<ref name=\"pod\">{{cite podcast|url=http://nashvillepubliclibrary.org/offtheshelf/paul-lazarus-legends-of-film/|title=Legends of Film: Paul Lazarus|date=December 27, 2004}}</ref> The script was written in August 1972. Lazarus says he asked Crichton why he did not tell the story as a book; Crichton said he felt the story was visual, and would not really work as a book.<ref name=\"pod\"/>\n\nThe script was offered to all the major studios. They all turned down the project except for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], then under head of production [[Dan Melnick]] and president [[James T. Aubrey]]. Crichton said:\n\n{{Quote | MGM had a bad reputation among filmmakers; in recent years, directors as diverse as [[Robert Altman]], [[Blake Edwards]], [[Stanley Kubrick]], [[Fred Zinneman]] and [[Sam Peckinpah]] had complained bitterly about their treatment there. There were too many stories of unreasonable pressure, arbitrary script changes, inadequate post production, and cavalier recutting of the final film. Nobody who had a choice made a picture at Metro, but then we didn't have a choice. Dan Melnick&nbsp;... assured [us]&nbsp;... that we would not be subjected to the usual MGM treatment. In large part, he made good on that promise.<ref>Crichton p. ix</ref>}}\n\nCrichton said pre-production was difficult. MGM demanded script changes up to the first day of shooting and the leads were not signed until 48 hours before shooting began. Crichton said he had no control over casting<ref name=\"los\"/> and MGM originally would only make the film for under a million dollars but later increased this amount by $250,000.<ref name=\"Crichton p x\"/> Crichton said that $250,000 of the budget was paid to the cast, $400,000 to the crew and the remainder on everything else (including $75,000 for sets).<ref>Crichton p. x\u2013xi</ref>\n\n===Principal photography===\n''Westworld'' was filmed in several locations, including the [[Mojave Desert]], the gardens of the [[Harold Lloyd Estate]], several MGM [[sound stage]]s and on the MGM [[backlot]], one of the final films to be shot there.<ref name=\"tcm.com\"/> It was filmed with [[Panavision]] [[Anamorphic format|anamorphic]] lenses by [[Gene Polito]].\n\nRichard Benjamin later said he loved making the film:\n\n{{Quote | It probably was the only way I was ever going to get into a Western, and certainly into a science-fiction Western.... So you get to do stuff that's like you're 12 years old. All of the reasons you went to the movies in the first place. You're out there firing a six-shooter, riding a horse, being chased by a gunman, and all of that. It's the best!<ref name=\"av\">{{cite web| url= http://www.avclub.com/article/richard-benjamin-on-peter-otoole-celebrity-treasur-88775 |title= Richard Benjamin on Peter O'Toole, celebrity treasure hunts, and Woody Allen| first= Nathan| last= Rabin |authorlink= Nathan Rabin| website= AVClub.com |date= November 15, 2012| access-date= June 18, 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nThe Gunslinger's appearance is based on Chris Adams, Brynner's character from ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]''. The two characters' costumes are nearly identical.<ref>{{cite book |last=Friedman |first=Lester D. |title=American Cinema of the 1970s: Themes and Variations |publisher=Rutgers University Press |year=2007 |location=Camden |isbn=0-8135-4023-2 |page=100}}</ref> According to Lazarus, Yul Brynner agreed to play the role for only $75,000, because he needed the money.<ref name=\"pod\"/>\n\nIn the scene when Richard Benjamin's character splashes the Gunslinger in the face with acid, Brynner's face was covered with an oil-based makeup mixed with ground [[Alka-Seltzer]]. A splash of water then produced the fizzing effect.\n\nThe score for ''Westworld'' was composed by American composer [[Fred Karlin]]. It combines [[Ersatz good|ersatz]] western scoring, [[Diegesis#Film sound and music|source cues]], and [[electronic music]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/cds/detail.cfm/cdID/348/ |title=Film Score Monthly CD: Coma/Westworld/The Carey Treatment |website= Filmscoremonthly.com |access-date=April 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCrichton later wrote that since \"most of the situations in the film are cliches; they are incidents out of hundreds of old movies\" that the scenes \"should be shot as [[clich\u00e9]]s. This dictated a conventional treatment in the choice of lenses and the staging.\"<ref>Crichton p. xiii</ref>\n\nThe movie was shot in 30 days. In order to save time, Crichton tried to shoot only what was needed.<ref>Crichton p. xvi</ref>\n\nThe original script and original ending of the movie culminated in a fight between Martin and the Gunslinger, which resulted in the Gunslinger being torn apart by a rack. Crichton said he \"had liked the idea of a complex machine being destroyed by a simple machine\", but when attempting it, \"it seemed stagey and foolish\", so the idea was dropped.<ref name=\"Crichton p xix\">Crichton p. xix</ref> He also wanted to open the film with shots of a hovercraft traveling over the desert, but was unable to get the effect he wanted, so this was dropped as well.<ref name=\"Crichton p xix\"/>\n\n===Post-production===\nIn the novelization, Crichton explained how he re-edited the first cut of the movie, because he was depressed by how long and boring it was. Scenes that were deleted from the rough cut include a bank robbery and sales room sequences, an opening with a hovercraft flying above the desert, additional and longer dialogue scenes, more scenes with robots attacking and killing guests including a scene where one guest is tied down to a rack and is killed when his arms are pulled out, a longer chase scene with the Gunslinger chasing Peter, and one where the Gunslinger cleans his face with water after Peter throws acid on him. Crichton's assembly cut featured a different ending that included a fight between Gunslinger and Peter, and an alternate death scene in which the Gunslinger was killed on a rack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.putlearningfirst.com/br/westworldshoot.html|title=Shooting Westworld}}</ref>\n\nA Yul Brynner biography mentions that 10 minutes of \"adult material\" was cut, because of the censors, probably for [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#From M to GP to PG|PG rating]], but no details about footage that was cut for rating issues were mentioned in Brynner's biography or anywhere else.\n\nOnce the film was completed, MGM authorized the shooting of some extra footage. A television commercial to open the film was added; because there was a writers' strike in Hollywood at the time, this was written by Steven Frankfurt, a New York advertising executive.<ref>Crichton p xvii</ref>\n\n===Digital image processing===\n''Westworld'' was the first feature film to use [[digital image processing]]. Crichton originally went to the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] in Pasadena, but after learning that two minutes of animation would take nine months and cost $200,000, he contacted [[John Whitney (animator)|John Whitney Sr.]], who in turn recommended his son John Whitney Jr. The latter went to [[Information International, Inc.]], where they could work at night and complete the animation both faster and much more cheaply.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tested.com/art/movies/512325-whitney-family-pioneers-computer-animation/|title=The Whitney Family: Pioneers in Computer Animation |website=Tested.com}}</ref> Whitney Jr. digitally processed motion picture photography at Information International, Inc. to appear [[Pixelization|pixelized]] in order to portray the Gunslinger android's [[Point-of-view shot|point of view]].<ref name=yaeger/> The approximately 2 minutes and 31 seconds' worth of cinegraphic block portraiture was accomplished by color-separating (three basic color separations plus black mask) each frame of source [[70 mm film]] images, scanning each of these elements to convert into rectangular blocks, then adding basic color according to the tone values developed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atariarchives.org/artist/sec17.php |title=Ed Manning BlocPix |website=Atariarchives.org |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> The resulting coarse pixel matrix was output back to film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vasulka.org/archive/show-fest3/ArsElectronica'92/ChronologyTools/CompAnimTechHist.pdf |title=Chapter 4: A HISTORY OF COMPUTER ANIMATION 3/20/92 (note that this article is in error about the year the film was made) |access-date=April 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406031124/http://www.vasulka.org/archive/show-fest3/ArsElectronica'92/ChronologyTools/CompAnimTechHist.pdf |archive-date=April 6, 2008 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The process was covered in the ''[[American Cinematographer]]'' article \"Behind the scenes of Westworld\"<ref>''[[American Cinematographer]]'' 54(11):1394-1397, 1420-1421, 1436-1437. November 1973.</ref> and in a 2013 [[The New Yorker|''New Yorker'']] online article.<ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/how-michael-crichtons-westworld-pioneered-modern-special-effects \"How Michael Crichton's 'Westworld' Pioneered Modern Special Effects\"], David A. Price, ''The New Yorker'', May 16, 2013</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Box office===\nThe film was released on an experimental regional saturation basis<ref name=\"Var\"/> and grossed $2 million in its first week in 275 theatres in the Chicago, Detroit and Cleveland areas.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Day-by-day|magazine=[[Daily Variety]] |date=October 30, 1973|page=164}}</ref> It was MGM's biggest box-office success of that year,<ref name=\"los\"/> earning $4 million in rentals in the US and Canada by the end of 1973.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Big Rental Films of 1973|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 9, 1974|page=19}}</ref> After a re-release in 1976, it earned $7,365,000.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=All-time Film Rental Champs|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 7, 1976|page=44}}</ref>\n\n===Book tie-in===\nCrichton's original screenplay was released as a mass-market paperback in conjunction with the film.<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Crichton (Author) |url=https://www.amazon.com/Westworld-Michael-Crichton/dp/0553084410/ |title=Amazon Listing for Westworld |website=Amazon.com |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n[[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] described the film as excellent, saying that it \"combines solid entertainment, chilling topicality, and superbly intelligent serio-comic story values\".<ref name=\"Var\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/1972/film/reviews/westworld-1200422881/ |title=Westworld |page=12|date=August 15, 1973 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Crichton had made \"a creditable debut as a film director,\" but \"Crichton the director seems to have had more fun with the film than Crichton the writer, whose screenplay can offer us no better explanation for the sudden, bloody robot rebellion than an epidemic of 'central mechanism psychosis.'\"<ref>[[Vincent Canby|Canby, Vincent]] (November 22, 1973). \"The Screen: 'Westworld'\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. 51.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film three stars out of four, calling the first half \"exciting and provocative\" but thinking much less of the second half which he thought deteriorated into an \"illogical and meandering chase story. It is difficult to believe the same man wrote both halves of the film.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (August 17, 1973). \"'Westworld': Is it a look at tomorrow?\" ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 2, p. 1.</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"a clever sci-fi fantasy ... with enough ingenuity and conviction to make it a successful diversion for those seeking novel rather than sophisticated entertainment.\"<ref>[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Thomas, Kevin]] (October 24, 1973). \"Acting Out Fantasy in 'Westworld\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 11.</ref> Jean M. White of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that \"Crichton spends too much time establishing his robot world and short-circuits suspense with long, arid stretches of Grade B Western.\"<ref>White, Jean M. (September 26, 1973). \"Robots Run Amok\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. D8.</ref>\n\nThe film has a rating of 87% at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 38 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/westworld/ |title=Westworld (1973) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=June 24, 2010}}</ref> Reviewing the [[DVD-Video|DVD]] release in September 2008, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reviewer Philip Horne described the film as a \"richly suggestive, bleakly terrifying fable\u2014and Brynner's performance is chillingly pitch-perfect.\"<ref name=\"Tel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3560933/Westworld-DVD-of-the-week-review.html |title=Westworld: DVD of the week review |first=Philip |last=Horne |date=September 20, 2008 |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=June 24, 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n'''[[American Film Institute]] lists'''\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/thrills400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills Nominees |website=afi.com |publisher=American Film Institute |format=PDF |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains]]:\n** Robot Gunslinger \u2013 Nominated Villain<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes and Villains Nominees |website=afi.com |publisher=American Film Institute |format=PDF |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 10 Top 10]] \u2013 Nominated Science Fiction Film<ref>{{cite web|website=afi.com |publisher=American Film Institute |url=http://www.afi.com/drop/ballot.pdf |title=AFI's 10 Top 10 Ballot |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter making the film, Crichton took a year off. \"I was intensely fatigued by ''Westworld'',\" he said later. \"I was pleased but intimidated by the audience reaction. ... The laughs are in the wrong places. There was extreme tension where I hadn't planned it. I felt the reaction, and maybe the picture, was out of control.\"<ref name=\"los\"/> He believed that the film had been misunderstood as warning of the dangers of technology: \"Everyone remembers the scene in ''Westworld'' where Yul Brynner is a robot that runs amok. But there is a very specific scene where people discuss whether or not to shut down the resort. I think the movie was as much about that decision as anything. They just didn't really think it was really going to happen.\"<ref name=\"yakai198502\">{{cite news |title=Michael Crichton / Reflections of a New Designer |url=https://archive.org/stream/1985-02-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_057_1985_Feb#page/n45/mode/2up |work=Compute! |date=February 1985 |access-date=September 16, 2016 |author=Yakai, Kathy |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> His real intention was to warn against corporate greed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/09/westworld-franchise-long-weird-history.html |title=The Long, Weird History of the Westworld Franchise |website=Vulture |first=Brian |last=Tallerico |date=September 30, 2016 |access-date=November 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor him the picture marked the end of \"about five years of science fiction/monster pictures for me\".<ref name=\"los\"/> He took a break from the genre and wrote ''[[The Great Train Robbery (novel)|The Great Train Robbery]]''.\n\nCrichton did not make a film for another five years. He did try, and had one set up \"but I insisted on a certain way of doing it and as a result it was never made.\"<ref>\"Director Michael Crichton Films a Favorite Novelist\" by Michael Owen. ''The New York Times'' (1923-Current file) [New York, N.Y] January 28, 1979: D17.</ref>\n\n==Network television airings==\n''Westworld'' was first aired on [[NBC]] television on February 28, 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtango.com/series/nbc_saturday_night_movies/episodes?filters%5Bday%5D=&filters%5Bseason%5D=&filters%5Bbroadcast%5D=All&filters%5Bmedia%5D=&commit=|title=TV Tango Saturday Night Movies Broadcast Date for Westworld|access-date=June 14, 2014}}</ref> The network aired a slightly longer version of the film than was shown in theaters or subsequently released on home video. Some of the extra scenes that were added for the United States television version are:{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n* Brief fly-by exterior shot of the [[hovercraft]] zooming just a few feet above the desert floor. In the theatrical version, all scenes involving the hovercraft were interior shots only.\n* The scenes with the scientists having a meeting in the underground complex was much longer, giving more insight into their \"virus\" problem with the robots.\n* A scene of technicians talking in the locker room about the work load of each robot world.\n* There was a longer discussion between Peter and the sheriff after his arrest when he shot the Gunslinger.\n* A scene in Medieval World in which a guest is tortured on the rack, which appears in the theatrical version only as a still image, was restored.\n* The Gunslinger's chase of Peter through the three worlds was also extended.\n\n==Legacy==\nA [[sequel]], ''[[Futureworld]]'', was filmed in 1976, and released by [[American International Pictures]], rather than MGM. Only Brynner returned from the original cast to reprise his Gunslinger character, though it did provide details regarding the carnage: more than 50 guests killed and 95 staff members killed or wounded.\n\nFour years later, in 1980, the [[CBS]] television network aired a short-lived television series, ''[[Beyond Westworld]]'', \"which took the ''Futureworld'' concept of android doppelgangers, but ignored the movie itself, harking back to Westworld\"<ref>Sherman, Fraser A. (2010) ''Screen Enemies of the American Way'' McFarland pg 155</ref> with new characters. Its poor ratings caused it to be canceled after only three of the five episodes aired.\n\nCrichton used similar plot elements\u2014a high-tech amusement park running amok and a central control paralyzed by a power failure\u2014in his bestselling novel ''[[Jurassic Park (novel)|Jurassic Park]]''.\n\n''Westworld'' contains one of the earliest references to a computer virus and the first mention of the concept of a computer virus in a movie.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} The analogy is made by the Chief Supervisor in a staff meeting where the spread of malfunctions across the park is discussed.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0070909/synopsis: IMDB synopsis of Westworld. Retrieved June 15, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, ''[[Westworld 2000]]'', a [[video game]] sequel to the film, was released by [[Byron Preiss]] Multimedia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/westworld-2000 |title=''Westworld 2000'' |publisher=[[MobyGames]] |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2002, trade publications reported that a ''Westworld'' remake starring [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] was in production, and would be written by ''[[Terminator 3]]'' screenwriters Michael Ferris and John Bracanto.<ref name=\"EmpRe\">{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/News/story.asp?nid=17030 |title=Westworld Headed Back To Screen |date=August 12, 2005 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |access-date=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"VarRe\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117863930.html?categoryid=3&cs=1&query=westworld |title=Arnold back for 'Westworld,' 'Conan' redos |first=Michael |last=Fleming |date=March 13, 2002 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?id=41831|archive-url=https://archive.is/20071115042003/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?id=41831|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-11-15|title=Scifiwire |website=Scifi.com}}</ref> [[Tarsem Singh]] was originally slated to direct, but left the project. [[Quentin Tarantino]] was approached, but turned it down.<ref>[[Hostel: Part II]] DVD commentary track.</ref> On January 19, 2011, Warner Bros announced that plans for the remake were still active.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/heat-vision/lethal-weapon-wild-bunch-reboots-73493|title=EXCLUSIVE: 'Lethal Weapon,' 'Wild Bunch' Reboots Revived After Warner Bros. Exec Shuffle | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Borys|last=Kit}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, it was announced that [[HBO]] had ordered a pilot for a [[Westworld (TV series)|''Westworld'' TV series]], to be produced by [[J. J. Abrams]], [[Jonathan Nolan]], and [[Jerry Weintraub]]. Nolan and his wife [[Lisa Joy]] were set to write and executive produce the series, with Nolan directing the pilot episode.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hertzfeld |first=Laura |date=August 30, 2013|title=HBO orders 'Westworld' adaptation from J.J. Abrams |work=Entertainment Weekly |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/08/30/westworld-jj-abrams-hbo/|access-date=September 2, 2013}}</ref> Production began in Summer 2014 in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fienberg |first=David |title=Press Tour: July 2014 HBO Executive Session Live-Blog|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-fien-print/press-tour-july-2014-hbo-executive-session-live-blog/|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Laratonda |first=Ryanne |title=Los Angeles Film & TV Production Listings|url=http://www.backstage.com/los-angeles-production-listings/|access-date=July 2, 2014}}</ref> The new series premiered October 2, 2016. On May 1, 2018, the series was renewed for a third season.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AFI film|id=54403}}\n* {{IMDb title|0070909|Westworld}}\n* {{TCMDb title|2748|Westworld}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|westworld|Westworld}}\n\n{{Westworld}}\n{{Michael Crichton}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westworld}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:1970s science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American chase films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) films]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Michael Crichton]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Fred Karlin]]\n[[Category:Films set in amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1983]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Westworld]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Michael Crichton]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1973 film|the 2016 HBO TV series|Westworld (TV series)}}\n{{short description|1973 science fiction film directed by Michael Crichton}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Westworld\n| image          = Westworld ver2.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[Neal Adams]]\n| director       = [[Michael Crichton]]\n| producer       = [[Paul N. Lazarus III]]\n| writer         = Michael Crichton\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Yul Brynner]]\n* [[Richard Benjamin]]\n* [[James Brolin]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Fred Karlin]]\n| cinematography = [[Gene Polito]]\n| editing        = [[David Bretherton]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1973|08|17}}<ref name=AFI>{{AFI film|id=54403}}</ref>\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.2 million<ref name=\"Crichton p x\">Crichton p x</ref>\n| gross          = $10 million<ref name=\"los\"/>\n}}\n'''''Westworld''''' is a 1973 American [[Science fiction film|science-fiction]] [[Western (genre)|Western]] [[thriller film]] written and directed by [[Michael Crichton]]. Its plot concerns amusement park [[Android (robot)|android]]s that malfunction and begin killing visitors. It stars [[Yul Brynner]] as an android in a futuristic [[American Old West|Western]]-themed amusement park, and [[Richard Benjamin]] and [[James Brolin]] as guests of the park.\n\nThe film was from an original screenplay by Crichton, and served as his [[List of directorial debuts|feature directorial debut]].<ref name=\"tcm.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/thismonth/article.jsp?cid=12461&mainArticleId=245816 |title=Westworld |website=tcm.com |publisher=TCM |access-date=April 29, 2012}}</ref> It was also the first feature film to use [[#Digital image processing|digital image processing]] to [[pixellate]] photography to simulate an android point of view.<ref name=yaeger>[http://www.beanblossom.in.us/larryy/cgi.html A Brief, Early History of Computer Graphics in Film] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717074134/http://www.beanblossom.in.us/larryy/cgi.html |date=July 17, 2012 }}, [[Larry Yaeger]], August 16, 2002 (last update). Retrieved March 24, 2010</ref> The film was nominated for [[Hugo Award|Hugo]], [[Nebula Award|Nebula]], and [[Saturn Awards|Saturn]] awards.\n\n''Westworld'' was followed by a sequel, ''[[Futureworld]]'' (1976), and a short-lived television series, ''[[Beyond Westworld]]'' (1980). [[Westworld (TV series)|A television series]] based on the film debuted in 2016 on [[HBO]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn the then-future year of 1983, a high-tech, highly realistic adult [[amusement park]] called Delos features three themed \"worlds\": Western World (the [[American Old West]]), Medieval World ([[medieval Europe]]), and Roman World (the [[ancient Roman]] city of [[Pompeii]]). The resort's three \"worlds\" are populated with lifelike [[Android (robot)|android]]s that are practically indistinguishable from human beings, each programmed in character for their assigned historical environment. For $1,000 per day, guests may indulge in any adventure with the android population of the park, including sexual encounters and a simulated fight to the death. Delos's tagline in its advertising promises \"Boy, have we got a vacation for you!\"\n\nPeter Martin, a first-time Delos visitor, and his friend John Blane, on a repeat visit, go to Westworld. One of the attractions is the [[Gunfighter|Gunslinger]], an android programmed to instigate gunfights. The firearms issued to the park guests have temperature sensors that prevent them from shooting anything with a high body temperature, such as humans, but allow them to \"kill\" the cold-blooded androids. The Gunslinger's programming allows guests to draw their guns and kill it, with the android always returning the next day for another duel.\n\nThe technicians running Delos notice problems beginning to [[Computer virus|spread like an infection among the androids]]: the androids in Roman World and Medieval World begin experiencing an increasing number of breakdowns and systemic failures, which are said to have spread to Westworld. When one of the supervising computer scientists scoffs at the \"analogy of an infectious disease\", he is told by the chief supervisor \"We aren't dealing with ordinary machines here. These are highly complicated pieces of equipment, almost as complicated as living organisms. In some cases, they've been [[Computer-aided engineering|designed by other computers]]. We don't know exactly how they work.\"\n\nThe malfunctions become more serious when a robotic rattlesnake bites Blane in Westworld, and, against its programming, an android refuses a guest's advances in Medieval World. The failures escalate until Medieval World's [[Black knight|Black Knight]] android kills a guest in a [[Swordsmanship|sword fight]]. The resort's supervisors try to regain control by shutting down power to the entire park. However, the shutdown traps them in central control when the doors automatically lock, unable to turn the power back on and escape. Meanwhile, the androids in all three worlds run amok, operating on reserve power.\n\nMartin and Blane, recovering from a drunken bar-room brawl, wake up in Westworld's [[brothel]], unaware of the park's massive breakdown. When the Gunslinger challenges the men to a showdown, Blane treats the confrontation as an amusement until the android outdraws and shoots, killing him. Martin runs for his life and the android implacably follows.\n\nMartin flees to the other areas of the park, but finds only dead guests, damaged androids, and a panicked technician attempting to escape Delos, who is shortly thereafter shot by the Gunslinger. Martin climbs down through a manhole in Roman World into the underground control complex and discovers that the resort's computer technicians suffocated in the control room when the ventilation system shut down. The Gunslinger stalks him through the underground corridors, so he runs away until he enters an android-repair laboratory. When the Gunslinger enters the room, Martin pretends to be an android, throws acid into the Gunslinger's face, and flees, returning to the surface inside the Medieval World castle.\n\nWith its optical inputs damaged by the acid, the Gunslinger is unable to track Martin visually and tries to find Martin using its [[infrared]] scanners. Martin stands beneath the flaming torches of the Great Hall to mask his presence from the android, before setting it on fire with one of the torches. The burned shell of the Gunslinger attacks him on the dungeon steps before succumbing to its damage. Martin sits on the dungeon steps in a state of near-exhaustion and shock, as the irony of Delos' slogan resonates: \"Boy, have we got a vacation for you!\"\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Yul Brynner]] as the Gunslinger\n* [[Richard Benjamin]] as Peter Martin\n* [[James Brolin]] as John Blane\n* [[Alan Oppenheimer]] as the Chief Supervisor\n* [[Victoria Shaw (actress)|Victoria Shaw]] as the Medieval Queen\n* [[Dick Van Patten]] as the Banker\n* [[Linda Gaye Scott|Linda Scott]] as Arlette, the French prostitute\n* [[Steve Franken]] as the Delos technician shot dead by the Gunslinger\n* Michael Mikler as the Black Knight\n* [[Terry Wilson (actor)|Terry Wilson]] as the Sheriff\n* [[Majel Barrett]] as Miss Carrie, madame of the Westworld bordello\n* [[Anne Randall]] as Daphne, the serving-maid who refuses the Medieval Knight's advances\n* [[Nora Marlowe]] as the Hostess\n* [[Charles Seel]] as the Bellhop\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Screenplay===\nCrichton said he did not wish to make his feature directorial debut (after one TV film) with science fiction but \"That's the only way I could get the studio to let me direct. People think I'm good at it I guess.\"<ref name=\"los\">Author of 'Terminal Man' Building Nonterminal Career: CRICHTON; GELMIS, JOSEPH. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] January 4, 1974: d12.</ref>\n\nCrichton's agent introduced him to producer [[Paul N. Lazarus III]]; they became friends and decided to make a film together.<ref name=\"pod\">{{cite podcast|url=http://nashvillepubliclibrary.org/offtheshelf/paul-lazarus-legends-of-film/|title=Legends of Film: Paul Lazarus|date=December 27, 2004}}</ref> The script was written in August 1972. Lazarus says he asked Crichton why he did not tell the story as a book; Crichton said he felt the story was visual, and would not really work as a book.<ref name=\"pod\"/>\n\nThe script was offered to all the major studios. They all turned down the project except for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], then under head of production [[Dan Melnick]] and president [[James T. Aubrey]]. Crichton said:\n\n{{Quote | MGM had a bad reputation among filmmakers; in recent years, directors as diverse as [[Robert Altman]], [[Blake Edwards]], [[Stanley Kubrick]], [[Fred Zinneman]] and [[Sam Peckinpah]] had complained bitterly about their treatment there. There were too many stories of unreasonable pressure, arbitrary script changes, inadequate post production, and cavalier recutting of the final film. Nobody who had a choice made a picture at Metro, but then we didn't have a choice. Dan Melnick&nbsp;... assured [us]&nbsp;... that we would not be subjected to the usual MGM treatment. In large part, he made good on that promise.<ref>Crichton p. ix</ref>}}\n\nCrichton said pre-production was difficult. MGM demanded script changes up to the first day of shooting and the leads were not signed until 48 hours before shooting began. Crichton said he had no control over casting<ref name=\"los\"/> and MGM originally would only make the film for under a million dollars but later increased this amount by $250,000.<ref name=\"Crichton p x\"/> Crichton said that $250,000 of the budget was paid to the cast, $400,000 to the crew and the remainder on everything else (including $75,000 for sets).<ref>Crichton p. x\u2013xi</ref>\n\n===Principal photography===\n''Westworld'' was filmed in several locations, including the [[Mojave Desert]], the gardens of the [[Harold Lloyd Estate]], several MGM [[sound stage]]s and on the MGM [[backlot]], one of the final films to be shot there.<ref name=\"tcm.com\"/> It was filmed with [[Panavision]] [[Anamorphic format|anamorphic]] lenses by [[Gene Polito]].\n\nRichard Benjamin later said he loved making the film:\n\n{{Quote | It probably was the only way I was ever going to get into a Western, and certainly into a science-fiction Western.... So you get to do stuff that's like you're 12 years old. All of the reasons you went to the movies in the first place. You're out there firing a six-shooter, riding a horse, being chased by a gunman, and all of that. It's the best!<ref name=\"av\">{{cite web| url= http://www.avclub.com/article/richard-benjamin-on-peter-otoole-celebrity-treasur-88775 |title= Richard Benjamin on Peter O'Toole, celebrity treasure hunts, and Woody Allen| first= Nathan| last= Rabin |authorlink= Nathan Rabin| website= AVClub.com |date= November 15, 2012| access-date= June 18, 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nThe Gunslinger's appearance is based on Chris Adams, Brynner's character from ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]''. The two characters' costumes are nearly identical.<ref>{{cite book |last=Friedman |first=Lester D. |title=American Cinema of the 1970s: Themes and Variations |publisher=Rutgers University Press |year=2007 |location=Camden |isbn=0-8135-4023-2 |page=100}}</ref> According to Lazarus, Yul Brynner agreed to play the role for only $75,000, because he needed the money.<ref name=\"pod\"/>\n\nIn the scene when Richard Benjamin's character splashes the Gunslinger in the face with acid, Brynner's face was covered with an oil-based makeup mixed with ground [[Alka-Seltzer]]. A splash of water then produced the fizzing effect.\n\nThe score for ''Westworld'' was composed by American composer [[Fred Karlin]]. It combines [[Ersatz good|ersatz]] western scoring, [[Diegesis#Film sound and music|source cues]], and [[electronic music]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/cds/detail.cfm/cdID/348/ |title=Film Score Monthly CD: Coma/Westworld/The Carey Treatment |website= Filmscoremonthly.com |access-date=April 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCrichton later wrote that since \"most of the situations in the film are cliches; they are incidents out of hundreds of old movies\" that the scenes \"should be shot as [[clich\u00e9]]s. This dictated a conventional treatment in the choice of lenses and the staging.\"<ref>Crichton p. xiii</ref>\n\nThe movie was shot in 30 days. In order to save time, Crichton tried to shoot only what was needed.<ref>Crichton p. xvi</ref>\n\nThe original script and original ending of the movie culminated in a fight between Martin and the Gunslinger, which resulted in the Gunslinger being torn apart by a rack. Crichton said he \"had liked the idea of a complex machine being destroyed by a simple machine\", but when attempting it, \"it seemed stagey and foolish\", so the idea was dropped.<ref name=\"Crichton p xix\">Crichton p. xix</ref> He also wanted to open the film with shots of a hovercraft traveling over the desert, but was unable to get the effect he wanted, so this was dropped as well.<ref name=\"Crichton p xix\"/>\n\n===Post-production===\nIn the novelization, Crichton explained how he re-edited the first cut of the movie, because he was depressed by how long and boring it was. Scenes that were deleted from the rough cut include a bank robbery and sales room sequences, an opening with a hovercraft flying above the desert, additional and longer dialogue scenes, more scenes with robots attacking and killing guests including a scene where one guest is tied down to a rack and is killed when his arms are pulled out, a longer chase scene with the Gunslinger chasing Peter, and one where the Gunslinger cleans his face with water after Peter throws acid on him. Crichton's assembly cut featured a different ending that included a fight between Gunslinger and Peter, and an alternate death scene in which the Gunslinger was killed on a rack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.putlearningfirst.com/br/westworldshoot.html|title=Shooting Westworld}}</ref>\n\nA Yul Brynner biography mentions that 10 minutes of \"adult material\" was cut, because of the censors, probably for [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#From M to GP to PG|PG rating]], but no details about footage that was cut for rating issues were mentioned in Brynner's biography or anywhere else.\n\nOnce the film was completed, MGM authorized the shooting of some extra footage. A television commercial to open the film was added; because there was a writers' strike in Hollywood at the time, this was written by Steven Frankfurt, a New York advertising executive.<ref>Crichton p xvii</ref>\n\n===Digital image processing===\n''Westworld'' was the first feature film to use [[digital image processing]]. Crichton originally went to the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] in Pasadena, but after learning that two minutes of animation would take nine months and cost $200,000, he contacted [[John Whitney (animator)|John Whitney Sr.]], who in turn recommended his son John Whitney Jr. The latter went to [[Information International, Inc.]], where they could work at night and complete the animation both faster and much more cheaply.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tested.com/art/movies/512325-whitney-family-pioneers-computer-animation/|title=The Whitney Family: Pioneers in Computer Animation |website=Tested.com}}</ref> Whitney Jr. digitally processed motion picture photography at Information International, Inc. to appear [[Pixelization|pixelized]] in order to portray the Gunslinger android's [[Point-of-view shot|point of view]].<ref name=yaeger/> The approximately 2 minutes and 31 seconds' worth of cinegraphic block portraiture was accomplished by color-separating (three basic color separations plus black mask) each frame of source [[70 mm film]] images, scanning each of these elements to convert into rectangular blocks, then adding basic color according to the tone values developed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atariarchives.org/artist/sec17.php |title=Ed Manning BlocPix |website=Atariarchives.org |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> The resulting coarse pixel matrix was output back to film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vasulka.org/archive/show-fest3/ArsElectronica'92/ChronologyTools/CompAnimTechHist.pdf |title=Chapter 4: A HISTORY OF COMPUTER ANIMATION 3/20/92 (note that this article is in error about the year the film was made) |access-date=April 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406031124/http://www.vasulka.org/archive/show-fest3/ArsElectronica'92/ChronologyTools/CompAnimTechHist.pdf |archive-date=April 6, 2008 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The process was covered in the ''[[American Cinematographer]]'' article \"Behind the scenes of Westworld\"<ref>''[[American Cinematographer]]'' 54(11):1394-1397, 1420-1421, 1436-1437. November 1973.</ref> and in a 2013 [[The New Yorker|''New Yorker'']] online article.<ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/how-michael-crichtons-westworld-pioneered-modern-special-effects \"How Michael Crichton's 'Westworld' Pioneered Modern Special Effects\"], David A. Price, ''The New Yorker'', May 16, 2013</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Box office===\nThe film was released on an experimental regional saturation basis<ref name=\"Var\"/> and grossed $2 million in its first week in 275 theatres in the Chicago, Detroit and Cleveland areas.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Day-by-day|magazine=[[Daily Variety]] |date=October 30, 1973|page=164}}</ref> It was MGM's biggest box-office success of that year,<ref name=\"los\"/> earning $4 million in rentals in the US and Canada by the end of 1973.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Big Rental Films of 1973|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 9, 1974|page=19}}</ref> After a re-release in 1976, it earned $7,365,000.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=All-time Film Rental Champs|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 7, 1976|page=44}}</ref>\n\n===Book tie-in===\nCrichton's original screenplay was released as a mass-market paperback in conjunction with the film.<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael Crichton (Author) |url=https://www.amazon.com/Westworld-Michael-Crichton/dp/0553084410/ |title=Amazon Listing for Westworld |website=Amazon.com |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n[[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] described the film as excellent, saying that it \"combines solid entertainment, chilling topicality, and superbly intelligent serio-comic story values\".<ref name=\"Var\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/1972/film/reviews/westworld-1200422881/ |title=Westworld |page=12|date=August 15, 1973 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Crichton had made \"a creditable debut as a film director,\" but \"Crichton the director seems to have had more fun with the film than Crichton the writer, whose screenplay can offer us no better explanation for the sudden, bloody robot rebellion than an epidemic of 'central mechanism psychosis.'\"<ref>[[Vincent Canby|Canby, Vincent]] (November 22, 1973). \"The Screen: 'Westworld'\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. 51.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film three stars out of four, calling the first half \"exciting and provocative\" but thinking much less of the second half which he thought deteriorated into an \"illogical and meandering chase story. It is difficult to believe the same man wrote both halves of the film.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (August 17, 1973). \"'Westworld': Is it a look at tomorrow?\" ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 2, p. 1.</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \"a clever sci-fi fantasy ... with enough ingenuity and conviction to make it a successful diversion for those seeking novel rather than sophisticated entertainment.\"<ref>[[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Thomas, Kevin]] (October 24, 1973). \"Acting Out Fantasy in 'Westworld\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 11.</ref> Jean M. White of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that \"Crichton spends too much time establishing his robot world and short-circuits suspense with long, arid stretches of Grade B Western.\"<ref>White, Jean M. (September 26, 1973). \"Robots Run Amok\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. D8.</ref>\n\nThe film has a rating of 87% at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 38 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/westworld/ |title=Westworld (1973) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=June 24, 2010}}</ref> Reviewing the [[DVD-Video|DVD]] release in September 2008, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reviewer Philip Horne described the film as a \"richly suggestive, bleakly terrifying fable\u2014and Brynner's performance is chillingly pitch-perfect.\"<ref name=\"Tel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3560933/Westworld-DVD-of-the-week-review.html |title=Westworld: DVD of the week review |first=Philip |last=Horne |date=September 20, 2008 |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=June 24, 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n'''[[American Film Institute]] lists'''\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills]] \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/thrills400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills Nominees |website=afi.com |publisher=American Film Institute |format=PDF |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains]]:\n** Robot Gunslinger \u2013 Nominated Villain<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/handv400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes and Villains Nominees |website=afi.com |publisher=American Film Institute |format=PDF |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[AFI's 10 Top 10]] \u2013 Nominated Science Fiction Film<ref>{{cite web|website=afi.com |publisher=American Film Institute |url=http://www.afi.com/drop/ballot.pdf |title=AFI's 10 Top 10 Ballot |access-date=February 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter making the film, Crichton took a year off. \"I was intensely fatigued by ''Westworld'',\" he said later. \"I was pleased but intimidated by the audience reaction. ... The laughs are in the wrong places. There was extreme tension where I hadn't planned it. I felt the reaction, and maybe the picture, was out of control.\"<ref name=\"los\"/> He believed that the film had been misunderstood as warning of the dangers of technology: \"Everyone remembers the scene in ''Westworld'' where Yul Brynner is a robot that runs amok. But there is a very specific scene where people discuss whether or not to shut down the resort. I think the movie was as much about that decision as anything. They just didn't really think it was really going to happen.\"<ref name=\"yakai198502\">{{cite news |title=Michael Crichton / Reflections of a New Designer |url=https://archive.org/stream/1985-02-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_057_1985_Feb#page/n45/mode/2up |work=Compute! |date=February 1985 |access-date=September 16, 2016 |author=Yakai, Kathy |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> His real intention was to warn against corporate greed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/09/westworld-franchise-long-weird-history.html |title=The Long, Weird History of the Westworld Franchise |website=Vulture |first=Brian |last=Tallerico |date=September 30, 2016 |access-date=November 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor him the picture marked the end of \"about five years of science fiction/monster pictures for me\".<ref name=\"los\"/> He took a break from the genre and wrote ''[[The Great Train Robbery (novel)|The Great Train Robbery]]''.\n\nCrichton did not make a film for another five years. He did try, and had one set up \"but I insisted on a certain way of doing it and as a result it was never made.\"<ref>\"Director Michael Crichton Films a Favorite Novelist\" by Michael Owen. ''The New York Times'' (1923-Current file) [New York, N.Y] January 28, 1979: D17.</ref>\n\n==Network television airings==\n''Westworld'' was first aired on [[NBC]] television on February 28, 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtango.com/series/nbc_saturday_night_movies/episodes?filters%5Bday%5D=&filters%5Bseason%5D=&filters%5Bbroadcast%5D=All&filters%5Bmedia%5D=&commit=|title=TV Tango Saturday Night Movies Broadcast Date for Westworld|access-date=June 14, 2014}}</ref> The network aired a slightly longer version of the film than was shown in theaters or subsequently released on home video. Some of the extra scenes that were added for the United States television version are:{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n* Brief fly-by exterior shot of the [[hovercraft]] zooming just a few feet above the desert floor. In the theatrical version, all scenes involving the hovercraft were interior shots only.\n* The scenes with the scientists having a meeting in the underground complex was much longer, giving more insight into their \"virus\" problem with the robots.\n* A scene of technicians talking in the locker room about the work load of each robot world.\n* There was a longer discussion between Peter and the sheriff after his arrest when he shot the Gunslinger.\n* A scene in Medieval World in which a guest is tortured on the rack, which appears in the theatrical version only as a still image, was restored.\n* The Gunslinger's chase of Peter through the three worlds was also extended.\n\n==Legacy==\nA [[sequel]], ''[[Futureworld]]'', was filmed in 1976, and released by [[American International Pictures]], rather than MGM. Only Brynner returned from the original cast to reprise his Gunslinger character, though it did provide details regarding the carnage: more than 50 guests killed and 95 staff members killed or wounded.\n\nFour years later, in 1980, the [[CBS]] television network aired a short-lived television series, ''[[Beyond Westworld]]'', \"which took the ''Futureworld'' concept of android doppelgangers, but ignored the movie itself, harking back to Westworld\"<ref>Sherman, Fraser A. (2010) ''Screen Enemies of the American Way'' McFarland pg 155</ref> with new characters. Its poor ratings caused it to be canceled after only three of the five episodes aired.\n\nCrichton used similar plot elements\u2014a high-tech amusement park running amok and a central control paralyzed by a power failure\u2014in his bestselling novel ''[[Jurassic Park (novel)|Jurassic Park]]''.\n\n''Westworld'' contains one of the earliest references to a computer virus and the first mention of the concept of a computer virus in a movie.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} The analogy is made by the Chief Supervisor in a staff meeting where the spread of malfunctions across the park is discussed.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0070909/synopsis: IMDB synopsis of Westworld. Retrieved June 15, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, ''[[Westworld 2000]]'', a [[video game]] sequel to the film, was released by [[Byron Preiss]] Multimedia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/westworld-2000 |title=''Westworld 2000'' |publisher=[[MobyGames]] |accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2002, trade publications reported that a ''Westworld'' remake starring [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] was in production, and would be written by ''[[Terminator 3]]'' screenwriters Michael Ferris and John Bracanto.<ref name=\"EmpRe\">{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/News/story.asp?nid=17030 |title=Westworld Headed Back To Screen |date=August 12, 2005 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |access-date=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"VarRe\">{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117863930.html?categoryid=3&cs=1&query=westworld |title=Arnold back for 'Westworld,' 'Conan' redos |first=Michael |last=Fleming |date=March 13, 2002 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?id=41831|archive-url=https://archive.is/20071115042003/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/index.php?id=41831|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-11-15|title=Scifiwire |website=Scifi.com}}</ref> [[Tarsem Singh]] was originally slated to direct, but left the project. [[Quentin Tarantino]] was approached, but turned it down.<ref>[[Hostel: Part II]] DVD commentary track.</ref> On January 19, 2011, Warner Bros announced that plans for the remake were still active.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/heat-vision/lethal-weapon-wild-bunch-reboots-73493|title=EXCLUSIVE: 'Lethal Weapon,' 'Wild Bunch' Reboots Revived After Warner Bros. Exec Shuffle | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Borys|last=Kit}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, it was announced that [[HBO]] had ordered a pilot for a [[Westworld (TV series)|''Westworld'' TV series]], to be produced by [[J. J. Abrams]], [[Jonathan Nolan]], and [[Jerry Weintraub]]. Nolan and his wife [[Lisa Joy]] were set to write and executive produce the series, with Nolan directing the pilot episode.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hertzfeld |first=Laura |date=August 30, 2013|title=HBO orders 'Westworld' adaptation from J.J. Abrams |work=Entertainment Weekly |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/08/30/westworld-jj-abrams-hbo/|access-date=September 2, 2013}}</ref> Production began in Summer 2014 in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fienberg |first=David |title=Press Tour: July 2014 HBO Executive Session Live-Blog|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-fien-print/press-tour-july-2014-hbo-executive-session-live-blog/|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Laratonda |first=Ryanne |title=Los Angeles Film & TV Production Listings|url=http://www.backstage.com/los-angeles-production-listings/|access-date=July 2, 2014}}</ref> The new series premiered October 2, 2016. On May 1, 2018, the series was renewed for a third season.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AFI film|id=54403}}\n* {{IMDb title|0070909|Westworld}}\n* {{TCMDb title|2748|Westworld}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|westworld|Westworld}}\n\n{{Westworld}}\n{{Michael Crichton}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westworld}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:1970s science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American chase films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction thriller films]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) films]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Michael Crichton]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Fred Karlin]]\n[[Category:Films set in amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1983]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Westworld]]\n[[Category:Western (genre) science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Michael Crichton]]\n", "name_user": "Mdiamante", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(according to my Amazon rental, the movie is 98 minutes long, not 88.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Westworld_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Chemicus", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Chemicus\n| released = 2001\n}}\n\n'''''Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side''''' is a 2001 educational adventure game by [[Heureka-Klett]] as part of Tivola's \"Quest for Knowledge\" series. A sequel named '''''Chemicus II: Die versunkene Stadt''''' was released in 2002. The game was originally released in Germany.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe first-person game has gameplay similar to ''[[Myst]]'' and ''[[Riven]].''\n\n== Plot ==\nThe player is a friend of Richard, a chemistry lover who is falsely accused of stealing a treasured item from the land of Chemicus after he arrives there in a portal. It is the player's job to rescue him.\n\nThe game has no death states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uhs-hints.com/articles/reviews/chemicus.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407092141/http://www.uhs-hints.com/articles/reviews/chemicus.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-04-07|title=UHS: Chemicus Review|date=2016-04-07|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nEblong likened the game's puzzle design to games such as ''[[Zork: Grand Inquisitor]]'', ''Myst'', and ''[[Traitors Gate]]'' though noted that puzzles are completed by doing chemistry experiments rather than using spells, in-universe mythology or technological gizmos respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eblong.com/zarf/gamerev/chemicus.html|title=Review: Chemicus|website=www.eblong.com|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref> Metzomagic praised the game's graphics and musical score, and deemed it harder than its sister games [[Physicus]] and [[Bioscopia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metzomagic.com/showArticle.php?index=520|title=Chemicus Review by metzomagic.com|website=www.metzomagic.com|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>  Adventure Gamers thought the concept was admirable and was interesting in playing the sequel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adventuregamers.com:80/display.php?id=224|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041104191958/http://www.adventuregamers.com:80/display.php?id=224|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-11-04|title=Chemicus {{!}} Adventure Gamers|date=2004-11-04|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nAdventure Archiv thought the puzzles were fastidiously designed and that chemistry concepts were seamlessly integrated into the gameplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adventurearchiv.de/c/chemicusreviewen.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311070649/http://adventurearchiv.de/c/chemicusreviewen.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-11|title=Chemicus - Review english|date=2016-03-11|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> Gameboomers gave the game very high praise and was excited to try the other two games in the series,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gameboomers.com/reviews/Cc/Chemicusbysyd.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330111618/http://www.gameboomers.com/reviews/Cc/Chemicusbysyd.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-30|title=Chemicus review by syd|date=2016-03-30|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> and Mr Bills Adventure Land went away with a similar impression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mrbillsadventureland.com/reviews/c-d/chemicusR/chemicusR.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322024130/http://mrbillsadventureland.com/reviews/c-d/chemicusR/chemicusR.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-22|title=Chemicus Review - Mr. Bill's Adventureland|date=2016-03-22|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> Tap Repeatedly highly recommended the game as a chemistry learning tool for children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tap-repeatedly.com/Reviews/Chemicus/Chemicus.shtml|title=Four Fat Chicks -- Chemicus Review|website=www.tap-repeatedly.com|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> The AV Vault gave the game high praise, and noted that it managed to overcome the negative stigma around educational games as having \"terrible graphics, shallow stories, little replay value, and shoddy production values\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504114127/http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-05-04|title=AVault {{!}} PC {{!}} Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side Review|date=2006-05-04|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528021804/http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-05-28|title=AVault {{!}} PC {{!}} Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side Review|date=2006-05-28|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041121141525/http://www.avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=3|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-11-21|title=AVault {{!}} PC {{!}} Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side Review|date=2004-11-21|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nJust Adventure noted that while there was an overarching goal, there was no plot-related logical reasoning given for the player to complete each individual puzzle, beside the fact that they can't progress to different areas until they do.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://justadventure.com/2013-05-20-21-09-14/1099-chemicus|title=Throwback Thursday: Chemicus|last=Tait|first=Alexander|website=justadventure.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224101555/http://justadventure.com/2013-05-20-21-09-14/1099-chemicus|archive-date=2017-12-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> Similarly, Adventure Gamers thought the game could have been served better by having a juicier story that matched its intriguing world and puzzles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adventuregamers.com/articles/view/17597|title=Chemicus Review|website=Adventure Gamers|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> GameSpy offered a mixed review, but ultimately gave it a 1 star rating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/chemicus/5669p1.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908080721/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/chemicus/5669p1.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-09-08|title=GameSpy: Chemicus - Page 1|date=2015-09-08|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> Mystery Manor wrote that the addition of a narrator would have sharply improved the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mysterymanor.net/reviewchemicus.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805000429/http://mysterymanor.net/reviewchemicus.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-08-05|title=Mystery Manor Chemicus Review|date=2016-08-05|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nAdventureTreff thought that Chemicus 2 worked well as a sequel, despite its limited budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adventure-treff.de/artikel/tests/chemicus2.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050227220905/http://www.adventure-treff.de/artikel/tests/chemicus2.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-02-27|title=Adventure-Treff|date=2005-02-27|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and nominations ===\n* 2002 Comenius medal (won)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediengewalt.de/spiele/beste-lernspiele-kinder-12-jahre.shtml|title=Beste Lernspiele f\u00fcr Kinder ab 12 Jahre (und andere Altersgruppen)|website=www.mediengewalt.de|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n* 2002 Giga Mouse - 6 mice (nominated)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2002 Padi Seal of Approval<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2002 6 Buffalo at Edut@in-Preis<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:Adventure games]]\n[[Category:Educational video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Underlinked|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Chemicus\n| released = 2001\n}}\n\n'''''Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side''''' is a 2001 educational adventure game by HEUREKA-Klett Softwareverlag as part of Tivola's \"Quest for Knowledge\" series. A sequel named '''''Chemicus II: Die versunkene Stadt''''' was released in 2002. The game was originally released in Germany.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe first-person game has gameplay similar to ''Myst'' and ''Riven.''\n\n== Plot ==\nThe player is a friend of Richard, a chemistry lover who is falsely accused of stealing a treasured item from the land of Chemicus after he arrives there in a portal. It is the player's job to rescue him.\n\nThe game has no death states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uhs-hints.com/articles/reviews/chemicus.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407092141/http://www.uhs-hints.com/articles/reviews/chemicus.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-04-07|title=UHS: Chemicus Review|date=2016-04-07|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nEblong likened the game's puzzle design to games such as ''Zork Grand Inquisitor'', ''Myst'', and ''Traitors Gate'' though noted that puzzles are completed by doing chemistry experiments rather than using spells, in-universe mythology or technological gizmos respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eblong.com/zarf/gamerev/chemicus.html|title=Review: Chemicus|website=www.eblong.com|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref> Metzomagic praised the game's graphics and musical score, and deemed it harder than its sister games [[Physicus]] and [[Bioscopia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metzomagic.com/showArticle.php?index=520|title=Chemicus Review by metzomagic.com|website=www.metzomagic.com|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>  Adventure Gamers thought the concept was admirable and was interesting in playing the sequel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adventuregamers.com:80/display.php?id=224|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041104191958/http://www.adventuregamers.com:80/display.php?id=224|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-11-04|title=Chemicus {{!}} Adventure Gamers|date=2004-11-04|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nAdventure Archiv thought the puzzles were fastidiously designed and that chemistry concepts were seamlessly integrated into the gameplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adventurearchiv.de/c/chemicusreviewen.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311070649/http://adventurearchiv.de/c/chemicusreviewen.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-11|title=Chemicus - Review english|date=2016-03-11|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> Gameboomers gave the game very high praise and was excited to try the other two games in the series,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gameboomers.com/reviews/Cc/Chemicusbysyd.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330111618/http://www.gameboomers.com/reviews/Cc/Chemicusbysyd.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-30|title=Chemicus review by syd|date=2016-03-30|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> and Mr Bills Adventure Land went away with a similar impression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mrbillsadventureland.com/reviews/c-d/chemicusR/chemicusR.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322024130/http://mrbillsadventureland.com/reviews/c-d/chemicusR/chemicusR.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-22|title=Chemicus Review - Mr. Bill's Adventureland|date=2016-03-22|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> Tap Repeatedly highly recommended the game as a chemistry learning tool for children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tap-repeatedly.com/Reviews/Chemicus/Chemicus.shtml|title=Four Fat Chicks -- Chemicus Review|website=www.tap-repeatedly.com|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> The AV Vault gave the game high praise, and noted that it managed to overcome the negative stigma around educational games as having \"terrible graphics, shallow stories, little replay value, and shoddy production values\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504114127/http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-05-04|title=AVault {{!}} PC {{!}} Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side Review|date=2006-05-04|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528021804/http://avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-05-28|title=AVault {{!}} PC {{!}} Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side Review|date=2006-05-28|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041121141525/http://www.avault.com:80/reviews/review_temp.asp?game=chemi&page=3|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-11-21|title=AVault {{!}} PC {{!}} Chemicus: Journey to the Other Side Review|date=2004-11-21|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nJust Adventure noted that while there was an overarching goal, there was no plot-related logical reasoning given for the player to complete each individual puzzle, beside the fact that they can't progress to different areas until they do.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://justadventure.com/2013-05-20-21-09-14/1099-chemicus|title=Throwback Thursday: Chemicus|last=Tait|first=Alexander|website=justadventure.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224101555/http://justadventure.com/2013-05-20-21-09-14/1099-chemicus|archive-date=2017-12-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> Similarly, Adventure Gamers thought the game could have been served better by having a juicier story that matched its intriguing world and puzzles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adventuregamers.com/articles/view/17597|title=Chemicus Review|website=Adventure Gamers|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> GameSpy offered a mixed review, but ultimately gave it a 1 star rating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/chemicus/5669p1.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908080721/http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/chemicus/5669p1.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-09-08|title=GameSpy: Chemicus - Page 1|date=2015-09-08|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref> Mystery Manor wrote that the addition of a narrator would have sharply improved the game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mysterymanor.net/reviewchemicus.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805000429/http://mysterymanor.net/reviewchemicus.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-08-05|title=Mystery Manor Chemicus Review|date=2016-08-05|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\nAdventureTreff thought that Chemicus 2 worked well as a sequel, despite its limited budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adventure-treff.de/artikel/tests/chemicus2.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050227220905/http://www.adventure-treff.de/artikel/tests/chemicus2.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-02-27|title=Adventure-Treff|date=2005-02-27|access-date=2017-12-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and nominations ===\n* 2002 Comenius medal (won)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediengewalt.de/spiele/beste-lernspiele-kinder-12-jahre.shtml|title=Beste Lernspiele f\u00fcr Kinder ab 12 Jahre (und andere Altersgruppen)|website=www.mediengewalt.de|access-date=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n* 2002 Giga Mouse - 6 mice (nominated)<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2002 Padi Seal of Approval<ref name=\":0\" />\n* 2002 6 Buffalo at Edut@in-Preis<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:Adventure games]]\n[[Category:Educational video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Festivemark", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added wikilinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemicus"}
{"title_page": "Commendatori", "text_new": "{{Infobox Television episode\n| title          = Commendatori\n| series         = [[The Sopranos]]\n| caption        = Tony talks with Annalisa, the ''de facto'' boss of a [[Camorra]] family.\n| season         = 2\n| episode        = 4\n| guests         = ''see below''\n| airdate        = February 6, 2000\n| length         = 52 minutes\n| editor         = \n| production     = 204\n| writer         = [[David Chase]]\n| director       = [[Tim Van Patten]]\n| photographer   = [[Phil Abraham]]\n| episode_list   = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 2)\n| image          = Sopranos ep204.jpg\n| image_size     = 300px\n| prev           = [[Toodle-Fucking-Oo]]\n| next           = [[Big Girls Don't Cry (The Sopranos)|Big Girls Don't Cry]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Commendatori'''\" is the seventeenth episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and the fourth of the show's second season. It was written by [[David Chase]] and directed by [[Tim Van Patten]], and originally aired on February 6, 2000.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]] *\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Pussy Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]]\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]]\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]] *\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]]\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]] *\n* [[David Proval]] as [[Richie Aprile]] *\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Livia Soprano]]*\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Sofia Milos]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Annalisa Zucca|Annalisa]]\n* [[Louis Lombardi|Louis Lombardi, Jr.]] as [[FBI on The Sopranos#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]]\n* [[Federico Castelluccio]] as [[Furio Giunta|Furio]]\n* [[Vittorio Duse]] as Zi Vittorio\n* [[Toni Kalem]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]\n* Mike Memphis as Jimmy Bones\n* [[Steven R. Schirripa]] as [[Bobby Baccalieri|Bobby \"Bacala\" Baccalieri]]\n* [[Sharon Angela]] as [[Rosalie Aprile]]\n* [[Jay Lynch]] as Partner\n* Emme Shaw as Nurse\n* [[Maureen Van Zandt]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gabriella Dante|Gabriella Dante]]\n* Ciro Maggio as Raffaelle\n* [[Danton Stone]] as Mr. Sontag\n* Melissa Weil as Mrs. Sontag\n* [[Jason Fuchs]] as Jr. Sontag\n* Jessica Peters as Sis Sontag\n* [[Gano Grills]] as Antonio\n* Anthony Alessandro as Waiter\n* Frank Caero as Host\n* Pina Cutolo as Mother\n* Raffaele Giulivo as Camillo\n* Antonio Lubrano as Nino\n* Rocco Malozzi as Don Vittorio's Assistant\n* Guido Palliggiano as Pino\n* Alida Tarallo as Prostitute\n* Alex Toma as Kid\n* Giuseppe Zeno as Tanno\n* Riccardo Zinna as Hotel Manager\n}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Tony Soprano|Tony]] goes to [[Naples]] to negotiate the [[smuggling]] of stolen American cars with a local [[Camorra]] family (distantly related to the Sopranos). His contact there is [[Furio Giunta]], a local mobster who speaks English. Tony learns that Don Vittorio, [[crime boss|boss]] of the  Naples family, is senile and that his son-in-law, Mauro Zucca, is serving a life sentence. He finds it very hard to accept that [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Annalisa Zucca|Annalisa]], who is Vittorio's daughter and Mauro's wife, is the effective head of the family.\n\nTony names his price for the cars, and also wants Furio transferred to America to work for him, and others later, as he requires. Annalisa negotiates hard, scoffs at his price, and tensions are further raised by their mutual sexual attraction. He lowers his price and they shake on it; he does not seem very pleased. Annalisa comes on to him; he tells her he wishes to keep their relationship professional. \n\nTony is accompanied to Naples by [[Paulie Walnuts|Paulie]] and [[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]]. The former goes on a mission to rediscover his roots, only to uncover a distaste for Naples; the latter is doped on [[heroin]] almost all the time.\n\nWhile Tony is away, [[Carmela Soprano|Carmela]], who is resentful that Tony has not taken her, has lunch with [[Rosalie Aprile]] and [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]. Angie shocks them by saying that when [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero|Pussy]] returned she wished he had died; he is indifferent to her, even now that she has a tumor; she has thought of suicide; and she  intends to divorce him. Carmela later visits her, urging her not to break the sacrament of marriage.  \n\nWhile with his [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] handler, [[FBI Informants on The Sopranos#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]], Pussy runs into [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Jimmy Bones|Jimmy Bones]], a Soprano associate. The pair concoct a cover story but Pussy is afraid he does not believe it. He goes to Jimmy's home and beats him to death with a [[ball-peen hammer]]. He then goes to his own home and gives a bunch of flowers to Angie, whose tumor, she has told him, is benign. She takes the flowers, pauses, then beats him with them.\n\nTony returns home. Carmela is upstairs, doing housework. He calls her. She pauses, then goes to greet him.\n\n==First appearances==\n* '''[[Furio Giunta]]''': a [[made man]] from the [[Camorra|Naples Mafia]] headed by Don Vittorio and Annalisa Zucca. Furio is sent to America after a successful trade between Tony and Annalisa.\n* This also marks the first recast appearances of '''[[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]''': Pussy's wife, and '''[[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gabriella Dante|Gabriella Dante]]''': Silvio's wife. Previously, both of these characters (although only implied as their wives) appeared very briefly in \"[[The Legend of Tennessee Moltisanti]]\", played by different actresses.\n\n==Deceased==\n* '''[[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Jimmy Bones|Jimmy Bones]]''': an [[Elvis Presley|Elvis]] [[Elvis impersonator|impersonator]] and Mafia associate, whom Big Pussy beat to death with a ball peen hammer, after Bones ran into Pussy talking with his FBI handler.\n\n==Title reference==\nThe episode's title is a plural of the [[Italian language]] word [[Commander (order)|commendatore]], which is an honorable title in Italian society. Tony and his crew are given this greeting in Italy, which Paulie hears and then tries to use throughout the episode.\n\n==Historical reference==\n* A Neapolitan passer-by complains to Paulie that NATO cut their cable car. This refers to the [[Cavalese cable car disaster (1998)]].\n\n==Production==\n* Series creator and head writer [[David Chase]] makes a cameo appearance in the episode as an Italian man, sitting at an Italian cafe with other men. When Paulie says \"commendatori\" to the table, Chase glances at him indifferently and then turns away.\n* [[Vittorio Duse]], who played Zi Vittorio, also played [[Don Tommasino]] in ''[[The Godfather Part III]]''.\n\n==Music==\n* The song \"[[Con te partir\u00f2]]\" by [[Andrea Bocelli]] is played three times throughout the episode.\n* When Tony is driven to Annalisa Zucca's villa the Napolitano song \"[[Core 'ngrato]]\" is played (without the vocals).\n* The song \"Marco Polo\" by [[Jovanotti]] is briefly played when Christopher is taking drugs the first time.\n* The song \"Certamente\" by the Italian rock band [[Madreblu]] is played when Christopher is taking drugs the second time.\n* The song played over the end credits is \"Piove\" by [[Jovanotti]].\n\n== Filming locations ==\nListed in order of first appearance:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sopranos-locations.com/season-2/episode-4/|title=The Sopranos location guide - Filming locations for|last=Ugoku|website=www.sopranos-locations.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* [[Lodi, New Jersey]]\n* [[Naples|Naples, Italy]]\n* [[Monte di Procida|Monte di Procida, Italy]]\n* [[Bacoli|Bacoli, Italy]]\n* [[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark International Airport]]\n* [[New Jersey Route 21|Route 21]] in [[Belleville, New Jersey]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/index.html#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/17-commendatori/index.html \"Commendatori\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705237}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/commendatori-26464}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Commendatori}}\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2000 American television episodes]]\n\n[[fr:Retour aux sources (Les Sopranos)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Television episode\n| title = Commendatori\n| series = [[The Sopranos]]\n| season = 2\n| episode = 4\n| guests= ''see below''\n| airdate = February 6, 2000\n| length = 52 minutes\n| production = 204\n| writer = [[David Chase]]\n| director = [[Tim Van Patten]]\n| photographer = [[Phil Abraham]]\n| episode_list = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 2)\n| image = Sopranos ep204.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| prev = [[Toodle-Fucking-Oo]]\n| next = [[Big Girls Don't Cry (The Sopranos)|Big Girls Don't Cry]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Commendatori'''\" is the seventeenth episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and the fourth of the show's second season. It was written by [[David Chase]] and directed by [[Tim Van Patten]], and originally aired on February 6, 2000.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]] *\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Pussy Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]]\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]]\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]] *\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]]\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]] *\n* [[David Proval]] as [[Richie Aprile]] *\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Livia Soprano]]*\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Sofia Milos]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Annalisa Zucca|Annalisa]]\n* [[Louis Lombardi|Louis Lombardi, Jr.]] as [[FBI on The Sopranos#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]]\n* [[Federico Castelluccio]] as [[Furio Giunta|Furio]]\n* [[Vittorio Duse]] as Zi Vittorio\n* [[Toni Kalem]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]\n* Mike Memphis as Jimmy Bones\n* [[Steven R. Schirripa]] as [[Bobby Baccalieri|Bobby \"Bacala\" Baccalieri]]\n* [[Sharon Angela]] as [[Rosalie Aprile]]\n* [[Jay Lynch]] as Partner\n* Emme Shaw as Nurse\n* [[Maureen Van Zandt]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gabriella Dante|Gabriella Dante]]\n* Ciro Maggio as Raffaelle\n* [[Danton Stone]] as Mr. Sontag\n* Melissa Weil as Mrs. Sontag\n* [[Jason Fuchs]] as Jr. Sontag\n* Jessica Peters as Sis Sontag\n* [[Gano Grills]] as Antonio\n* Anthony Alessandro as Waiter\n* Frank Caero as Host\n* Pina Cutolo as Mother\n* Raffaele Giulivo as Camillo\n* Antonio Lubrano as Nino\n* Rocco Malozzi as Don Vittorio's Assistant\n* Guido Palliggiano as Pino\n* Alida Tarallo as Prostitute\n* Alex Toma as Kid\n* Giuseppe Zeno as Tanno\n* Riccardo Zinna as Hotel Manager\n}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Tony Soprano|Tony]] goes to [[Naples]] to negotiate the [[smuggling]] of stolen American cars with a local [[Camorra]] family (distantly related to the Sopranos). His contact there is [[Furio Giunta]], a local mobster who speaks English. Tony learns that Don Vittorio, [[crime boss|boss]] of the  Naples family, is senile and that his son-in-law, Mauro Zucca, is serving a life sentence. He finds it very hard to accept that [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Annalisa Zucca|Annalisa]], who is Vittorio's daughter and Mauro's wife, is the effective head of the family.\n\nTony names his price for the cars, and also wants Furio transferred to America to work for him, and others later, as he requires. Annalisa negotiates hard, scoffs at his price, and tensions are further raised by their mutual sexual attraction. He lowers his price and they shake on it; he does not seem very pleased. Annalisa comes on to him; he tells her he wishes to keep their relationship professional. \n\nTony is accompanied to Naples by [[Paulie Walnuts|Paulie]] and [[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]]. The former goes on a mission to rediscover his roots, only to uncover a distaste for Naples; the latter is doped on [[heroin]] almost all the time.\n\nWhile Tony is away, [[Carmela Soprano|Carmela]], who is resentful that Tony has not taken her, has lunch with [[Rosalie Aprile]] and [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]. Angie shocks them by saying that when [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero|Pussy]] returned she wished he had died; he is indifferent to her, even now that she has a tumor; she has thought of suicide; and she  intends to divorce him. Carmela later visits her, urging her not to break the sacrament of marriage.  \n\nWhile with his [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] handler, [[FBI Informants on The Sopranos#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]], Pussy runs into [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Jimmy Bones|Jimmy Bones]], a Soprano associate. The pair concoct a cover story but Pussy is afraid he does not believe it. He goes to Jimmy's home and beats him to death with a [[ball-peen hammer]]. He then goes to his own home and gives a bunch of flowers to Angie, whose tumor, she has told him, is benign. She takes the flowers, pauses, then beats him with them.\n\nTony returns home. Carmela is upstairs, doing housework. He calls her. She pauses, then goes to greet him.\n\n==First appearances==\n* '''[[Furio Giunta]]''': a [[made man]] from the [[Camorra|Naples Mafia]] headed by Don Vittorio and Annalisa Zucca. Furio is sent to America after a successful trade between Tony and Annalisa.\n* This also marks the first recast appearances of '''[[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]''': Pussy's wife, and '''[[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gabriella Dante|Gabriella Dante]]''': Silvio's wife. Previously, both of these characters (although only implied as their wives) appeared very briefly in \"[[The Legend of Tennessee Moltisanti]]\", played by different actresses.\n\n==Deceased==\n* '''[[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Jimmy Bones|Jimmy Bones]]''': an [[Elvis Presley|Elvis]] [[Elvis impersonator|impersonator]] and Mafia associate, whom Big Pussy beat to death with a ball peen hammer, after Bones ran into Pussy talking with his FBI handler.\n\n==Title reference==\nThe episode's title is a plural of the [[Italian language]] word [[Commander (order)|commendatore]], which is an honorable title in Italian society. Tony and his crew are given this greeting in Italy, which Paulie hears and then tries to use throughout the episode.\n\n==Historical reference==\n* A Neapolitan passer-by complains to Paulie that NATO cut their cable car. This refers to the [[Cavalese cable car disaster (1998)]].\n\n==Production==\n* Series creator and head writer [[David Chase]] makes a cameo appearance in the episode as an Italian man, sitting at an Italian cafe with other men. When Paulie says \"commendatori\" to the table, Chase glances at him indifferently and then turns away.\n* [[Vittorio Duse]], who played Zi Vittorio, also played [[Don Tommasino]] in ''[[The Godfather Part III]]''.\n\n==Music==\n* The song \"[[Con te partir\u00f2]]\" by [[Andrea Bocelli]] is played three times throughout the episode.\n* When Tony is driven to Annalisa Zucca's villa the Napolitano song \"[[Core 'ngrato]]\" is played (without the vocals).\n* The song \"Marco Polo\" by [[Jovanotti]] is briefly played when Christopher is taking drugs the first time.\n* The song \"Certamente\" by the Italian rock band [[Madreblu]] is played when Christopher is taking drugs the second time.\n* The song played over the end credits is \"Piove\" by [[Jovanotti]].\n\n== Filming locations ==\nListed in order of first appearance:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sopranos-locations.com/season-2/episode-4/|title=The Sopranos location guide - Filming locations for|last=Ugoku|website=www.sopranos-locations.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* [[Lodi, New Jersey]]\n* [[Naples|Naples, Italy]]\n* [[Monte di Procida|Monte di Procida, Italy]]\n* [[Bacoli|Bacoli, Italy]]\n* [[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark International Airport]]\n* [[New Jersey Route 21|Route 21]] in [[Belleville, New Jersey]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/index.html#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/17-commendatori/index.html \"Commendatori\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705237}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/commendatori-26464}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Commendatori}}\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2000 American television episodes]]\n\n[[fr:Retour aux sources (Les Sopranos)]]\n", "name_user": "Fullmetal2887", "label": "safe", "comment": "image caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commendatori"}
{"title_page": "Violet (Peanuts)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Violet (''Peanuts'')}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name       = Violet Gray\n| series     = [[Peanuts]]\n| image      = [[File:Violet peanuts.jpg|frameless]]\n| caption    = \n| first      = February 7, 1951<br>''[[A Charlie Brown Christmas]]'' (television special)<br>''[[A Boy Named Charlie Brown]]'' (film)\n| gender     = Female\n| family      = Unnamed father\n| voice      = [[Sally Dryer]] (1963, 1965)<br />Karen Mendelson (1966)<br />Ann Altieri (1966-1969)<br />Linda Ercoli (1972-1975, 1976)<br />Lynn Mortensen (1974)<br />[[Linda Thompson (actress)|Linda Jenner]] (1974)<br />Roseline Rubens (1980)<br />[[Fergie (singer)|Stacy Ferguson]] (1985)<br />Deanna Tello (1992)<br />[[Ashley Edner]] (2000)<br>Kaitlyn Maggio (2003)<br />Jolean Wejbe (2006)<br>Taya Calicetto (2008-2009)<br />Blesst Bowden (2011)<br>[[Madisyn Shipman]] (2015)\n|color = #00FF00}}\n'''Violet Gray''' is a fictional character featured in the long-running syndicated [[Daily strip|daily]] and [[Sunday strip|Sunday]] [[comic strip]] ''[[Peanuts]]'', created by [[Charles M. Schulz]]. She was originally a major character, until she was eventually relegated to  background and cameo appearances.\n\nViolet is best known as a bit of a snob who likes bragging and, along with her friends [[Patty (Peanuts)|Patty]] (her best friend) and [[Lucy van Pelt|Lucy]] often teases and torments [[Charlie Brown]].\n\nIn addition to the comic strip, Violet has appeared alongside other ''Peanuts'' characters in numerous ''Peanuts'' television specials, cinematic movies, theatrical plays, and video games.\n\n== History ==\nViolet was first featured in the February 7, 1951 ''Peanuts'' strip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1951/02/07|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for February 07, 1951 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1951-02-07|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> From there on, Violet's character changed and developed until the 1960s, when she began to be seen less often than the other major characters, with her  appearances eventually reduced to  the background and cameos. Her last appearance in the strip, discounting the reruns, was on the November 27, 1997 ''Peanuts'' strip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1997/11/27|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for November 27, 1997 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1997-11-27|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== Appearance ==\nAs Violet's character developed over the years, her appearance changed as well. In the early strips, Violet has her shoulder-length dark hair kept in either pigtails, a bun, or, sometimes, a ponytail. Later on, Schulz dropped the braids and kept Violet's hair only in ponytails. Violet also wears front bangs and often wears dresses which are originally depicted as purple; later they were depicted as green, as well as black [[Mary Jane (shoe)|Mary Janes]] shoes. Violet wears her classic purple dress in ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]''.\n\n== Personality ==\nViolet is smart, popular, and somewhat of a [[snob]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Violet Gray {{!}} The Peanuts Movie {{!}} NOW PLAYING|url = http://www.peanutsmovie.com/characters/violet|website = Peanuts Movie {{!}} Official Site {{!}} NOW PLAYING!|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref> She makes her opinions known to everyone,<ref name=\":0\"/> and her haughtiness causes her to often torment other people,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Against Snoopy {{!}} Manhattan, New York, NY {{!}} News|url = http://www.nypress.com/against-snoopy/|website = www.nypress.com|accessdate = 2015-12-10}}</ref> whom she views as beneath her.\n\nCompared to the apparent [[middle-class]] upbringing of the other characters, Violet is supposedly of [[upper-class]] mentality, and she likes to brag about how her father possesses something her friends' fathers don't; it is also implied, however, that Violet's father is often absent from her life, which her peers use against her when she gets too obnoxious. For example, in a [[Father's Day]] strip, her boasts are quelled by Charlie Brown when he takes her to his dad's barber shop. After telling her about how his dad would always smile at him no matter how bad a workday he was having, a moved and humbled Violet walked away, but not before quietly wishing Charlie Brown a Happy Father's Day. In another example, a character named \"[[list of minor characters in Peanuts#555 95472|5]]\" fired back at her with \"''My'' dad goes to [[Parent-Teacher Association|PTA]] meetings!\" Charlie Brown once deflated her with the comeback: \"''My'' dad has a ''son''.\"<ref>Schulz, Charles M. [http://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1958/04/30 ''Peanuts'', 30 April 1958]</ref>\n\nIn the early strips, Violet often acted like a preschool-age Suzy Homemaker:<ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet the Gang|url = http://www.fivecentsplease.org/dpb/castlist.html|website = www.fivecentsplease.org|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref> frequently making mud pies, playing \"house,\" and being linked to romantic scenarios involving Shermy or  Charlie Brown. She also [[stamp collecting|collects stamps]] as a hobby. On some occasions, Violet was shown walking and keeping company with [[Lucy]].\n\nHer surname (Gray) was mentioned only once, on April 4, 1953.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1953/04/04|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for April 04, 1953 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1953-04-04|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\nViolet's personality was much more forceful and recognizable compared to the more generic early ''Peanuts'' characters like [[Patty (Peanuts)|Patty]] and [[Shermy]], which allowed her to survive slightly longer than those founding characters when a new wave of characters; [[Linus van Pelt|Linus]], [[Lucy van Pelt|Lucy]] and [[Schroeder (Peanuts)|Schroeder]]; were introduced (as an example, Violet has key roles in the TV specials ''[[A Charlie Brown Christmas]]'' and ''[[It's the Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown]]''). By the 1960s, however, Violet, too, was largely phased out with the introduction of the next wave of characters ([[Peppermint Patty]], [[Marcie (Peanuts)|Marcie]], [[Franklin (Peanuts)|Franklin]] and such). Schulz admitted in a 1988 interview that Violet's pure vindictiveness had made it difficult to give her [[punch line]]s. Speaking of her, Patty and Shermy: \"Some characters just don't seem to have enough personality to carry out ideas. They're just almost born straight men.\" Violet's use in the strip was eventually reduced to appearances in the background.\n\n== Relationship with other ''Peanuts ''characters ==\n\n=== Interactions with Charlie Brown ===\nViolet often teased [[Charlie Brown]] (often adding a series of Nyah's), who often makes comebacks. In an example of such, Violet once said to him, \"It simply goes without saying that you are an inferior human being.\"  His adroit reply to this was, \"If it goes without saying, why did ''you'' have to say it?\" She, along with Patty, do not invite him to their parties and enjoyed tormenting him with this. Charlie Brown is usually depressed by this, but sometimes he decides to turn the tables on the two girls.  For example:\n* ''November 23, 1951'':  When they mentioned excluding Charlie Brown from their party, he let it roll off his back saying he did not want to go to their \"dumb ol' party\" anyway. After he left, they pondered whether he meant it. Violet was convinced he did, so Patty suggested \"In that case, maybe we'd better invite him.\"\n* ''January 29, 1954'':  Charlie Brown replied to them saying if they did not like him they were better off not inviting him. Stunned to silence, the girls just walked away, with Charlie Brown smiling after them.\n* ''September 1, 1954'':  Charlie Brown uncharacteristically threatened to [[strafe]], then [[bomb]] their house if he was not invited, to which both girls replied, \"Okay, you're invited.\"\nIn early strips, Violet was linked to romantic scenarios involving Shermy or Charlie Brown. She also feels bad for Charlie Brown when he doesn't get a Valentine's Day card in ''Be My Valentine, Charlie Brown'', which hints that she cares about him deep down (this caring is inconsistent; when he doesn't receive a Christmas card in ''A Charlie Brown Christmas'', Violet responds in her usual mocking tone).\n\nAlthough Charlie Brown was the usual recipient of Violet's cruelty, he was not the only one.  One memorable Sunday strip of September 20, 1959, featured her hurling a series of virulent insults at Lucy (so venomous that Charlie Brown remarked that he was glad she wasn't yelling at ''him'', because he wouldn't have been able to take it), although ultimately Lucy won this battle by unleashing her own string of rapid-fire insults at Violet, causing Violet to walk away in shock.  Nor was Linus immune - one 1961 strip involved her and Patty mocking Linus for carrying a blanket (to which Linus responded by wrapping himself in his blanket and doing an impression of [[Count Dracula]], leading both girls to flee in terror). She and Patty insult 'Pig-Pen' in various comic strips and specials.\n\nViolet also is often prone to using physical violence against Charlie Brown in various comics. Some examples are:\n\n* April 1953, Violet Gray punches Charlie Brown on top of his head after he says, \"Ol' tattletale Gray, huh?\"\n*August 4, 1963, an angry Violet is seen chasing Charlie Brown, threatening to \"knock (his) block off\". Before she can throw a punch, Charlie Brown stops her and tries to reason with her, saying that there are better ways to solve problems than with violence. Unfazed, Violet ends up punching him in the middle of his speech, and in the final panel admits to Patty, \"I had to hit him quick. He was beginning to make sense!\"\n\n=== Interactions with Patty ===\nViolet and [[Patty (Peanuts)|Patty]] were friends, and would be seen walking about with each other, talking, and making mud pies. Despite this, not all their interactions were friendly, as on the 4th of April 1953, Patty calls Violet a 'tattletale' and storms off.\n<ref name=\"auto\"/><br />\n\n=== Interactions with Lucy van Pelt ===\nViolet and Lucy were also close friends, and would be seen together sometimes accompanied by Patty teasing Charlie Brown in the TV specials and films, or walking and talking with each other in them and the comics. Sometimes, they wouldn't bee to friendly towards each other as in one strip they were verbally fighting each other with insults, in which Lucy won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1959/09/20|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for September 20, 1959 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1959-09-20|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n=== Interactions with 'Pig-Pen' ===\nViolet always insults \"Pig-Pen\". For example, In a strip Violet attempts to shame 'Pig-Pen' by making him look in a mirror and she asks him, \"Aren't you ashamed?\" to which 'Pig-Pen' replies, \"On the contrary. I didn't think I looked this good.\" He also told Violet \"I forgot to rake my hair\" when she mocked him for having leaves on his head in a strip from November 16, 1984. In the Peanuts educational computer game, It's the Big Game, Charlie Brown, 'Pig-Pen' says that he is in love with Violet, due to her habit of making mud pies. However, this has never been stated in the comic strip, and therefore cannot be considered canon. But it has been hinted in the strip, for example, in one early strip, 'Pig-Pen' cleans up after seeing Violet hug Snoopy, complaining that no one ever hugged him this way, to impress her and possibly get a hug.\n<br />\n\n=== Interactions with Shermy ===\nShermy and Violet were seen talking a few times, for example in a strip where Charlie Brown is called to the office and comes back as a safety patrol member, they discuss it. In early strips, there was hint at a love rivalry between him, Charlie, and Violet. In the strip from January 9, 1952, Shermy claims that Violet is the most prettiest girl in the world. However, Charlie Brown rides on a sled with Snoopy running, yelling \"MUSH! MUSH!\" It is presumed Violet thought Shermy was lying, as in the next panel Shermy beats up Charlie Brown. However, in 1959, where Violet talks to Charlie Brown at the wall. She says that Shermy should be her friend, but he just isn't.\n<br />\n\n=== Interactions with Snoopy ===\nViolet has a good relationship with Snoopy and unlike Lucy, she is not afraid to be licked or kissed by him. In one strip, Lucy lashes out at the dog, but Violet comforts him and hugs him. Violet can frequently be seen cuddling with Snoopy, especially in the 50's.\n\n==Voiced by==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Sally Dryer]] (1963, 1965)\n*Karen Mendelson (1966)\n*Ann Altieri (1966-1969)\n*Linda Ercoli (1972-1975, 1976)\n*Lynn Mortensen (1974)\n*Linda Jenner (1974)\n*Roseline Rubens (1980)\n*[[Stacy Ferguson]] (1985)\n*Deanna Tello (1992)\n*[[Ashley Edner]] (2000)\n*Kaitlyn Maggio (2003)\n*Jolean Wejbe (2006)\n*Taya Calicetto (2008-2009)\n*Blesst Bowden (2011)\n*[[Madisyn Shipman]] (2015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1951/02/07 First appearance of Violet], ''Peanuts'', 7 February 1951\n\n{{wikiquote|Peanuts#Violet|Violet}}\n{{Peanuts}}\n\n[[Category:Peanuts characters]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1951]]\n[[Category:Child characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Female characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Fictional bullies]]\n[[Category:Child characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Violet (''Peanuts'')}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name       = Violet Gray\n| series     = [[Peanuts]]\n| image      = [[File:Violet peanuts.jpg|frameless]]\n| caption    = \n| first      = February 7, 1951<br>''[[A Charlie Brown Christmas]]'' (television special)<br>''[[A Boy Named Charlie Brown]]'' (film)\n| gender     = Female\n| family      = Unnamed father\n| voice      = [[Sally Dryer]] (1963, 1965)<br />Karen Mendelson (1966)<br />Ann Altieri (1966-1969)<br />Linda Ercoli (1972-1975, 1976)<br />Lynn Mortensen (1974)<br />[[Linda Thompson (actress)|Linda Jenner]] (1974)<br />Roseline Rubens (1980)<br />[[Fergie (singer)|Stacy Ferguson]] (1985)<br />Deanna Tello (1992)<br />[[Ashley Edner]] (2000)<br>Kaitlyn Maggio (2003)<br />Jolean Wejbe (2006)<br>Taya Calicetto (2008-2009)<br />Blesst Bowden (2011)<br>[[Madisyn Shipman]] (2015)\n|color = #00FF00}}\n'''Violet Gray''' is a fictional character featured in the long-running syndicated [[Daily strip|daily]] and [[Sunday strip|Sunday]] [[comic strip]] ''[[Peanuts]]'', created by [[Charles M. Schulz]]. She was originally a major character, until she was eventually relegated to  background and cameo appearances.\n\nViolet is best known as a bit of a snob who likes bragging and, along with her friends [[Patty (Peanuts)|Patty]] (her best friend) and [[Lucy van Pelt|Lucy]] often teases and torments [[Charlie Brown]].\n\nIn addition to the comic strip, Violet has appeared alongside other ''Peanuts'' characters in numerous ''Peanuts'' television specials, cinematic movies, theatrical plays, and video games.\n\n== History ==\nViolet was first featured in the February 7, 1951 ''Peanuts'' strip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1951/02/07|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for February 07, 1951 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1951-02-07|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> From there on, Violet's character changed and developed until the 1960s, when she began to be seen less often than the other major characters, with her  appearances eventually reduced to  the background and cameos. Her last appearance in the strip, discounting the reruns, was on the November 27, 1997 ''Peanuts'' strip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1997/11/27|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for November 27, 1997 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1997-11-27|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== Appearance ==\nAs Violet's character developed over the years, her appearance changed as well. In the early strips, Violet has her shoulder-length dark hair kept in either pigtails, a bun, or, sometimes, a ponytail. Later on, Schulz dropped the braids and kept Violet's hair only in ponytails. Violet also wears front bangs and often wears dresses which are originally depicted as purple; later they were depicted as green, as well as black [[Mary Jane (shoe)|Mary Janes]] shoes. Violet wears her classic purple dress in ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]''.\n\n== Personality ==\nViolet is smart, popular, and somewhat of a [[snob]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Violet Gray {{!}} The Peanuts Movie {{!}} NOW PLAYING|url = http://www.peanutsmovie.com/characters/violet|website = Peanuts Movie {{!}} Official Site {{!}} NOW PLAYING!|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref> She makes her opinions known to everyone,<ref name=\":0\"/> and her haughtiness causes her to often torment other people,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Against Snoopy {{!}} Manhattan, New York, NY {{!}} News|url = http://www.nypress.com/against-snoopy/|website = www.nypress.com|accessdate = 2015-12-10}}</ref> whom she views as beneath her.\n\nCompared to the apparent [[middle-class]] upbringing of the other characters, Violet is supposedly of [[upper-class]] mentality, and she likes to brag about how her father possesses something her friends' fathers don't; it is also implied, however, that Violet's father is often absent from her life, which her peers use against her when she gets too obnoxious. For example, in a [[Father's Day]] strip, her boasts are quelled by Charlie Brown when he takes her to his dad's barber shop. After telling her about how his dad would always smile at him no matter how bad a workday he was having, a moved and humbled Violet walked away, but not before quietly wishing Charlie Brown a Happy Father's Day. In another example, a character named \"[[list of minor characters in Peanuts#555 95472|5]]\" fired back at her with \"''My'' dad goes to [[Parent-Teacher Association|PTA]] meetings!\" Charlie Brown once deflated her with the comeback: \"''My'' dad has a ''son''.\"<ref>Schulz, Charles M. [http://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1958/04/30 ''Peanuts'', 30 April 1958]</ref>\n\nIn the early strips, Violet often acted like a preschool-age Suzy Homemaker:<ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet the Gang|url = http://www.fivecentsplease.org/dpb/castlist.html|website = www.fivecentsplease.org|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref> frequently making mud pies, playing \"house,\" and being linked to romantic scenarios involving Shermy or  Charlie Brown. She also [[stamp collecting|collects stamps]] as a hobby. On some occasions, Violet was shown walking and keeping company with [[Lucy]].\n\nHer surname (Gray) was mentioned only once, on April 4, 1953.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1953/04/04|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for April 04, 1953 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1953-04-04|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\nViolet's personality was much more forceful and recognizable compared to the more generic early ''Peanuts'' characters like [[Patty (Peanuts)|Patty]] and [[Shermy]], which allowed her to survive slightly longer than those founding characters when a new wave of characters; [[Linus van Pelt|Linus]], [[Lucy van Pelt|Lucy]] and [[Schroeder (Peanuts)|Schroeder]]; were introduced (as an example, Violet has key roles in the TV specials ''[[A Charlie Brown Christmas]]'' and ''[[It's the Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown]]''). By the 1960s, however, Violet, too, was largely phased out with the introduction of the next wave of characters ([[Peppermint Patty]], [[Marcie (Peanuts)|Marcie]], [[Franklin (Peanuts)|Franklin]] and such). Schulz admitted in a 1988 interview that Violet's pure vindictiveness had made it difficult to give her [[punch line]]s. Speaking of her, Patty and Shermy: \"Some characters just don't seem to have enough personality to carry out ideas. They're just almost born straight men.\" Violet's use in the strip was eventually reduced to appearances in the background.\n\n== Relationship with other ''Peanuts ''characters ==\n\n=== Interactions with Charlie Brown ===\nViolet often teased [[Charlie Brown]] (often adding a series of Nyah's), who often makes comebacks. In an example of such, Violet once said to him, \"It simply goes without saying that you are an inferior human being.\"  His adroit reply to this was, \"If it goes without saying, why did ''you'' have to say it?\" She, along with Patty, do not invite him to their parties and enjoyed tormenting him with this. Charlie Brown is usually depressed by this, but sometimes he decides to turn the tables on the two girls.  For example:\n* ''November 23, 1951'':  When they mentioned excluding Charlie Brown from their party, he let it roll off his back saying he did not want to go to their \"dumb ol' party\" anyway. After he left, they pondered whether he meant it. Violet was convinced he did, so Patty suggested \"In that case, maybe we'd better invite him.\"\n* ''January 29, 1954'':  Charlie Brown replied to them saying if they did not like him they were better off not inviting him. Stunned to silence, the girls just walked away, with Charlie Brown smiling after them.\n* ''September 1, 1954'':  Charlie Brown uncharacteristically threatened to [[strafe]], then [[bomb]] their house if he was not invited, to which both girls replied, \"Okay, you're invited.\"\nIn early strips, Violet was linked to romantic scenarios involving Shermy or Charlie Brown. She also feels bad for Charlie Brown when he doesn't get a Valentine's Day card in ''Be My Valentine, Charlie Brown'', which hints that she cares about him deep down (this caring is inconsistent; when he doesn't receive a Christmas card in ''A Charlie Brown Christmas'', Violet responds in her usual mocking tone).\n\nAlthough Charlie Brown was the usual recipient of Violet's cruelty, he was not the only one.  One memorable Sunday strip of September 20, 1959, featured her hurling a series of virulent insults at Lucy (so venomous that Charlie Brown remarked that he was glad she wasn't yelling at ''him'', because he wouldn't have been able to take it), although ultimately Lucy won this battle by unleashing her own string of rapid-fire insults at Violet, causing Violet to walk away in shock.  Nor was Linus immune - one 1961 strip involved her and Patty mocking Linus for carrying a blanket (to which Linus responded by wrapping himself in his blanket and doing an impression of [[Count Dracula]], leading both girls to flee in terror). and her and Patty insult 'Pig-Pen' in various comic strips and specials.\n\nViolet also is often prone to using physical violence against Charlie Brown in various comics. Some examples are:\n\n* April 1953, Violet Gray punches Charlie Brown on top of his head after he says, \"Ol' tattletale Gray, huh?\"\n*August 4, 1963, an angry Violet is seen chasing Charlie Brown, threatening to \"knock (his) block off\". Before she can throw a punch, Charlie Brown stops her and tries to reason with her, saying that there are better ways to solve problems than with violence. Unfazed, Violet ends up punching him in the middle of his speech, and in the final panel admits to Patty, \"I had to hit him quick. He was beginning to make sense!\"\n\n=== Interactions with Patty ===\nViolet and [[Patty (Peanuts)|Patty]] were friends, and would be seen walking about with each other, talking, and making mud pies. Despite this, not all their interactions were friendly, as on the 4th of April 1953, Patty calls Violet a 'tattletale' and storms off.\n<ref name=\"auto\"/><br />\n\n=== Interactions with Lucy van Pelt ===\nViolet and Lucy were also close friends, and would be seen together sometimes accompanied by Patty teasing Charlie Brown in the TV specials and films, or walking and talking with each other in them and the comics. Sometimes, they wouldn't bee to friendly towards each other as in one strip they were verbally fighting each other with insults, in which Lucy won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1959/09/20|title=Peanuts by Charles Schulz for September 20, 1959 {{!}} GoComics.com|last=Schulz|first=Charles|date=1959-09-20|website=GoComics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n=== Interactions with 'Pig-Pen' ===\nViolet always insults \"Pig-Pen\". For example, In a strip Violet attempts to shame 'Pig-Pen' by making him look in a mirror and she asks him, \"Aren't you ashamed?\" to which 'Pig-Pen' replies, \"On the contrary. I didn't think I looked this good.\" He also told Violet \"I forgot to rake my hair\" when she mocked him for having leaves on his head in a strip from November 16, 1984. In the Peanuts educational computer game, It's the Big Game, Charlie Brown, 'Pig-Pen' says that he is in love with Violet, due to her habit of making mud pies. However, this has never been stated in the comic strip, and therefore cannot be considered canon. But it has been hinted in the strip, for example, in one early strip, 'Pig-Pen' cleans up after seeing Violet hug Snoopy, complaining that no one ever hugged him this way, to impress her and possibly get a hug.\n<br />\n\n=== Interactions with Shermy ===\nShermy and Violet were seen talking a few times, for example in a strip where Charlie Brown is called to the office and comes back as a safety patrol member, they discuss it. In early strips, there was hint at a love rivalry between him, Charlie, and Violet. In the strip from January 9, 1952, Shermy claims that Violet is the most prettiest girl in the world. However, Charlie Brown rides on a sled with Snoopy running, yelling \"MUSH! MUSH!\" It is presumed Violet thought Shermy was lying, as in the next panel Shermy beats up Charlie Brown. However, in 1959, where Violet talks to Charlie Brown at the wall. She says that Shermy should be her friend, but he just isn't.\n<br />\n\n=== Interactions with Snoopy ===\nViolet has a good relationship with Snoopy and unlike Lucy, she is not afraid to be licked or kissed by him. In one strip, Lucy lashes out at the dog, but Violet comforts him and hugs him. Violet can frequently be seen cuddling with Snoopy, especially in the 50's.\n\n==Voiced by==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Sally Dryer]] (1963, 1965)\n*Karen Mendelson (1966)\n*Ann Altieri (1966-1969)\n*Linda Ercoli (1972-1975, 1976)\n*Lynn Mortensen (1974)\n*Linda Jenner (1974)\n*Roseline Rubens (1980)\n*[[Stacy Ferguson]] (1985)\n*Deanna Tello (1992)\n*[[Ashley Edner]] (2000)\n*Kaitlyn Maggio (2003)\n*Jolean Wejbe (2006)\n*Taya Calicetto (2008-2009)\n*Blesst Bowden (2011)\n*[[Madisyn Shipman]] (2015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gocomics.com/peanuts/1951/02/07 First appearance of Violet], ''Peanuts'', 7 February 1951\n\n{{wikiquote|Peanuts#Violet|Violet}}\n{{Peanuts}}\n\n[[Category:Peanuts characters]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1951]]\n[[Category:Child characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Female characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Fictional bullies]]\n[[Category:Child characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "Many Conflicts of Interest", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violet_(Peanuts)"}
{"title_page": "Schitt's Creek", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Schitt's Creek\n| image                    = File:Schitt's_Creek_logo.png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Sitcom]]\n| creator                  = {{unbulleted list|[[Eugene Levy]]|[[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]]}}\n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| starring                 = {{unbulleted list|Eugene Levy|[[Catherine O'Hara]]|Dan Levy|[[Annie Murphy]]|[[Emily Hampshire]]|[[Jennifer Robertson|Jenn Robertson]]|[[Chris Elliott]]|[[Tim Rozon]]|[[Sarah Levy]]|[[Dustin Milligan]]|[[Noah Reid]]|[[Karen Robinson]]|[[John Hemphill (actor)|John Hemphill]]}}\n| composer                 = \n| country                  = Canada\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 6\n| num_episodes             = 79<!--Only use the number of episodes aired -->\n| list_episodes            = List of Schitt's Creek episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{unbulleted list|Eugene Levy|Daniel Levy|Fred Levy|Andrew Barnsley|Ben Feigin|Kevin White|David West Read}}\n| producer                 = {{unbulleted list|[[Colin Brunton]]|Kosta Orfanidis}}\n| location                 = \n| runtime                  = 22\u201348 minutes\n| company                  = Not a Real Company Productions\n| distributor              = [[ITV Studios#ITV Studios Global Entertainment|ITV Studios Global Entertainment]]<br>[[Debmar-Mercury]]/[[Lionsgate Television]] (U.S. only)\n| network                  = [[CBC Television]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|1|13}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| website                  = http://www.cbc.ca/schittscreek/\n| website_title            = CBC Television's ''Schitt'$ Creek''\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n}}\n'''''Schitt's Creek''''' (stylized as '''''Schitt{{sup|$}} Creek''''') is a Canadian television [[sitcom]] created by [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan]] and [[Eugene Levy]] that premiered on [[CBC Television]] on January 13, 2015.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/eugene-levy-and-catherine-o-hara-are-up-schitt-s-creek-1.2806231 |title=Eugene Levy and Catherine O'Hara are up Schitt's Creek |date=October 21, 2014 |website=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> The series is produced by Not a Real Company Productions.<ref name=\"playback\">{{cite magazine |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2014/02/11/sctv-alums-levy-and-ohara-to-star-in-cbc-comedy/ |title=SCTV alums Levy and O'Hara to star in CBC comedy |last=Cummins |first=Julianna |date=February 11, 2014 |magazine=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |accessdate=January 14, 2015}}</ref>  The series's sixth and final season began airing on January 7, 2020; it consists of 14 episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/danjlevy/status/1108745156059123713|title=To Our Dear Fans...pic.twitter.com/FIXjD3gbzA|first=Dan|last=Levy|date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> The final episode will be simulcasted in the US on [[Comedy Central]] and [[Logo TV|Logo]] on April 7, 2020.<ref>https://deadline.com/2020/03/pop-pulls-plug-florida-girls-best-intentions-flack-questions-scripted-future-1202874777/</ref> The series follows the trials and tribulations of the formerly wealthy Rose family who are forced to relocate to Schitt's Creek, a small town they once purchased as a joke.<ref name=\"weisblott\" /> Now living in two adjoining motel rooms, Johnny ([[Eugene Levy]]) and Moira ([[Catherine O'Hara]]) Rose\u2014along with their adult children, David ([[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Dan Levy]]) and Alexis ([[Annie Murphy]])\u2014must adjust to a life without money and with each other.<ref name=\"weisblott\" />\n\nThe series was conceived by Dan Levy, who wondered how the wealthy families frequently depicted on American [[reality television]] would react if they were stripped of all their money.<ref name=\"out-2015\" /> Levy further developed the series with his father, actor Eugene, before pitching the series to several networks in Canada and the United States. The series was first sold to [[CBC Television]] in Canada and later to Pop TV in the United States.<ref name=\":14\" /> \n\nThe series has won various accolades, including two [[ACTRA Award|ACTRA Awards]] and 18 [[Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/awards-and-festivals/film-awards/room-hyena-road-lead-early-canadian-screen-award-categories/article29204639/|title=Room, Schitt's Creek dominate Canadian Screen Awards|access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/winners-the-18th-annual-actra-awards-in-toronto-1028928909|title=Winners: The 18th Annual ACTRA Awards in Toronto {{!}} Markets Insider|last=|first=|date=2020-02-22|website=markets.businessinsider.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> It is the first Canadian comedy series to be nominated for a [[Critics' Choice Television Award]] for Best Comedy Series and the first to win an [[MTV Movie & TV Award]], winning [[MTV Movie Award for Best Comedic Performance|Best Comedic Performance]] for Dan Levy in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|first=Debra |last=Yeo |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2018/12/13/schitts-creek-becomes-first-canadian-comedy-series-nominated-for-a-critics-choice-award.html |title=Schitt's Creek becomes first Canadian comedy series nominated for a Critics' Choice Award |work=The Star |date=December 13, 2018 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> It is also the first program from Pop TV to receive [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/schitts-creek-breaks-first-emmy-nominations-pop-tv-1224564|title=Pop TV President Celebrates 'Schitt's Creek' Emmy Breakthrough: \"Holy S***!\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref> Along with a standard finale episode, there will be an hour-long \"documentary\" showing behind-the-scenes footage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1130556/some-good-news-schitt-s-creek-is-saying-goodbye-with-a-behind-the-scenes-documentary-special|title=Schitt's Creek Will End With Hour-Long Documentary Special|date=2020-03-12|website=E! Online|accessdate=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Synopsis ==\nThe wealthy Rose family\u2014[[Video rental shop|video store]] magnate Johnny ([[Eugene Levy]]), his wife and former soap opera actress Moira ([[Catherine O'Hara]]), and their adult children David and Alexis ([[Dan Levy (TV personality)|Dan Levy]] and [[Annie Murphy (actress)|Annie Murphy]])\u2014lose their fortune after being defrauded by their business manager. They are forced to rebuild their lives with their sole remaining asset: a small town named Schitt's Creek, which Johnny had bought for David as a joke birthday gift in 1991.<ref name=weisblott>[http://o.canada.com/entertainment/cbc-schitts-creek/ \"SCTV stars Levy and O\u2019Hara reunite for a forthcoming CBC sitcom called Schitt\u2019s Creek\"]. [[canada.com]], February 10, 2014.</ref> The Roses relocate to Schitt's Creek, moving into two adjacent rooms in a run-down motel. As the family adjusts to their new lives, their well-to-do attitudes come into conflict with the more provincial residents of Schitt's Creek, including mayor Roland Schitt ([[Chris Elliott]]), his wife Jocelyn ([[Jennifer Robertson|Jenn Robertson]]), and the motel's manager Stevie Budd ([[Emily Hampshire]]).<ref name=weisblott />\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Schitt's Creek episodes}}\n{{:List of Schitt's Creek episodes}}\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* [[Eugene Levy]] as [[Johnny Rose]]\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]] as [[Moira Rose]]\n* [[Dan Levy (Canadian actor)|Daniel Levy]] as [[David Rose (Schitt's Creek)|David Rose]]\n* [[Annie Murphy]] as [[Alexis Rose]]\n* [[Emily Hampshire]] as Stevie Budd, the motel clerk, and later, motel owner\n* [[Jennifer Robertson|Jenn Robertson]] as Jocelyn Schitt, the mayor's wife\n* [[Chris Elliott]] as Roland Schitt, the mayor\n* [[Tim Rozon]] as Mutt Schitt (seasons 1\u20133; guest season 4), Roland and Jocelyn's son and Alexis's former love interest\n* [[Dustin Milligan]] as Ted Mullens, the town's [[Veterinary physician|veterinarian]], and Alexis's boyfriend\n* [[Sarah Levy]] as Twyla Sands, the caf\u00e9's waitress.\n* [[John Hemphill (actor)|John Hemphill]] as Robert \"Bob\" Currie, proprietor of Bob's Garage and a member of the town council\n* [[Karen Robinson]] as Veronica \"Ronnie\" Lee, a member of the town council\n* [[Noah Reid]] as Patrick Brewer (season 4\u2013present; recurring season 3), David's business partner and fianc\u00e9\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Rizwan Manji]] as Ray Butani, the only real estate agent in town and a former member of the town council\n* Marilyn Bellfontaine as Gwen Currie, Bob's wife.\n* [[Robin Duke]] as Wendy Kurtz (season 2 & 5), dress shop owner and David's former employer\n* [[Jasmin Geljo]] as Ivan (seasons 2 & 3), a baker who supplies the motel with pastries\n* [[Ennis Esmer]] as Emir Kaplan (season 5), a travel blogger and Stevie's former love interest\n*[[Steve Lund]] as Jake (seasons 2\u20134, 6), Stevie and David's ex who dates them at the same time.\n\n== Development and production ==\n\n=== Conception ===\nDaniel Levy came up with the idea for the show while watching reality television. He told [[Out (magazine)|Out.com]], \"I had been watching some reality TV at the time and was concentrating on what would happen if one of these wealthy families would lose everything. Would the Kardashians still be the Kardashians without their money?\"<ref name=\"out-2015\">{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Michael |title=Dan Levy Discusses Schitt's Creek, His Eyebrows & Being a Sex Object |url=https://www.out.com/television/2015/3/09/dan-levy-discusses-schitts-creek-his-eyebrows-being-sex-object |website=Out.com |accessdate=October 15, 2018|date=March 9, 2015 }}</ref> He turned to his father, Eugene Levy, to help develop the show; Eugene Levy came up with series title. Daniel Levy decided to make the location of Schitt's Creek vague, but in August 2018 said that it is in Canada.<ref name=\"mentalfloss-15facts\">{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/526195/15-funny-facts-about-schitts-creek|title=15 Funny Facts About Schitt's Creek|last1=McCarthy|first1=Erin|website=mentalfloss.com|accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"buzzfeed-shittscreeklocation\">{{cite web |last1=Mack |first1=David |title=We Finally Know Where \"Schitt's Creek\" Is Set |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/davidmack/schitts-creek-us-canada-setting-location-dan-levy |website=www.buzzfeed.com |publisher=Buzzfeed |accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Levys initially pitched the show to several networks in Canada and the United States. Cable networks [[HBO]] and [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] passed on the series, while broadcast networks [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (United States) and the [[CBC Television|CBC]] (Canada) expressed interest. The show was first sold to the CBC, but the Levys decided against ABC as its U.S. broadcaster due to the network's alleged history of creative interference. ''Schitt's Creek'' eventually found a U.S. home on Pop TV after striking a deal with network head Brad Schwartz, who had previously hired Daniel on [[MTV (Canada)|MTV Canada]].<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nDuring the early stages of development, various networks suggested the title of the show be changed to make it sound less profane. The Levys resisted these suggestions and argued \"Schitt\" was a legitimate last name. To prove their point, they brought pages copied from a phone book to the CBC showing listings for individuals with the \"Schitt\" surname. The CBC agreed and allowed the Levys to keep the original title.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/01/12/how_eugene_levy_convinced_cbc_to_name_his_show_schitts_creek.html|title=How Eugene Levy convinced CBC to name his show 'Schitt's Creek'|last=Wong|first=Tony|date=January 12, 2015|newspaper=Toronto Star|accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> The name has still faced censorship issues during promotional tours in the United States, with many networks shortening the title or providing extra disclaimers before using it on-air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2015/02/schitt-s-creek-sitcom-polite-reviewers-find-themselves-without-a-paddle.html|title=The Winding Circumlocutions of Schitt's Creek Reviews|last=Friedman|first=Nancy|date=February 16, 2015|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=July 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDaniel Levy initially envisioned the series ending with season five, but agreed to a sixth season after receiving a two-year renewal following the show's fourth season.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/dan-levy-schitts-creek-final-season-interview|title=Dan Levy Cried Over the End of 'Schitt's Creek' (and You Will Too)|last=Meslow|first=Scott|date=November 13, 2019|website=GQ|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Catherine O'Hara]] was the series creators' first choice for the role of eccentric family matriarch, Moira Rose. O'Hara had previously worked with Eugene Levy on [[Second City Television|SCTV]], ''[[Best in Show (film)|Best in Show]]'', ''[[A Mighty Wind]]'', ''[[Waiting for Guffman]]'', and ''[[For Your Consideration (film)|For Your Consideration]]''. She initially turned down Levy's offer to star in ''Schitt's Creek'', citing \"laziness\" and an aversion to long-term projects. Levy reached out to another unnamed actress, but continued to court O'Hara for the role. O'Hara eventually agreed to participate in the presentation pilot with no obligation to continue in the role after ''Schitt's Creek'' was ordered to series. After the show was picked up by the CBC, O'Hara agreed to continue in the role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jarettwieselman/eugene-levy-and-catherine-ohara-look-back-on-their-40-year-f|title=Eugene Levy And Catherine O'Hara Look Back On Their 40-Year Friendship|last=Wieselman|first=Jarett|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n[[Annie Murphy]] was offered the role of spoiled socialite Alexis Rose after actress [[Abby Elliott]], who had portrayed the character in the presentation pilot, was unable to continue when the show was picked up to series, due to scheduling conflicts.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/04/schitts-creek-annie-murphy-interview.html|title=Annie Murphy Can't Help But Bring Her Schitt's Creek Vocal Fry Home With Her|last=Ivie|first=Devon|date=2018-04-11|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Murphy first auditioned for the role in Los Angeles, where Daniel Levy said she stood out due to her \"wonderfully natural likability.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mIHWFOGshKE&t=396s|title=\"Schitt's Creek\": Eugene Levy, Catherine O'Hara, Annie Murphy and Daniel Levy with Ophira Eisenberg|last=92nd Y|date=2016-03-15|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Eugene Levy was unsure of Murphy's casting because she did not possess the blonde hair he had pictured for the role of Alexis. Murphy was subsequently called back for a second audition for a different role, sarcastic motel clerk Stevie Budd. After this audition, Daniel Levy convinced his father that Murphy could dye her hair blonde, and she was officially cast as Alexis Rose.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n[[Emily Hampshire]] was cast as the deadpan motel clerk, Stevie Budd, after auditioning for the role in Los Angeles. She originally requested to submit a taped audition on account of her nerves and recurring hives breakouts. Hampshire ultimately agreed to audition in person, but states she has no recollection of the experience. According to Daniel Levy, who was present for the process, Hampshire gave a \"great\" audition, then proceeded to lift her shirt over her head to hide and slowly rocked back and forth. Levy later told Hampshire he found her audition \"charming,\" and she was offered the part of Stevie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/node/47164875|title=Emily Hampshire on Her Schitt's Creek Audition, Breaking Character, and the Show's Legacy|last=Messina|first=Victoria|date=2020-02-05|website=POPSUGAR Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n[[Noah Reid]] was offered the role of David's business partner and love interest, Patrick Brewer, in season three. Daniel Levy was socially familiar with Reid and invited him to audition on the suggestion of [[Stacey Farber]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FPcVdN9aKjg|title=Ep #1 DAN LEVY {{!}} Good For You Podcast with Whitney Cummings|last=Cummings|first=Whitney|date=2019-11-05|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Reid had never watched the show before he auditioned and was unsure how long the character would be a part of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myentertainmentworld.ca/2018/03/noah-reid/|title=Nominee Interview Series: Noah Reid|last=Bedard|first=Kelly|date=2018-03-18|website=My Entertainment World|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secondcity.com/explosively-endearing-things-uncovered-at-schitts-creek-up-close-personal|title=Explosively Endearing Things Uncovered at 'Schitt's Creek: Up Close & Personal'|website=The Second City|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> Daniel Levy was not present during the audition process and could not chemistry test with Reid before he was cast.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOther cast regulars [[Chris Elliott]] and [[Sarah Levy]] were given the roles of Roland Schitt and Twyla Sands, respectively, without auditioning. Elliot says when Eugene Levy offered him the role of the titular town mayor, he thought, \"Why would I say no?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sKEyd5StanA|title=Chris Elliott Announces a 6th Season of Schitt's Creek|last=King|first=Larry|date=2018-12-14|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Sarah Levy, the real-life daughter of Eugene Levy and real-life sister of Daniel Levy, was asked to be a part of the show before it was fully developed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tv-eh.com/2020/01/03/sarah-levy-says-goodbye-to-schitts-creek/|title=Sarah Levy says goodbye to Schitt's Creek {{!}} TV, eh?|website=www.tv-eh.com|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> She says she was glad not to be cast as Alexis, as being out of her real-life family's orbit on the show allowed her to \"do [her] own thing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flare.com/celebrity/schitts-creek-sarah-levy-interview/|title=Sarah Levy Interview: On Working With Eugene and Dan on Schitt's Creek|website=www.flare.com|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Production  ===\n''Schitt's Creek'' is produced by Not a Real Company Productions in association with CBC and Pop TV.<ref name=\"playback\" /> Pop TV joined the production team in season two after the series' first season was produced solely in association with CBC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/voices/in-contention/streaming-us-global-tv-shows-awards-1203309274/|title=For Awards, the Divide Between U.S., Global TV Shows Is Blurred Thanks to Streaming|last=Schneider|first=Michael|date=August 22, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> [[ITV Studios|ITV Studios Global Entertainment]] also partnered with the CBC and Pop to distribute the show worldwide.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/schitts-creek-netflix-pop-success-story.html|title=The Unlikely Rise of Schitt's Creek|last=Adalain|first=Josef|date=January 16, 2019|website=www.vulture.com|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 6, 2019}}</ref>  Eugene Levy, Dan Levy, Fred Levy, Andrew Barnsley, and Ben Feigin have served as [[executive producer]]s throughout the show's entirety.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\" /> Other executive producers have included writers Kevin White (seasons two and three) and David West Read (seasons five and six).<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://press.poptv.com/releases/schittscreekseasonfive|title=Pop Press|website=press.poptv.com|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://press.poptv.com/releases/Schitts_Creek_Season_6_announcement_date|title=Pop Press|website=press.poptv.com|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> Eugene Levy served as [[showrunner]] alongside co-creator and son, Dan Levy, during the series' first season; Dan Levy took over as sole showrunner beginning in season two.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/dan-levy-schitts-creek-profile.html|title=Dan Levy Made Schitt's Creek With His Dad. But It's His Weird Little Baby.|last=Jung|first=E. Alex|date=2019-01-16|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\n''Schitt's Creek'' was part of a \"new direction\" in programming taken by both CBC and Pop TV during the 2014-15 television season.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2014/05/29/cbc-upfront-hellos-goodbyes-and-new-directions-2/|title=CBC upfront: hellos, goodbyes and 'new directions'|last=May 29|first=Katie Bailey|last2=2014|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> Premiering alongside 12 new primetime shows on CBC, the series represented one of the network's efforts to produce more \"serialized, scripted\" content, as well as more \"cable-like\" shows.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/mediacentre/press-release/cbc-reveals-lineup-for-2014-15-television-season-featuring-returning-hits-a|title=CBC REVEALS LINEUP FOR 2014-15 TELEVISION SEASON, FEATURING RETURNING HITS AND 12 NEW PRIMETIME TITLES|last=|first=|date=2014-05-29|work=CBC|access-date=|url-status=live|type=Press Release}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tv-eh.com/2015/01/19/cbc-not-dead-yet/|title=CBC: Not dead yet {{!}} TV, eh?|last=Wild|first=Diane|date=2015-01-19|website=www.tv-eh.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> The series was also the first original, scripted program to air on Pop TV after its re-branding in January 2015. Formerly known as [[History of Pop (American TV channel)|TV Guide Network]], Pop TV was re-branded as a channel \"filled with optimism, passion, funny and excitement.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://press.poptv.com/releases/schittscreek|title=Pop Press|website=press.poptv.com|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming style and locations ===\n''Schitt's Creek'' is filmed using a [[Single-camera setup|single camera set-up]] with no live audience or [[laugh track]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2014/04/09/schitts-creek-starts-production-adds-cast/|title=Schitt's Creek starts production, adds cast|date=April 9, 2014|first=Katie|last=Bailey|website=playbackonline.ca|access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref> The interior scenes for the first two seasons were filmed at [[Pinewood Toronto Studios]] in Toronto,<ref name=\":0\" /> while interior scenes for season 3 were shot at Dufferin Gate Studios in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dufferingate.com/|title=Dufferin Gate Studios \u2013 Toronto|website=dufferingate.com|access-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref> Interior scenes were also filmed at Revival Studios  in Toronto for an unknown number of seasons.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=http://locationmanagers.org/up-schitts-creek/|title=Up Schitt\u2019s Creek|date=2020-03-20|website=Location Managers Guild International|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The remainder of the series is filmed on location in [[Goodwood, Ontario]], the [[Regional Municipality of Durham]] of the [[Greater Toronto Area]], and [[Mono, Ontario]], where the motel scenes are filmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orangeville.com/news-story/4596347-hockley-sets-scene-for-cbc-comedy-starring-eugene-levy/ |title=Hockley sets scene for CBC comedy starring Eugene Levy |last=Halliday |first=Chris |date=June 24, 2014 |work=Orangeville Banner |accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Goodwood was one of 30 towns scouted for the fictional location of Schitt's Creek before production of the series began in 2014.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/comedy/103-surprising-facts-easter-eggs-and-trivia-that-every-schitt-s-creek-fan-should-know-1.5471387|title=103 surprising facts, easter eggs and trivia that every Schitt's Creek fan should know|last=|first=|date=2020-03-02|website=CBC Comedy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>  \n\nThe series has filmed in several additional locations during its run. The opening shot of the first season features [[Lisa Vanderpump]]\u2019s former [[Beverly Park]] estate as the facade of the Rose family estate. Interior shots of the Rose family estate were filmed on location in a [[Sistine Chapel]]-inspired mansion in Toronto.<ref name=\":13\" /> Main Street [[Stouffville, Ontario]] served as a filming location for an unspecified number of scenes in the series' first two seasons. Scenes involving the fictional retailer, Blouse Barn, in seasons two and three were filmed on location on Main Street in [[Unionville, Ontario]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkregion.com/news-story/5659946-schitt-s-creek-fans-get-up-close-with-tv-stars-in-stouffville/|title=Schitt's Creek fans get up close with TV stars in Stouffville|last=Mason|first=Jim|date=June 3, 2015|website=YorkRegion.com|language=en-CA|access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.narcity.com/life/this-tiny-town-just-outside-of-toronto-is-the-secret-filming-destination-for-your-favourite-tv-shows-and-movies|title=This Tiny Town Just Outside Of Toronto Is The Secret Filming Destination For Your Favourite TV Shows & Movies|website=narcity.com|language=en-CA|access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref> In the season four episode \"[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|The Jazzaguy]],\" scenes involving a spa retreat were filmed on location at Monte Carlo Inn in [[Vaughan|Vaughan, Ontario]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MonteCarloInns/posts/1570016823052544|title=Monte Carlo Inns|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Exterior filming also took place at [[Rattlesnake Point (Canada)|Rattlesnake Point]] in [[Milton, Ontario]] for season five's \"[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|The Hike]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehalton.com/whatson-story/9268492-spoiler-alert-episode-of-schitt-s-creek-filmed-in-milton/|title=SPOILER ALERT: Episode of Schitt's Creek filmed in Milton|last=Rosella|first=Louie|date=April 4, 2019|website=InsideHalton.com|language=en-CA|access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref> In season six's \"[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|Smoke Signals]],\" the series shot on location at Graydon Hall Manor, a wedding venue in Toronto.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-ca/schitts-creek-season-six-recap-episode-1|title=Schitt's Creek Season 6, Episode 1 Recap: The Roses Are Back On Their Bull-Schitt|last=Newman-Bremang|first=Kathleen|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref> The series also filmed in [[Bay Adelaide Centre|Bay-Adelaide Centre]] and [[Toronto-Dominion Centre]] for the season six episode \"[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|The Pitch]].\"<ref name=\":15\" /> Additional filming for several season six episodes took place at a local motel in [[Brantford|Brantford, Ontario]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brantfordexpositor.ca/news/local-news/fans-watch-schitts-creek-filming-in-city|title=Fans watch Schitt's Creek filming in city|last=Ruby|first=Michelle|date=2019-06-17|website=Brantford Expositor|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> \n\n=== Music ===\n''Schitt\u2019s Creek'' features several musical performances from its main and supporting characters. The majority of these performances feature the town singing group, the Jazzagals. The Jazzagals' main members are Moira Rose, Jocelyn Schitt, Twyla Sands, Ronnie Lee, and Gwen Currie. Throughout the series, they have covered \u201c[[It's Raining Men]];\u201d \u201c[[Baby I'm Yours (Barbara Lewis song)|Baby, I'm Yours]];\u201d \"Takin\u2019 It Home;\" \"[[Silent Night]];\" and \"[[Islands in the Stream (song)|Islands in the Stream]].\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/article/schitts-creek-moira-rose-career.html|title=Everything We Know About Moira Rose's Showbiz Career on Schitt's Creek|last=Bierly|first=Mandi|date=April 10, 2019|website=www.vulture.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn season one's \"[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|Carl's Funeral]],\" Moira sings an a cappella version of \"[[Danny Boy]]\" as a distraction when Johnny's eulogy goes awry. She performs the same song a second time later in the episode.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn season four\u2019s \u201c[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|Asbestos Fest]],\u201d David and Moira perform a duet known as \u201cThe Number.\u201d This medley of holiday songs was regularly performed at the annual Rose Christmas party and included \u201c[[O Come, All Ye Faithful|Oh Come All Ye Faithful]],\u201d \u201c[[Deck the Halls]],\u201d and \u201c[[God Rest You Merry, Gentlemen|God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen]].\u201d The song was arranged by Moira's portrayer, Catherine O\u2019Hara.<ref>{{Citation|last=Schitt's Creek|title=Schitt's Creek - Behind the Episode: \"Asbestos Fest\"|date=February 8, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M-s9KhmuI5w&list=PLyIx941Qzz0HSwMGOzzYo7tzBFB9m9FOZ&index=3|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn season four's \u201c[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|Open Mic]],\u201d Patrick sings an acoustic cover of [[Tina Turner|Tina Turner's]] \u201c[[The Best (song)|The Best]]\u201d as a declaration of love to David. The song was arranged and performed by Patrick's portrayer, Noah Reid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/schitts-creek-season-4-episode-6-open-mic-dan-levy-tina-turner-the-best-serenade/|title=How Schitt's Creek Created the Most Romantic Scene on TV {{!}} TV Guide|date=February 28, 2018|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> After airing on ''Schitt\u2019s Creek'', Reid's version of the song was released on [[Spotify]] and [[iTunes]], where it reached #1 on the Canadian charts. All proceeds from the single were donated to the Ontario charity, LGBT Youth Line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canadianbeats.ca/2018/03/03/noah-reid-hits-1-on-itunes-charts-with-his-cover-of-simply-the-best/|title=Noah Reid hits #1 on iTunes charts with his cover of \"Simply The Best\" {{!}} Canadian Beats Media|last=Bickell|first=Dutch|language=en-US|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn season five's \u201c[[List of Schitt's Creek episodes|The Hospies]],\u201d Alexis auditions for a community theatre production by singing \u201cA Little Bit Alexis,\u201d the theme song from her defunct reality show of the same name. Alexis\u2019 portrayer, Annie Murphy, who wrote and performed the song for the show, says she drew inspiration from the pop songs of [[Paris Hilton]] and [[Lindsay Lohan|Lindsay Lohan]]. Menno Versteeg and Nixon Boyd of the Canadian band, [[Hollerado]], also helped produce the song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/television/8500491/schitts-creek-annie-murphy-interview-a-little-bit-alexis-song|title='Schitt's Creek': How Annie Murphy Channeled Britney Spears and Paris Hilton for 'A Little Bit Alexis' Banger|website=Billboard|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> \u201cA Little Bit Alexis\u201d was released as a single on Spotify and iTunes, where it reached #28 on the Canadian charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itunescharts.net/can/artists/music/annie-murphy/songs/a-little-bit-alexis-from-schitts-creek/|title=iTunesCharts.net: 'A Little Bit Alexis (From Schitt's Creek)' by Annie Murphy (Canadian Songs iTunes Chart)|website=www.itunescharts.net|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn season five's \u201c[[Life Is a Cabaret (Schitt's Creek)|Life Is a Cabaret]]\u201d, several main characters perform \u201c[[Willkommen]]\u201d from the musical ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]''. Stevie also sings a second number, \u201c[[Maybe This Time (song)|Maybe This Time]],\u201d as her ''Cabaret'' character, [[Sally Bowles]], in the same episode.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/04/schitts-creek-recap-season-5-episode-14-life-is-a-cabaret.html|title=Schitt's Creek Season Finale Recap: Curtain Call|last=Fremont|first=Maggie|date=April 10, 2019|website=www.vulture.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref> Both songs were performed in front of a live audience during filming.<ref>{{Citation|last=Schitt's Creek|title=Schitt's Creek - Behind the Episode: \"Life is a Cabaret\"|date=April 11, 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uQ_LvUjfe38&list=PLyIx941Qzz0GsSdpCY6So-W7pBu_n9mMw&index=5|access-date=July 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\n\n=== Original broadcast ===\n''Schitt's Creek'' has been co-broadcast in Canada and the United States since 2015. The show initially premiered on the CBC in Canada on Tuesday, January 13, 2015 at 9:00 pm/9:30 pm NT with back-to-back episodes.<ref name=\":2\" /> It made its debut in the United States on Pop TV on Wednesday, February 11, 2015 at 10:00 pm ET/PT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/eugene-levy-schitts-creek-series-pop-856574|title=Pop Picks Up Eugene Levy Comedy 'Schitt's Creek' As First Original Scripted Series|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=October 21, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Jue|first=Teresa|date=November 17, 2014|title=TVGN rebrand Pop announces lineup for 2015, premieres clip from 'Schitt's Creek'|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/11/17/tvgn-rebrand-pop-announces-lineup-for-2015-premieres-clip-from-schitts-creek|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 11, 2015}}</ref> Pop moved the series to an 8:00 pm ET/PT time slot with an encore broadcast at 11:00 pm ET/PT for seasons two through four; it returned to its original 10:00 pm ET/PT time slot for season five.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://press.poptv.com/releases/scseason2premieredate|title=Pop Press|last=|first=|date=October 22, 2015|website=press.poptv.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://press.poptv.com/releases/SchittsCreekS3|title=Pop Press|last=|first=|date=November 14, 2016|website=press.poptv.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://press.poptv.com/releases/schittscreek_letsgetphysical|title=Pop Press|last=|first=|date=November 12, 2017|website=press.poptv.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"tvline-season5-sept\">{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2018/09/24/schitts-creek-season-5-premiere-date-pop/|title=Schitt's Creek Season 5 Gets Premiere Date, Larger Episode Order|last1=Ianucci|first1=Rebecca|website=TVline.com|accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref> The series maintained staggered premieres throughout its first five seasons, with new episodes debuting in Canada before being broadcast in the United States. The series' sixth and final season debuted simultaneously in Canada and the United States on January 7, 2020.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/schitts-creek-gets-premiere-date-for-sixth-final-season-on-pop-tv-1202736543/|title='Schitt's Creek' Gets Premiere Date For Sixth & Final Season On Pop TV|last=Bennett|first=Anita|date=September 17, 2019|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Other broadcasts ===\nAs of 2019, the series also airs on [[4Music]] in the UK; [[Viacom 18]] in India; [[Fox (Asian TV channel)|Fox Asia]]; and [[ABC Comedy]] in Australia.<ref name=\":5\">https://www.tvguide.co.uk/mobile/channellisting.asp?ch=506#425701113</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/pre-sales-for-noughts-and-crosses-lead-scripted-deals-for-itv-studios-at-mipcom-1203369354/|title=Pre-Sales for 'Noughts and Crosses' Lead Scripted Deals for ITV Studios at Mipcom|last=Dams|first=Tim|date=October 14, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 25, 2019}}</ref> It was previously broadcast in New Zealand by [[TV2 (New Zealand)|TV2]] and [[TVNZ]] on Demand, in Australia by [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]] and its [[ABC iview|iView]] streaming service, and on [[Comedy Central (Indian TV channel)|Comedy Central]] in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/shows/schitts-creek|title=Schitt's Creek|website=www.tvnz.co.nz|access-date=October 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/comedycentralin/status/1085763645550874625|title=Schitt's Creek is back better than ever! Catch the Season 5 Premiere tonight only on Comedy Central India. @SchittsCreek {{!}} TONIGHT {{!}} 10 PMpic.twitter.com/4XQPRBh923|date=January 16, 2019|website=@comedycentralin|language=en|access-date=October 27, 2019}}</ref> The five seasons appear, though not always together, on different streaming television services worldwide. Netflix carries the full series for viewers in the U.S., UK, Ireland, Japan, South Africa, and Australia. IMDb TV, a streaming service available through [[IMDb]], and CW Seed, a streaming service for the American [[The CW|CW network]], also carry the first five seasons for viewers in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/schitts-creek-cw-seed-acquires-off-season-streaming-rights-pop-tv-comedy-tca-1202660736/|title='Schitt's Creek': CW Seed Acquires Off-Season Streaming Rights To Pop TV Comedy \u2013 TCA|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=August 4, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/IMDbTV/status/1241528257230462976|title=PSA: Schitt's Creek seasons 1-5 are free on IMDb TV! No subscription required #IMDbinge https://amzn.to/2WFzGjw\u00a0pic.twitter.com/m1RscZpK7N|last=TV|first=IMDb|date=2020-03-21|website=@IMDbTV|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \n\nIn December 2019, fans on social media accused UK television station 4Music of censoring some scenes featuring \"intimate dialogue\" and kissing between the show's LGBTQ characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/television/2019/12/23/dan-levy-calling-out-network-censoring-schitts-creek|title=Dan Levy Is Calling Out a Network for Censoring 'Schitt's Creek'|last=Street|first=Mikelle|date=2019-12-23|website=www.out.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref> Co-creator and star, Dan Levy, also addressed the alleged censorship on social media calling it \"highly disturbing\" and \"dangerous.\" 4Music responded to the allegations of censored kissing with an apology, stating that the removal of a kiss between two male characters was \"human error\" and would be restored for future broadcasts. The station did not specifically respond to the allegations of censored dialogue between LGBTQ characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/television/2019/12/23/dan-levy-calls-out-uk-channel-editing-gay-schitts-creek-scenes|title=Dan Levy Calls Out UK Channel for Editing Gay 'Schitt's Creek' Scenes|last=Linnell|first=Christine|date=2019-12-23|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Syndication ===\nIn 2018, [[Debmar-Mercury]], a division of [[Lionsgate]], acquired the U.S. syndication rights to ''Schitt's Creek.'' The series is scheduled to debut in syndication on [[Fox Television Stations]] throughout the U.S. during the Fall 2020 television season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/schitts-creek-fox-television-stations-acquired-syndication-deal-h-lionsgates-debmar-mercury-1202750883/|title=Fox Television Stations Acquire Comedy 'Schitt's Creek'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=October 3, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nThe first season of ''Schitt's Creek'' received generally positive reviews. It holds an approval rating of 61% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 23 reviews, with an average rating of 6.38/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"The title is one of the best jokes of ''Schitt's Creek'', but performances from Eugene Levy and Catherine O'Hara give the writing a comedic boost.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/schitts-creek/s01/ |title=Schitt's Creek : Season 1 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=April 19, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the first season has a score of 64 out of 100, based on 11 critics, indicating \"generally favourable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/schitts-creek/ |title=Schitt's Creek : Season 1 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=April 19, 2018}}</ref> Vinay Menon of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' wrote that the show \"is one of the best CBC comedies in years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2015/01/19/schitts-creek-is-off-to-a-dazzling-start-menon.html|title=Schitt's Creek is off to a dazzling start: Menon \u2013 Toronto Star|publisher=|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref> After being picked up by [[Pop (U.S. TV network)|Pop]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' described the show as \"very funny, beautifully played, [and] sometimes touching,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-schitts-canadian-creek-review-eugene-levy-20150211-column.html|title=Canadian 'Creek' overflows with good humor|last=Lloyd|first=Robert|website=latimes.com|access-date=November 28, 2016}}</ref> although Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called ''Schitt's Creek'' \"drab and underwritten.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/11/arts/television/review-in-schitts-creek-a-spoiled-little-rich-family-starts-over.html|title=Review: In 'Schitt's Creek,' a Spoiled Little Rich Family Starts Over|first=Mike|last=Hale|date=February 10, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=March 27, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent seasons of ''Schitt's Creek'' have been more positively received, with the show growing in popularity after debuting on [[Netflix]] in January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/dan-levy-schitts-creek-profile.html|title=Dan Levy Made Schitt's Creek With His Dad. But It's His Weird Little Baby.|first=E. Alex|last=Jung|date=January 16, 2019|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Vulture.com}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, seasons 2, 4 and 5 have approval ratings of 100%, with season 4's consensus reading, \"The comedic real estate value rises for ''Schitt's Creek'' in its fourth year, the series gradually maturing into appointment viewing with a big, beating heart beneath its absurdity.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/schitts_creek/s02|title=Schitt's Creek : Season 2|website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/schitts_creek/s04 |title=Schitt's Creek : Season 4 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/schitts_creek/s05|title=Schitt's Creek : Season 5|website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> Bridget Read of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' wrote that while the series \"started off with typical fish out of water scenarios,\" it has \"fully come into its own, with a whole cast of ''[[Twin Peaks]]''-meets-[[Christopher Guest|Christopher-Guest]]-universe characters that are as equally endearing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/schitts-creek-watch-dysfunctional-family-comedy-fun|title=Schitt's Creek Is Like Succession\u2014But Fun|first=Bridget|last=Read|date=September 5, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Vogue.com}}</ref> In ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]'', Maggie Fremont wrote that \"the show takes a few episodes to get into its groove, but once it does, you\u2019ll never want to leave.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/04/schitts-creek-why-arent-you-watching.html|title=Why Aren't You Watching Schitt's Creek Yet?|first=Maggie|last=Fremont|date=April 9, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Vulture.com}}</ref> The series has placed on annual best-of lists published by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/g25439321/best-tv-episodes-2018/|title=The 10 Best Episodes of Television in 2018|first=Justin|last=Kirkland|date=December 10, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Esquire.com}}</ref> ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/gallery/best-tv-series-2018|title=The Best TV Shows of 2018|first=Christopher|last=Rosa|date=December 23, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Glamour.com}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/2018-in-review/my-not-top-ten-television-list-2018-edition|title=My Not-Top-Ten Television List: The Best TV Shows of 2018|first=Emily|last=Nussbaum|date=December 11, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Esquire.com}}</ref> and ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/best-tv-episodes-2018-1203051440/|title=The Top 20 TV Episodes of 2018|first=Daniel|last=D'Addario|date=December 13, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=January 16, 2019|via=Variety.com}}</ref> In 2019, the series was named \"The Best Show on TV Right Now\" by ''[[TV Guide]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/schitts-creek-best-show-on-tv/|title=Schitt's Creek Is the Best Show on TV Right Now|last=Gennis|first=Sadie|date=September 9, 2019|website=TV Guide|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe series has also been praised for its portrayal of a [[pansexual]] character, played by Dan Levy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.flare.com/celebrity/dan-levy-on-playing-pansexual-on-schitts-creek/|title=Dan Levy Talks Playing Pansexual on Schitt's Creek \u2013 Flare|date=March 31, 2015|work=Flare|access-date=December 8, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/11/pansexual-schitts-creek-character-wont-become-caricature.html|title=Dan Levy Won't Make Pansexual&nbsp;Schitt's Creek&nbsp;Character a 'Caricature'|last=Ferber|first=Taylor|work=Vulture|access-date=December 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref> as well as for how David's sexuality is simply accepted by the other characters with no expressions of [[homophobia]] in the storyline.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/dan-levy-explains-why-schitts-creek-has-no-homophobia.html|title=Dan Levy Explains Why Homophobia Will Never Infiltrate Schitt's Creek|last=Ivie|first=Devon|work=Vulture|date=November 18, 2018|access-date=January 16, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Schitt's Creek}}\nIn 2015, ''Schitt's Creek'''s first season received two [[Directors Guild of Canada]] awards from three nominations. At the [[4th Canadian Screen Awards|2016 ceremony]], season 1 received nine [[Canadian Screen Awards]] from 16 nominations. ''Schitt's Creek''<nowiki/>'s second season received 13 nominations at the 5th [[Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.academy.ca/category/2017-film-nominees/|title=2017 Film Nominees \u2013 Academy.ca|website=Academy.ca|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, the series received nominations from the US-based [[MTV Movie & TV Awards]] and the [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]. In 2019, the series was nominated for 15 [[Canadian Screen Awards]] and four [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, winning the award for Best Performance by an Actress in a Continuing Leading Comedic Role ([[Catherine O'Hara]]) and Best Comedy Program or Series at the Canadian Screen Awards. The same year, the series won [[Dorian Awards]] for TV Comedy of the Year and Unsung TV Show of the Year from the Society of LGBTQ Entertainment Critics.<ref>[https://galeca.org/dorian-awards/ \"Dorian Awards\". GALECA: The Society of LGBTQ Entertainment Critics: Home of The Dorian Awards.] Retrieved October 11, 2019</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.hellomagazine.com/film/02019040150689/anne-with-an-e-schitt-s-creek-win-canadian-screen-awards|title=Anne with an E, Schitt's Creek win big at 2019 Canadian Screen Awards|website=ca.hellomagazine.com|language=English|access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Other media==\n\n=== Home media ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Release !! Format !! Region !! Discs !! Distributor || Ref(s)\n|-\n| <center>''Schitt's Creek: The Complete First Season''</center> || <center>August 11, 20