[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles County High School for the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American actors of Jamaican descent]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records artists]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Records artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=February 2020}}\n{{About-distinguish2|the American actor and singer|[[Cordon bleu (dish)|Cordon Bleu]]}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Corbin Bleu\n| image            = Corbin Bleu (Headshot).jpg\n| caption          = Bleu at the [[Broadway theatre]], ''[[Godspell]]'' in New York City, April 11, 2012\n| birth_name       = Corbin Bleu Reivers\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Sasha Clements]]|2016}}\n| children         = \n| alias            =\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1989|2|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| residence        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater       = [[Los Angeles County High School for the Arts]]<br />[[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School|Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts]]\n| occupation       = {{ flatlist| \n* [[Actor]]\n* [[Model (person)|model]]\n* [[dancer]]\n* [[film producer]]\n* [[singer-songwriter]]}}\n| parents          = [[David Reivers]] {{small|(father)}}<br />Martha Callari {{small|(mother)}}\n| relatives        = Joseph Callari {{small|(great-uncle)}}\n| home_town        = \n| known_for        = ''[[Flight 29 Down]]''<br />''[[High School Musical (franchise)|High School Musical]]''<br />''[[Jump In!]]''<br />''[[One Life to Live]]''<br />''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 17)|Dancing with the Stars]]''<br />''[[Holiday Inn (musical)|Holiday Inn, The New Irving Berlin Musical]]''<br />''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]''\n| years_active     = 1996\u2013present\n| module           = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n*[[Dance music|dance]]\n*[[pop rock]]<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vocals]]\n* [[piano]]}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n* [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n* [[Sh-K-Boom Records|Ghostlight]]}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Vanessa Hudgens]]\n* [[Lucas Grabeel]]\n* [[Zac Efron]]\n* [[Miley Cyrus]]\n* David Reivers\n* [[Karina Smirnoff]]}}\n| URL              = {{URL|www.instagram.com/corbinbleu/|www.corbinbleu.com}}\n}}}}\n\n'''Corbin Bleu Reivers''' ({{IPAc-en|b|l|u\u02d0}}; born February 21, 1989),<ref>{{cite web |title=Corbin Bleu |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/film-and-television-biographies/corbin-bleu |website=Encyclopedia.com |accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=yochell says |url=http://www.relatemag.com/corbin-bleu/ |title=Actor Corbin Bleu in Relatemag.com |publisher=Relatemag.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> known professionally as '''Corbin Bleu''', is an American actor, model, dancer, film producer and singer-songwriter. He performed in the ''[[High School Musical (franchise)|High School Musical]]'' film series (2006\u20132008). Songs from the films also charted worldwide, with the song \"[[I Don't Dance (High School Musical song)|I Don't Dance]]\" peaking inside the Top 70 of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. During this time, he also starred in the [[List of Disney Channel original films|Disney Channel Original Movie]] ''[[Jump In!]]'' (2007). His first lead role was in the film ''[[Catch That Kid]]'' (2004). He has since appeared in the [[Discovery Kids]] drama series ''[[Flight 29 Down]]'' (2005\u20132007), as well as the film ''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]'' (2015). He competed in the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 17)|17th season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', partnered with professional dancer [[Karina Smirnoff]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://extratv.com/2013/09/03/dancing-with-the-stars-meet-the-new-dwts-season-17-cast/| title=Meet the New 'DWTS' Season 17 Cast! | work=[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] | publisher= | date =June 5, 2012 | accessdate=June 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHe has also pursued a music career, and released his debut album ''[[Another Side (Corbin Bleu album)|Another Side]]'' on May 1, 2007, which included the single \"[[Push It to the Limit (Corbin Bleu song)|Push It to the Limit]].\" The album debuted at number thirty-six on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 18,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/pop-songs#/search/Corbin%20Bleu |title=Pop Songs |publisher= Billboard.com |work=Corbin Bleu album}}</ref> Bleu released his second album, ''[[Speed of Light (album)|Speed of Light]]'', on March 10, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.aol.com/album/artist/corbin-bleu/531382 |title=Corbin Bleu albums and CDs in the Corbin Bleu discography |publisher=Music.aol.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130032818/http://music.aol.com/album/artist/corbin-bleu/531382 |archive-date=January 30, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He returned to television, starring in the short-lived [[Ashton Kutcher]]-produced [[The CW Television Network|CW]] series, ''[[The Beautiful Life: TBL]]'' (2009), and the movie ''[[Free Style (film)|Free Style]]'' (2009). He has appeared in the films ''[[The Little Engine That Could (2011 film)|The Little Engine That Could]]'' (2011), ''[[Scary or Die]]'' (2012), ''[[Nurse 3D]]'' (2013), ''[[Sugar (2013 film)|Sugar]]'' (2013), ''[[The Monkey's Paw (2013 film)|The Monkey's Paw]]'' (2013), and ''[[Walk. Ride. Rodeo.]]'' (2019).\n\nIn 2010, Bleu played Usnavi in the Broadway company of ''[[In the Heights]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadway.com/shows/in-the-heights/buzz/152504/corbin-bleu-extends-again-at-in-the-heights-seth-stewart-returning-for-four-weeks/| title=Corbin Bleu Extends Again at in the Heights; Seth Stewart Returning for Four Weeks | work=[[In the Heights]].com | publisher= | date =May 25, 2010 | accessdate=May 25, 2010 }}</ref> In 2012, he returned to Broadway in the revival of ''[[Godspell]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/162264/broadways-godspell-starring-corbin-bleu-eyes-closing-date/| title=Broadway's Godspell, Starring Corbin Bleu, Eyes Closing Date | work=extratv.com | publisher= | date = | accessdate=September 4, 2013 }}</ref> In 2013, he was cast as [[Jeffrey King]] in the short-lived online revival of the [[daytime soap]] ''[[One Life to Live]]''. In 2016, Bleu played Ted Hanover in the Broadway company of ''[[Holiday Inn (musical)|Holiday Inn, The New Irving Berlin Musical]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/186241/lets-say-it-with-ink-holiday-inn-starring-corbin-bleu-bryce-pinkham-lora-lee-gayer-opens-on-broadway/| title=Let's Say It With Ink! Holiday Inn, Starring Corbin Bleu, Bryce Pinkham & Lora Lee Gayer, Opens on Broadway | work=[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] | publisher= | date= | accessdate=October 6, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"playbill2016\">{{cite news|last1=Clement|first1=Olivia|title=See Who's Heading to the Holiday Inn on Broadway|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/see-who-39-s-heading-to-the-holiday-inn-on-broadway|accessdate=June 2, 2016|work=Playbill|date=May 27, 2016}}</ref> He subsequently signed a recording contract with [[Sh-K-Boom Records|Ghostlight Records]],{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''Sh-K-Boom Records''.}} to distribute his ''Holiday Inn'' soundtrack music, released in 2017.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\">{{cite web|first=Olivia |last=Clement |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/holiday-inn-announces-cast-album|title=Holiday Inn Announces Cast Album |date=December 22, 2016|publisher=playbill.com|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> In 2019, he returned to played Bill Calhoun/Lucentio in the Broadway company of ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/news-features/corbin-bleu-and-more-join-the-cast-of-kiss-me-kate-on-broadway| title=Corbin Bleu and more join the cast of Kiss Me, Kate! on Broadway | work=newyorktheatreguide.com | publisher= | date = | accessdate=October 11, 2018 }}</ref> He returned to subsequently signed a recording contract with [[Sh-K-Boom Records|Ghostlight Records]], to distribute his ''Kiss Me, Kate'' soundtrack music, released in June 7, 2019.<ref name=\"ReferenceK\">{{cite web|first=Andy|last=Lefkowitz|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/195539/kiss-me-kate-revival-to-receive-original-cast-album/|title=Kiss Me, Kate Revival to Receive Original Cast Album |date=|publisher=[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].com|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBleu was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], the son of Martha (n\u00e9e Callari) and [[David Reivers]] (born 1958), an actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2007/08/18/Music/Teen_star_is_true_to_.shtml |title=Music: Teen star is true to Corbin BleuMusic: Teen star is true to Corbin Bleu |publisher=Sptimes.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/ent/tv/articles/0105bleu0105.html |title=Elementary school musical star Corbin Bleu is in concert and back on TV with new movie 'High School Musical' star Corbin Bleu is in concert |publisher=Azcentral.com |date=January 5, 2007 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref><ref name=oci>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Corbin Bleu-High Energy Italian-American|pages=|publisher=Unico|date=July 2009|url=http://www.unico.org/pdf/ComUNICOjuly09.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722001229/http://www.unico.org/pdf/ComUNICOjuly09.pdf|archivedate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> His mother is [[Italian Americans|Italian American]] and his father is [[Jamaican Americans|Jamaican American]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2009/10/11/2009-10-11_celebrity_pop_quiz_corbin_bleu.html |title=Corbin Bleu is best known for two things: his mop of curly hair and living the 'tween dream as Zac Efron' |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=October 11, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2011 |location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20090913/ent/ent5.html |title=Jamaica Gleaner News \u2013 The lion and the mouse join forces \u2013 Tuff Gong signs distribution deal with Disney \u2013 Entertainment \u2013 Sunday &#124; September 13, 2009 |publisher=Jamaica-gleaner.com |date=September 13, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6A0jM2fBg?url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20090913/ent/ent5.html |archivedate=August 18, 2012  }}</ref> He has three sisters: Jag, Phoenix, and Hunter. As a child, Bleu studied dance for several years, focusing on [[ballet]] and [[Jazz dance|jazz]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/Corbin_Bleu/1185512#fullBio |work=Hollywood.com |title=Hot Corbin Bleu celebrity pictures and premiere and red carpet photos}}</ref> His great-uncle is actor Joseph Callari,<ref>{{cite web|last=Bleu |first=Corbin |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BfAEG4Sh2XC/  |title=Since I've only got 3 more days left of the keto diet \ud83d\ude12 I'll just stare at this pic of my uncle Joseph Callari treating us to some pizza for dessert a few months back. |publisher=[[Instagram]].com |date= |accessdate=February 10, 2018}}</ref> who won [[Indie Fest|IndieFEST FIlm awards]] of Excellence for Best Actor, with his performance in ''The Julie Stories''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thejuliestories.com/ |publisher=The Julie Stories.com |title=The Julie Stories|date= |accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts.jpg|thumb|right|Bleu attended [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School|Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts]] in New York City]]\n\nBleu appeared in television commercials starting at the age of two, for products such as [[Life cereal]], [[Bounty (brand)|Bounty]], [[Hasbro]], and [[Nabisco]]. He began taking jazz and ballet classes, usually being the only boy in the class. By the age of four he was a model with the [[Ford Modeling Agency]] in New York. He appeared in print ads for stores such as [[Macy's]], [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]], [[Target (magazine)|Target]], and [[Toys R Us]], and appeared in fashion spreads in ''[[Child (magazine)|Child]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'', and ''American Baby'' magazines, as well as having his image on toys and game packaging.\n\nAt age six, Corbin appeared in his first professional theater production off Broadway, at [[The Town Hall (New York City)|The Town Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/articleamp.cfm?colid=76351&ModPagespeed=off |title=Corbin Bleu Joins Cuccioli, Kudish, Block and More for Broadway Cabaret Festival, 10/16 \u2013 10/18 |publisher=Broadway.com |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref> This three-concert series, created, written, and hosted by Scott Siegel, took place over one weekend and included a tribute to [[David Merrick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/venue/view-more?venue=00000150-aacd-d8be-af71-ffef18860005 |title=View More Playbill |publisher=playbill.com |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Corbin Bleu played an abandoned homeless mute in the play ''Tiny Tim is Dead''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Broadway-HIGH-SCHOOL-MUSICAL-Alum-Corbin-Bleu-Ties-the-Knot-20160725 |title=Broadway & HIGH SCHOOL MUSICAL Alum Corbin Bleu Ties the Knot |publisher=Broadway.com |date= |accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBleu graduated from [[Los Angeles County High School for the Arts]]. He trained in dancing at the Debbie Allen Dance Academy, and attended the [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School|Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts]] in New York as a theater major, following in his mother's footsteps.<ref>{{cite web|first= |last= |url=https://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/actor-profile/corbin-bleu |publisher=newyorktheatreguide.com |title= Corbin Bleu On Stage |date= |accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Judith |last=Newmark |url=https://www.stltoday.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/corbin-bleu-has-been-waiting-a-long-time-for-this/article_120f93a3-3ff5-59c8-8573-f48cce648c9f.html |publisher= stltoday.com |title= Corbin Bleu has been waiting a long time for this rainy day. |date= |accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref> Bleu graduated from high school in 2007 and was admitted to [[Stanford University]], but declined to matriculate because of scheduling commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEO-Corbin-Bleu-Earns-Perfect-Score-Advances-to-Finals-on-DWTS-20131119|title=VIDEO: Corbin Bleu Earns Perfect Score; Advances to Finals on DWTS |first= |last=|date=November 19, 2013|publisher=Broadway.com|accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref> As of 2007 he continued to live at home with his parents and three younger sisters.\n\n==Acting career==\n\n===1996\u20132005: Early career===\nBleu moved with his family from New York to [[Los Angeles]] in 1996. He worked steadily in episodic television and feature film roles, including a recurring role on the short-lived [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] police drama ''[[High Incident]]'' and a guest star appearance on ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''. He also appeared in some films, like ''Beach Movie'' (1998),{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''Boardheads''.}} and the sci-fi thriller ''[[Soldier (1998 American film)|Soldier]]'' (1998). His feature films from this period include the [[Tim Allen]] comedy ''[[Galaxy Quest]]'' (1999), and the comedy ''[[Mystery Men]]'' (1999), which starred [[Ben Stiller]], and the drama ''Family Tree'' (1999), alongside [[Andrew Lawrence (actor)|Andrew Lawrence]] and [[Matthew Lawrence]]. Bleu also had roles in ''[[Malcolm & Eddie]]'', as Matthew, and ''[[Cover Me (U.S. TV series)|Cover Me: Based on the True Life of an FBI Family]]'' (2000), as Nick Elderby{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''Cover Me''.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0549865/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_39 |title=Cover Me: Based on the True Life of an FBI Family: Our Mr. Brooks |website=[[IMDb]] |date=April 23, 2000 }}</ref> and smaller roles like in the comedy series [[List of programs broadcast by Nickelodeon|Nickelodeon]]'s show ''[[The Amanda Show]]''.\n\nAdditionally, Bleu was developing his dance skills and in 2001 began intensive training at the Debbie Allen Dance Academy in the Los Angeles area. There he undertook a full gamut of dance instruction, including [[ballet]], [[Jazz dance|jazz]], [[Tap dance|tap]], [[Modern dance|modern]], [[Hip-hop dance|hip-hop]], African, break dance, salsa, flamenco, and ballroom. Allen, the famous choreographer who starred in the TV series ''Fame'', told ''Dance Spirit'' magazine, \"I think [Bleu] really has a career. Success is one thing, but a career is a much longer, broader journey\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005JN0D |title=Catch-That-Kid on DVD in |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Corbin Bleu 3, (Cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Bleu in January 2006]]\n\nBleu attended the [[Los Angeles County High School for the Arts]], a magnet school like the [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School|Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts]], which was portrayed in the movie and television series ''Fame'', and which Bleu's mother had attended.<ref>{{cite web|last=Katz |first=Nikki |url=http://www.lachsa.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=237817&type=d&termREC_ID=&pREC_ID=459520 |title=Alumni Spotlight \u2013 LA County High School for the Arts |publisher=lachsa.net |date= |accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> During his freshman year, he won his first sizable film role in the teen action caper ''[[Catch That Kid]]'' (2004),{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''Catch That Girl'', and ''Catch That Kid!''.}} about a girl and her friends who decide to rob a bank after learning that money is needed to aid her dying father, alongside [[Kristen Stewart]] and [[Max Thieriot]]. Although it was a box office flop, having only grossed $10 million, it served as an important step for Bleu, who was still building his acting career at the time. During high school, he performed in such student productions as ''[[Footloose (musical)|Footloose]]'' and ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'', winning the honor of Theatre Student of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/19692328/ |title=The Daily News from Huntingdon, Pennsylvania \u00b7 Page 11 |newspaper=The Daily News |accessdate=January 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2004 Bleu landed a starring role in the television series ''[[Flight 29 Down]]'', alongside Allen Alvarado, [[Hallee Hirsh]], [[Lauren Storm]], [[Jeremy James Kissner]], [[Johnny Pacar]] and [[Kristy Wu]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacafe.com/tags/corbin_bleu/ |title=Corbin Bleu Videos |publisher=Metacafe |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> which aired for three seasons on the [[Discovery Kids]] network. The program, a juvenile version of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] series Lost, concerned a group of teenagers stranded on a tropical island after their plane crashes. Bleu played as [[Nathan McHugh]], a Boy Scout whose leadership skills do not quite measure up to his self-confidence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Katz |first=Nikki |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/dayton/article/Corbin-Bleu-Colleen-Zenk-to-Star-in-Human-Race-Theatre-Companys-World-Premiere-of-FAMILY-SHOTS-20141028 |title=Corbin Bleu & Colleen Zenk to Star in Human Race Theatre Company's World Premiere of FAMILY SHOTS |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=October 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2006\u20132008: ''High School Musical'' and breakthrough===\n[[File:HSM Concert cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Bleu performing during [[High School Musical: The Concert]] in 2006]]\nAlthough popular with its young audience, the success of ''[[Flight 29 Down]]'' pales in comparison to Bleu's next television project the [[List of Disney Channel original films|Disney Channel original films]] ''[[High School Musical]]'' (2006). The youngest of the six lead actors who were catapulted to fame by the film, Bleu portrayed the basketball player [[Chad Danforth]], who tries to persuade his teammate [[Troy Bolton]] ([[Zac Efron]]) to give up his interest in theater and focus on winning the basketball championship. ''High School Musical'' premiered on January 20, 2006; with an audience of 7.7 million television viewers, it was the [[Disney Channel]]'s most successful TV movie up to that point. The film, which also starred [[Ashley Tisdale]], [[Lucas Grabeel]], [[Vanessa Hudgens]], and [[Monique Coleman]] in pivotal roles, became a major success and helped Bleu gain recognition among teenage audiences. The film's soundtrack was certified quadruple platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinum.php|title=RIA Gold & Platinum|accessdate=December 17, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231133408/http://riaa.com/goldandplatinum.php|archivedate=December 31, 2009|df=}}</ref>\n\nHe joined co-stars on the 51-date ''[[High School Musical: The Concert]]'' (2006\u20132007) tour to promote the film,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gans|first1=Andrew|last2=Hernandez|first2=Ernio|title=Stars of TV's \"High School Musical\" to Tour in Concert Version|journal=[[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]]|publisher=Philip S Birsh|date=October 24, 2006|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/stars-of-tvs-high-school-musical-to-tour-in-concert-version-135786|accessdate=September 18, 2014}}</ref> work on the second film in the High School Musical series began, and Bleu was confirmed to be returning for the sequel. ''[[High School Musical 2]]'' (2007) was released on August 17, 2007. The premiere was seen by a total of over 17.2 million viewers in the U.S., which is almost 10 million more than its predecessor, making it the highest-rated Disney Channel Movie of all time.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/markets-festivals/high-school-musical-2-aces-test-1117970479/| work=Variety | first1=Rick | last1=Kissell | first2=Michael | last2=Schneider | title='High School Musical 2' aces test | date=August 18, 2007 |accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref> Disney Channel aired a weekly program called ''Road to High School Musical 2'', beginning on June 8, 2007, and leading up to the premiere of ''High School Musical 2'' in August. The show offered viewers a behind-the-scenes look into the production of the movie. The world premiere of the opening number \"[[What Time Is It? (song)|What Time Is It]]\" was on [[Radio Disney]] May 25, 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/news/ah5483.shtml |title='High School Musical 2' Debuts First Song |work=Access Hollywood |accessdate=August 18, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070528034633/http://www.accesshollywood.com/news/ah5483.shtml |archivedate=May 28, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and similarly the song \"[[I Don't Dance (High School Musical song)|I Don't Dance]]\" premiered on August 14, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/televisionNews/idUSN1529894020070716 |title=High School Musical 2 enters interactive semester | work= Reuters |accessdate=August 18, 2007 | date=July 16, 2007}}</ref> The film was generally well received by critics, gaining a score of 77/100 at [[Metacritic]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/shows/highschoolmusical2 |title=High School Musical 2 (Disney) \u2013 Reviews from Metacritic |accessdate=August 19, 2007 }}</ref> while it received a generally mixed response of 50% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/high_school_musical_2/ |title=High School Musical 2 (2007) |publisher=Rottentomatoes.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> The film broke opening weekend records and grossed over $250 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-08-09-high-school-musical2_N.htm|title=Can 'High School Musical' do it again?|accessdate=December 10, 2009|date=August 13, 2007|last=Keveney|first=Bill|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref> The soundtrack for the film, featuring numerous contributions from Bleu, went on to sell over three million copies in the United States alone.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b54100_High_School_Rules_06_Album_Sales.html|title=High School Rules '06 Album Sales|author=Jenison, David|date=January 4, 2007|work=[[E!]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|accessdate=March 28, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416080709/http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b54100_High_School_Rules_06_Album_Sales.html|archivedate=April 16, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> The song \"[[I Don't Dance (High School Musical song)|I Don't Dance]]\" (2007), a duet with [[Lucas Grabeel]], became his first top forty hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/chart_beat/bonus_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003630131|title=Chart Beat|accessdate=August 24, 2007|last=Bronson|first=Fred|date=August 23, 2007|work=Billboard.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929143429/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/chart_beat/bonus_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003630131 |archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> It was named as the official theme song for the [[2007 Little League World Series]].<ref name=\"MLBPA\">{{Citation|last=MLBPA|title=Who says big leaguers don't dance?|date=August 2, 2007|url=http://mlbplayers.mlb.com/pa/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070802&content_id=2125248&vkey=mlbpa_news&fext=.jsp|newspaper=MLBPA News}}</ref> During this time, Bleu began song on soundtracks for the Disney Channel, and released a cover of \"[[Two Worlds (song)|Two Worlds]]\" (2007) to promote ''[[Tarzan (1999 film)|Tarzan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000N0KVPQ |title=Disneymania 5: B5, Everlife, Go-Go's, Keke Palmer, Drew Seeley: Music |date= |accessdate=November 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Bleu starred in his next film, another Disney Channel original entitled ''[[Jump In!]]'' (2007),{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Filming took place from June\u2013July 2006 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada.}} which aired on January 12, 2007. Directed by [[Paul Hoen]], the television movie revolved around a young boy named Izzy Daniels who trains regularly in order to try to follow in his fathers footsteps and win the Golden Glove, an amateur boxing tournament. While Bleu played the lead role of Daniels, [[Keke Palmer]] portrayed the role of Mary, his friend who has a crush on Daniels. Again, Disney scored a crossover hit with the ''[[It's My Turn Now|Jump In! soundtrack]]'' album, was released in January 2007, on which Bleu sings the track, \"[[Push It to the Limit (Corbin Bleu song)|Push It to the Limit]]\" (2006).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/high-school-musicals-38755/|title=High School Musical's Corbin Bleu Hits the Ropes|website= TVGuide.com|accessdate=January 12, 2007|date=January 12, 2007}}</ref> Reaching the screens on the [[Disney Channel]] that January, ''Jump In!'' was a major hit amongst young viewers and quickly became the highest rated premiere the network has ever since, breaking the previous record set by ''[[The Cheetah Girls 2]]'' in 2006. Similar to ''[[High School Musical (franchise)|High School Musical]]'', its soundtrack was also a commercial hit, having achieved gold status from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) three months after its release.<ref name=\"oci\" /> He appeared in a music video of a new Atlanta group Small Change's video, \"Don't Be Shy\" featuring Chani and [[Lil' JJ]].<ref name=\"ReferenceM\">{{cite web|first=Small |last=Change2008 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LsuYpAaDbJQ |publisher= YouTube |title= Don't Be Shy Feat. Chani and Lil' JJ |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CorbinBleuMay07.jpg|thumb|right|Bleu in May 2007]]\n\nHe guest starred as Johnny Collins in the premiere two episodes of Disney's ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' (2006\u20132008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-taylor-swift-pop-music-face-20061231-snap-htmlstory.html|title=Looking back at naming Taylor Swift a pop music face to watch after her debut album|accessdate=December 31, 2006|date=December 31, 2006}}</ref> He also had a small role as Spencer on ''[[Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide]]'', appearing in the episodes entitled ''[[List of Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide episodes#Season 3: 2006\u20132007|Guide to: The School Play]]'' and ''[[List of Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide episodes#Season 3: 2006\u20132007|Guide to: Revenge & School Records]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0091158/|title=Spencer (Character) from Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide|accessdate=October 22, 2006}}</ref> and ''Mother Goose Parade'' as Grand Marshal in 2006 and 2007.<ref>{{cite web|first= |last= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5m-VY0wr75U |publisher= YouTube |title= Corbin Bleu & Monet @ Mother Goose Parade |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> While with Disney Channel, Bleu also participated in the first ever [[Disney Channel Games]] and co-captained the blue team along with [[Jake T. Austin]], [[Maiara Walsh]], [[Cole Sprouse]] and [[Kiely Williams]]. A year before, he returned to repeat his captaincy of the blue team with [[Brenda Song]], [[Vanessa Hudgens]], [[Monique Coleman]] and [[Jason Earles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/monique-coleman/photos/197471/2 |title=Corbin Bleu in 2007 Disney Channel Games |website= TVGuide.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> In August 2007, Bleu starred in ''[[Flight 29 Down#Film|Flight 29 Down: The Hotel Tango]]'', an teen drama film version of the [[Flight 29 Down|television series of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/flight_29_down_hotel_tango_the_series_finale/ |title=Flight 29 Down: The Hotel Tango |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 11, 2007}}</ref> Also in 2007, he is voice in ''[[The Secret of the Magic Gourd (2007 film)|The Secret of the Magic Gourd]]'' (2007), He appeared on ''[[The Tyra Banks Show]]'' in 2008.<ref>{{cite web| publisher= Warner Bros. Online |url=http://tyrashow.warnerbros.com/2009/03/fridays_show_everybodys_talkin.php |title=actor Corbin Bleu in tyrashow in 2008 |website= Tyrashow.warnerbros.com |date=March 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBleu went on to reprise his role of Chad Danforth in ''[[High School Musical 3: Senior Year]]'' (2008), the first film in the ''High School Musical'' franchise to receive a theatrical release. It opened at number one at the North American box office in October 2008, earning $42 million in its first weekend, which broke the record previously held by ''[[Mamma Mia! (film)|Mamma Mia!]]'' for the biggest opening by a musical.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodman|first=Dean|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-boxoffice-idUSTRE49M98K20081026 |title=\"High School Musical\" tops box office|work=Reuters|date=October 26, 2008|accessdate=February 4, 2016}}</ref> The film finished with $252 million worldwide, which exceeded Disney's expectations.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=High School Musical 3: Senior Year|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=highschoolmusical3.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> The song \"The Boys Are Back\" (2008), a duet with [[Zac Efron]], became his second top forty hit on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6851107/high-school-musical-chart-topping-success-2006|title='High School Musical' Was a Chart-Topping Phenomenon 10 Years Ago|author=Caulfield, Keith|date=January 20, 2016|accessdate=January 21, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupagesARIACharts-Accreditations-2008Albums.htm |title=ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2008 Albums |publisher=Aria.com.au |date=December 31, 2008 |accessdate=February 21, 2012}}</ref> The phenomenon of High School Musical has changed Bleu's life, delivering him to the heights of media celebrity while still in his teens. For his role as Chad Danforth, the team captain of the school's basketball team, he was nominated for an [[NAACP Image Award]] and a [[Young Artist Award]] and [[Teen Choice Awards]] in 2007 and 2009 respectively.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.idolator.com/7620612/high-school-musical-by-the-numbers-10th-anniversary|title='High School Musical' By The Numbers: Breaking Down The Hit Movie On Its 10th Anniversary|first=Robbie|last=Daw|accessdate=January 20, 2016|date=January 20, 2016}}</ref> Bleu lent his voice for the role of Chad Danforth in ''[[High School Musical (franchise)#Video games|High School Musical video games]]'', a video game based on the three films.<ref name=\"HSMVideogames\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/08/15/high-school-musical-makin-the-cut-review|title=High School Musical: Makin' the Cut! Review|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|website=[[IGN]]|date=2007-08-14|accessdate=2013-12-27}}</ref><ref name=\"HSMVideogames1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/04/23/high-school-musical-2-work-this-out-review|title=High School Musical 2: Work This Out Review|last=DeVries|first=Jack|website=[[IGN]]|date=2008-04-23|accessdate=2013-12-28}}</ref><ref name=\"HSMVideogames2\">{{cite web|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/927/927854p1.html|title=High School Musical 3: Senior Year Dance! Review|last=DeVries|first=Jack|website=IGN|date=2008-11-06|accessdate=2013-12-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081110085451/http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/927/927854p1.html|archivedate=2008-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"HSMVideogames3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/11/05/high-school-musical-3-senior-year-review|title=High School Musical 3: Senior Year Review|last=DeVries|first=Jack|website=[[IGN]]|date=2008-11-05|accessdate=2013-12-28}}</ref><ref name=\"HSMVideogames4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/11/05/high-school-musical-sing-it-2|title=High School Musical: Sing It! (PS2)|last=Miller|first=Greg|website=[[IGN]]|date=2007-11-05|accessdate=2013-12-15}}</ref><ref name=\"HSMVideogames5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2009/03/06/disney-sing-it-high-school-musical-3-senior-year-review-2|title=Disney Sing It: High School Musical 3: Senior Year Review|last=Miller|first=Greg|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Bleu's 2008 commercial for [[Activision]]'s ''[[Guitar Hero: On Tour: Decades|Guitar Hero on Tour: Decades]]'' was deemed too sexy to dance.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.shacknews.com/article/53654/guitar-hero-on-tour-decades | title = Guitar Hero On Tour: Decades Unveiled | date= March 10, 2009 | accessdate = March 10, 2009 | first = Aaron | last = Linde | publisher = [[Shacknews]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamespot.com/ds/action/guitarherodecades/review.html | title = ''Guitar Hero On Tour: Decades'' review | date =November 25, 2008 | accessdate = July 23, 2011 |publisher= Gamespot | first = Austin | last = Shau }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.shacknews.com/article/55124/guitar-hero-ds-decades-arrives | title = Guitar Hero DS Decades Arrives November 16 | publisher = [[Shacknews]] | date = October 6, 2008 | accessdate = October 6, 2008 | first = Chris | last = Faylor }}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132014: ''Free Style'' and ''One Life to Live''===\n[[File:Corbin Bleu 07, 1.jpg|thumb|left|Bleu at the [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] in 2007.]]\nThe following year, Bleu played the lead role in the film called ''[[Free Style (film)|Free Style]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1206664_free_style |title=Free Style |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=February 9, 2010}}</ref> Opened in theatres in October 2009, the coming of age movie revolved around Cale Bryant, an eighteen-year-old man who tries to find himself by winning the Amateur National Motocross Championships. ''Free Style'' performed poorly in the box office, having only grossed $720,000 from a $10 million budget. Over the next few years, Bleu's television roles included the drama series [[The CW Television Network]]'s show ''[[The Beautiful Life: TBL]].''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/columnists/glenn-garvin/story/1234518.html |title=Review \u2013 'The Beautiful Life: TBL' might just surprise you \u2013 Glenn ...|publisher=Miamiherald.com}}</ref> The series was subsequently cancelled on September 25, 2009 after televising 2 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/first-fall-tv-casualty-beautiful-life-wbna33027191|title=First fall TV casualty: 'The Beautiful Life |first=|last=|date=|work=Today.com|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2009}}</ref> In December 2009, the technology company [[Hewlett-Packard|HP]] became the show's sponsor and began airing the show's five episodes on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediapost.com/publications/?fa=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=119384|title=HP To Sponsor 'Beautiful Life' On YouTube|first=|last=|date=|work=Media Post|publisher=|accessdate=December 19, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118000106/http://www.mediapost.com/publications/?fa=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=119384|archivedate=January 18, 2010|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parade.com/celebrity/hollywood-wire/2009/12/18/ashton-kutcher-brings-beautiful-life-back-to-life.html|title=Ashton Kutcher Brings 'Beautiful Life' Back to Life |first=|last=|date=|work=Parade|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2009}}</ref> Also in 2009, he was a voice actor in ''[[Beyond All Boundaries]]'', and appeared on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' and ''[[The Morning Show with Mike and Juliet]]''. Also in 2009, he was the voice of Coltrane in the premiere two episodes of Disney's ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''.<ref name=\"ReferenceJ\" /> Bleu was considered as host for ''[[The X Factor (U.S. TV series)|The X Factor]]'' USA.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/corbin-bleu/news/268425-corbin-bleu-x-factor-simon-cowell-nicole-scherzinger-cheryl-cole| title=Corbin Bleu To Host The X Factor USA? | work=[[MTV.com|MTV]].com.uk | publisher= | date =April 30, 2011 | accessdate=April 30, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nCorbin Bleu made his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] stage debut in 2010 as the lead character, bodega-owner Usnavi, in the critically acclaimed musical ''[[In the Heights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Time 2hrs, 25 mins. (1 Intermission) |url=http://www.broadway.com/shows/in-the-heights/ |title=In the Heights Tickets &#124; Broadway |publisher=Broadway.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> and guest starred in one episode of ''[[The Good Wife]]'' as DJ Javier Berlin in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2010/10/the-good-wife-review-cleaning-house/ |title=The Good Wife Review: Who is Wendy Scott-Carr?!? |publisher=TV Fanatic |date=October 20, 2010 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> in 2010, Corbin starred in the short comedy film ''I Owe My Life to Corbin Bleu'', alongside [[Andrew Caldwell (actor)|Andrew Caldwell]], [[Drake Bell]], [[Sarah Hyland]], [[Ryan Pinkston]], [[Sterling Knight]], [[Matt Prokop]], [[Matt Shively]] and [[Josh Sussman]]. In 2011, he performed the voice Lou in ''[[The Little Engine That Could (2011 film)|The Little Engine That Could]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.netflix.com/Movie/The-Little-Engine-That-Could/70166309| title=The Little Engine That Could to your movie list Whoopi Goldberg, Jamie Lee Curtis, Corbin Bleu and Brenda Song| work=netflix.com | publisher= | date =January 4, 2011 | accessdate=January 4, 2011 }}</ref> From August 5\u20137, Bleu performed in the musical ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' as Seaweed at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], alongside [[Nick Jonas]], [[Harvey Fierstein]], [[Marissa Jaret Winokur]], [[Drew Carey]] and [[Darlene Love]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/hollywood-bowl-hairspray-to-feature-harvey-fierstein-marissa-jaret-winokur-drew-carey-darlene-love-nick-jonas-com-179448 |title=Hollywood Bowl Hairspray to Feature Corbin Bleu, Harvey Fierstein, Marissa Jaret Winokur, Drew Carey, Darlene Love, Nick Jonas |publisher=playbill.com |date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=October 19, 2011}}</ref> and he performed the voice Flip in ''Tonka Chuck and Friends: Big Air Dare''.\n\nIn 2012, Bleu also had a role in and co-produced the indie horror anthology ''[[Scary or Die]]'' (2012), a collection of five short horror films.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/news/ni7393081/| title=Exclusive Early Details on Indie Anthology Scary or Die| work=[[IMDb]].com | publisher= | date =February 2, 2011 | accessdate=February 2, 2011 }}</ref> In 2012, he joined the cast of ''[[Godspell]]'' as Jesus beginning April 17 at the Circle in the Square Theatre.{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Corbin Bleu takes over the role from original star [[Hunter Parrish]], who will play his final performance on April 15.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/160799/corbin-bleu-to-succeed-hunter-parrish-as-jesus-in-broadways-godspell/ |title=Corbin Bleu to Succeed Hunter Parrish as Jesus in Broadway's Godspell |publisher=[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] |date=March 23, 2012 |accessdate=March 23, 2012}}</ref> He joined co-stars on the [[66th Tony Awards|66th Annual Tony Awards]], to performing \"[[Day by Day (Godspell song)|Day by Day]]\" and \"Light of the World\" at [[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/history/ceremonies/201307161373984619178.html |title=Year by Year 2012 TonyAwards |publisher=[[Tony Award]] |date=June 10, 2012 |accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gans|first=Andrew|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/broadways-big-night-neil-patrick-harris-hosts-66th-annual-tony-awards-june-10-com-194498 |title=Broadway's Big Night! Neil Patrick Harris Hosts 66th Annual Tony Awards June 10 |publisher=playbill.com |date=June 10, 2012 |accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> with [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as the host.<ref name=hostNYT>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=Footnote|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/03/theater/footnote.html|accessdate=April 3, 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 2, 2012}}</ref><ref name=hostLAT>{{cite news|last=Ng|first=David|title=Can Neil Patrick Harris boost Tony Awards ratings?|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2012/04/neil-patrick-harris-to-host-2012-tony-awards.html|accessdate=April 3, 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 3, 2012}}</ref> During this time, he recorded the duet \"[[If I Never Knew You]]\" (2012), with [[Anna Maria Perez de Tagle]] to promote ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/162082/corbin-bleu-sings-pocahontas-lindsay-mendez-belts-wicked-watch-the-godspell-cast-pay-tribute-to-stephen-schwartz/ |title=Corbin Bleu Sings Pocahontas! Lindsay Mendez Belts Wicked! Watch the Godspell Cast Pay Tribute to Stephen Schwartz |publisher=broadway.com |date= |accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Blank |first=Matthew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/photo-call-broadways-godspell-troupe-sings-stephen-schwartz-com-194022 |title=Broadway's Godspell Troupe Sings Stephen Schwartz |publisher=playbill.com |date= May 25, 2012|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref> He guest starred in one episode of ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]'' as Officer Blake in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/123994_Corbin_Bleu_Guest_Starring_on_Blue_Bloods/ |title='Blue Bloods' Taps 'HSM' Star |publisher=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |date= |accessdate=August 7, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, he performed the voice Drew in ''Twinkle Toes'', Bleu starred in the drama film ''[[To Write Love on Her Arms (film)|To Write Love on Her Arms]]'' (originally titled ''Renee''{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''Day One''; formerly ''Renee''.}}) in 2012, with [[Kat Dennings]], [[Chad Michael Murray]] and [[Rupert Friend]]. The film began production in [[Orlando, Florida]], in February 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twloha.com/news.php?nid=229 |title=Announces Support of Upcoming Film \"RENEE\" Orlando, FL \u2013 February 24, 2011 |publisher=Twloha.com |date=February 25, 2011 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Moore |first=Roger |url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_movies_blog/2011/02/renee-project-starring-kat-dennings-chad-michael-murray-and-rupert-friend-gets-underway-in-orlando.html |title='Renee,' starring Kat Dennings, Chad Michael Murray and Rupert Friend, gets underway in Orlandos |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=February 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227173727/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_movies_blog/2011/02/renee-project-starring-kat-dennings-chad-michael-murray-and-rupert-friend-gets-underway-in-orlando.html |archivedate=February 27, 2011 |accessdate=March 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Corbin Bleu at Kids' Inaugural cropped.jpg|thumb|right|Bleu at the ''[[First inauguration of Barack Obama#Kids' Inaugural: \"We Are the Future\"|Kids' Inaugural: \"We Are the Future\"]]'', January 2009.]]\n\nIn March 2013, Bleu had a role in the horror film ''[[The Monkey's Paw (2013 film)|The Monkey's Paw]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/chiller-stephen-lang-corbin-bleu-370749 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Philiana | last=Ng | title=Stephen Lang, Corbin Bleu to Topline Chiller TV Movie (Exclusive) | date=September 17, 2012}}</ref> and guest starred in one episode of ''[[Franklin & Bash]]'' as Jordan Allen French in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvgoodness.com/2013/06/20/guest-star-goodness-franklin-bash-2-hour-season-3-premiere/ |title=Guest Star Goodness: Franklin & Bash 2-Hour Season 3 Premiere |publisher=tvgoodness.com |date= |accessdate=June 20, 2013}}</ref> In April 2013, Bleu was cast in the role of [[Jeffrey King]] on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] daytime soap opera ''[[One Life to Live]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://deadline.com/2013/03/corbin-bleu-joins-one-life-to-live-453582/ | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | first= | last= | title=Corbin Bleu Joins Soap Revival 'One Life To Live' | date=March 14, 2013}}</ref> In 2013, Bleu starred in the film ''[[Sugar (2013 film)|Sugar]]'' (2013), alongside [[Shenae Grimes]] and [[Marshall Allman]]. about a runaway girl living on the streets of Venice, Los Angeles. The film began production in [[Venice, Los Angeles]], on November 30, 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2013/film/reviews/film-review-sugar-1200871315/ | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Geoff | last=Berkshire | title=Film Review: 'Sugar' 2013 | date=November 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Berkshire |first=Geoff |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/reviews/film-review-sugar-1200871315/ |title=Film Review: Sugar |magazine=variety.com |accessdate=November 22, 2013}}</ref> Also in 2013, Bleu appeared in the horror films ''[[Nurse 3D]]'' (2013), alongside [[Paz de la Huerta]] and [[Katrina Bowden]].<ref name=\"VarietyAug42011\">{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118040894|title=Corbin Bleu joins cast of 'Nurse 3D'|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=August 4, 2011|accessdate=October 8, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114115648/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118040894|archivedate=November 14, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The film began production in [[Toronto]], on September 6, 2011 and wrapped on October 21, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/04/doug-aarniokoski-to-helm-the-nurse-3d-for-lionsgate/|title=Doug Aarniokoski To Helm 'The Nurse 3D' For Lionsgate|last=Fleming|first=Mike|authorlink=|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]]|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=October 8, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820234404/http://www.deadline.com/2011/04/doug-aarniokoski-to-helm-the-nurse-3d-for-lionsgate/|archivedate=August 20, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/26130|title=Confirmed Shooting Cast for Lionsgate's 'Nurse 3D'|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=August 31, 2011|accessdate=October 8, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301082336/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/26130/|archivedate=March 1, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/VIDEO-First-Look-Corbin-Bleu-Stars-in-Horror-Thriller-NURSES-3D-20131205 |title=VIDEO: First Look \u2013 Corbin Bleu Stars in Horror Thriller Nurse 3D |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=December 31, 2013}}</ref> In 2014 he also appeared as a guest star in ''[[Psych]]'', the [[USA Network]] television series in [[Psych (season 8)|Season 8]]. He guest starred in one episode of ''[[Drop Dead Diva]]'' as Michael in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soapoperanetwork.com/2014/02/rick-springfield-colin-egglesfield-corbin-bleu-to-guest-on-drop-dead-diva |title=Rick Springfield, Colin Egglesfield, & Corbin Bleu to Guest On 'Drop Dead Diva' |publisher=soapoperanetwork.com |date= |accessdate=February 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u2013present: Further success ===\n[[File:CorbinBleuDec10.jpg|thumb|left|Bleu at a performance of ''The Hot Chocolate Nutcracker'', December 2010]]\nBleu's only release in 2015 was the moderately successful ''Megachurch Murder'' (2015), in which he played a Marcus King, with [[Tamala Jones]], [[Shanica Knowles]] and [[Romeo Miller]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thewrap.com/megachurch-murder-star-tamala-jones-on-playing-a-pastors-devious-wife-shes-really-a-monster/ | work=thewrap.com | first=Anita | last=Bennett | title='Megachurch Murder' Stars | date=February 7, 2015}}</ref> In addition, Bleu appeared in ''Family Shots'' with The Human Race Theatre Company. Bleu did make however a guest appearance in an episode of the family drama, ''[[The Fosters (2013 TV series)|The Fosters]]'' in 2016 playing the role of Mercutio, a character who appears in a school musical production of ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fosters-casts-high-school-musical-849590 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Kate | last=Stanhope | title='The Fosters' Casts 'High School Musical' Alum (Exclusive) | date=December 16, 2015}}</ref> Bleu and fellow guest-star [[Ashley Argota]] also co-starred in a production of ''Romeo and Juliet: Love Is a Battlefield'' at Rockwell Table and Stage, Produced by ''The Fosters'' co-creator Bradley Bredeweg.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|last= |first= |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Corbin-Bleu-Ashley-Argota-to-Take-Over-Lead-Roles-in-ROMEO-JULIET-LOVE-IS-A-BATTLEFIELD-20150421 |title=Corbin Bleu and Ashley Argota to Take Over Lead Roles in Romeo and Juliet: Love Is a Battlefield |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> He also had a small role as Spencer on ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/113718/20160205/castle-season-8-episode-9-spoilers-corbin-blue-guest-stars-in-tone-deaf-episode.htm |title='Castle' Season 8, Episode 9 Features Guest Star Corbin Bleu |publisher=latinpost.com |date= February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> Bleu was considered as host for ''[[Fake Off]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Corbin-Bleu-to-Host-New-Season-of-truTVs-FAKE-OFF-Glees-Harry-Shum-Jr-to-Judge-20150310#| title=Corbin Bleu to Host New Season of truTV's FAKE OFF; Glee's Harry Shum Jr. to Judge | work=broadwayworld.com | publisher= | date =March 10, 2015 | accessdate=March 10, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, he joined the cast of ''The Dodgers'' as Simon, the rational voice amid the habitually stoned chatter, and beginning January 21 at the Hudson Mainstage Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Corbin-Bleu-Emma-Hunton-More-to-Lead-World-Premiere-of-New-Play-THE-DODGERS-in-Los-Angeles-20160104 |title=Corbin Bleu, Emma Hunton & More to Lead World Premiere of New Play The Dodgers in Los Angeles |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=January 4, 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, he took part in Broadway productions notably the leading role in ''[[Holiday Inn (musical)|Holiday Inn, The New Irving Berlin Musical]]'' (originally titled ''Holiday Inn''), a musical based on the 1942 [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning [[Holiday Inn (film)|film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/holiday-inn-the-new-irving-berlin-musical-begins-on-broadway-tonight# |title=Critics Review Holiday Inn on Broadway |work=Playbill |date=October 7, 2016 |accessdate=November 1, 2016}}</ref> Returning to his tap dancing roots was \"like riding a bike\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundabouttheatre.org/Shows-Events/Holiday-Inn.aspx|title=Holiday Inn on Broadway|accessdate=September 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901033203/http://www.roundabouttheatre.org/Shows-Events/Holiday-Inn.aspx|archive-date=September 1, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> His former Disney co-stars appeared to be big fans of Bleu's new endeavor when they stopped by a performance in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/high-school-musical-reunion-zac-efron-corbin-bleu-lucas-grabeel-reunite/|title=''High School Musical'' Reunion! Wildcats Zac Efron, Corbin Bleu and Lucas Grabeel Reunite |work=People|first=Natalie|last=Stone|date=October 5, 2016|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> The [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] alum and [[High School Musical (franchise)|''High School Musical'']] favorite grabbed a camera as Broadway websites' newest vlogger,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2016/09/15/holiday-inn-corbin-bleu-broadway/ |title=Holiday Inn: Corbin Bleu on stepping into Fred Astaire's tap shoes on Broadway|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Devan|last=Coogan|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> resulting in ''Bleu Skies'': Backstage at ''Holiday Inn'' with Corbin Bleu. Bleu, who played Ted in the new [[Irving Berlin]] musical, gave a glimpse of backstage life at [[Studio 54]], where he and his co-stars (including former vlogger [[Bryce Pinkham]], [[Lora Lee Gayer]], [[Megan Lawrence]] and [[Megan Sikora]]) celebrated an entire year's worth of special occasions eight times a week. ''Bleu Skies'' launched off on August 23 and ran every Tuesday for eight weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/watch-broadway-holiday-inn-casts-joyous-dance-on-the-today-show |title=Watch Broadway Holiday Inn Cast's Joyous Dance on the Today Show |publisher=playbill.com |date= October 18, 2016|accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref> with Bleu being nominated for a [[Chita Rivera Awards for Dance and Choreography]] in 2017, for outstanding dancing in a Broadway show,<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwdance/article/BANDSTAND-CATS-HOLIDAY-INN-SWEET-CHARITY-Among-2017-Chita-Rivera-Award-Nominees-20170501 |title=Bandstand, Cats, Holiday Inn, Sweet Charity Among 2017 Chita Rivera Award Nominees |publisher= broadwayworld.com|date= |accessdate=May 1, 2017}}</ref> and eventually winning a Chita Rivera Award for his performance.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=corbinbleu|last=Bleu|first=Corbin|number=963130983724679169|title=My Chita Rivera Awards finally came in! I normally don't post about awards but I gotta say, this one means a lot! This is my first Broadway accolade and I am so honored that it was for Outstanding Male Dancer \ud83d\ude4f\ud83c\udffd I love & miss you my Holiday Inn musical fam \u2764\ufe0f|date=September 11, 2017|accessdate=February 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceG\">{{cite web |url=http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/chita-rivera-awards-2017-photos_82370.html |title=Megan Sikora, Andy Blankenbuehler, Tommy Tune Take Home 2017 Chita Rivera Awards |publisher= theatermania.com|date= |accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Corbin Bleu (Cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Bleu at the Summer with the Stars, Red Carpet in 2011]]\n\nWhile with [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television, Bleu also participated in the first ever ''[[Battle of the Network Stars#Battle of the Network Stars (2017)|Battle of the Network Stars]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Taylor |first=Kelly |url=http://www.foxla.com/good-day/good-day-la-celebrity-interviews/264685677-story |title=Corbin Bleu on marriage and competing in 'Battle of the Network Stars' |publisher=foxla.com |date= |accessdate=June 29, 2017}}</ref> joining the red team along with [[Joey Lawrence]], [[Nolan Gould]], [[Lisa Whelchel]] and [[Kim Fields]], with [[Ronda Rousey]] as the captain. The series premiered on June 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keveney |first=Bill |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2017/06/27/abc-battle-of-the-network-stars-reality-competition/103143742/ |title='Battle of the Network Stars' is latest summer nostalgia play |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref> From July 28\u201330, Bleu performed in the musical ''[[Mamma Mia!]]'' as Sky at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], alongside [[Dove Cameron]], [[Lea DeLaria]] and [[Jennifer Nettles]]. The theatre premiered on July 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Orenstein |first=Hannah |url=http://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/movies-tv/a10391988/corbin-bleu-is-gushing-about-co-starring-with-dove-cameron-in-mamma-mia-and-its-adorable/ |title=Corbin Bleu Is Gushing About Co-Starring with Dove Cameron in \"Mamma Mia\" and It's Adorable |publisher=seventeen.com |date= July 31, 2017|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref> Corbin Bleu's career also included [[voice-over|voice over]] work (or [[voice acting]]) with ''Breathe Bible''.<ref>[http://breathebible.com/voices/corbin-bleu/ Corbin Bleu, The Voice of John] BreatheBible.com Retrieved September 18, 2017</ref> In December 2017, Corbin Bleu hosted the 2017 Looking Ahead Awards, presented by [[Actors Fund of America|The Actors Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/los-angeles/article/Corbin-Bleu-to-Host-The-Actors-Funds-Looking-Ahead-Awards-Honoring-Youth-Cast-of-NBCs-THIS-IS-US-20171204 |title=Corbin Bleu to Host The Actors Fund's Looking Ahead Awards, Honoring Youth Cast of NBC's This Is Us |website=broadwayworld.com |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, he guest starred in one episode of ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' as Luke, a handsome drummer that catches Brad's attention.<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-First-Look-Corbin-Bleu-Guests-on-ABCs-THE-MIDDLE-20171222 |title=First Look \u2013 Corbin Bleu Guests on ABC's The Middle |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Scoop-THE-MIDDLE-on-ABC-Today-January-9-2018-20180108 |title=The Middle on ABC \u2013 Today, January 9, 2018 |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> In 2018 he also appeared as a guest star in ''[[Chicago Med]]'', the [[NBC]] television series in [[Chicago Med (season 3)|Season 3]], as Tommy Oliver. From June 27 \u2013 July 3, Bleu performed in the musical ''[[Singin' in the Rain (musical)|Singin' in the Rain]]'' as Don Lockwood at the [[The Muny|St. Louis Municipal Opera Theatre]],{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''The Muny''.}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/cast-complete-for-st-louis-munys-singin-in-the-rain-starring-corbin-bleu |publisher=[[Playbill]].com |title=Cast Complete for St. Louis Muny's Singin' in the Rain, Starring Corbin Bleu.|date= |accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref> a musical based on the 1952 [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Film Awards]]-winning [[Singin' in the Rain|film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kermode |first=Mark| url=http://www.bafta.org/film/awards/best-film-winner-the-artist |publisher=bafta.org |title=Best Film Winner: The Artist.|date= February 11, 2012|accessdate=February 11, 2012}}</ref> The theatre premiered on June 27, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lefkowitz |first=Andy| url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/191979/holiday-inn-showstoppers-corbin-bleu-megan-sikora-to-reunite-in-the-munys-singin-in-the-rain/ |publisher=broadway.com |title=Holiday Inn Showstoppers Corbin Bleu & Megan Sikora to Reunite in the Muny's Singin' in the Rain.|date= |accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gans |first=Andrew | url=http://www.playbill.com/article/watch-corbin-bleu-charm-in-scenes-from-st-louis-muny-singin-in-the-rain |publisher=[[Playbill]].com |title=Corbin Bleu Charm in Scenes From St. Louis Muny Singin' in the Rain.|date= |accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref> with Bleu being nominated for a St. Louis Theater Circle Awards in 2019, for Outstanding Actor in a Musical.<ref name=\"ReferenceH\">{{cite web|last=Hamdan |first=Lara |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/st-louis-theater-circle-announces-its-2019-nominees-celebrates-7-years-awards#stream/0 |title=St. Louis Theater Circle Announces Its 2019 Nominees, Celebrates 7 Years Of Awards |publisher= St. Louis Public Radio.com|date= |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> Near the end of 2018, Bleu played Billy Crocker in ''[[Anything Goes]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Clement |first=Olivia |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/corbin-bleu-and-soara-joye-ross-to-star-in-anything-goes-at-arena-stage |publisher=[[Playbill]].com |title=Corbin Bleu and Soara-Joye Ross to Star in Anything Goes at Arena Stage.|date= August 16, 2018|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> which will be seen in-the-round at Arena Stage in D.C. Washingtion from November 2 \u2013 December 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=| url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Corbin-Bleu-and-Soara-Joye-Ross-to-Lead-Arena-Stages-ANYTHING-GOES-20180816 |publisher=broadwayworld.com |title=Corbin Bleu and Soara-Joye Ross to Lead Arena Stage's Anything Goes.|date= |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> with Bleu being nominated for a [[Helen Hayes Award]] in 2019, for Outstanding Actor in a Musical,<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=2019 Helen Hayes Awards Nominations|pages=|publisher=Theatre Washington|date=February 2019|url=https://theatrewashington.org:8443/sites/default/files/news-uploads/2019%20Helen%20Hayes%20Awards%20Nominations%20List.pdf|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> and eventually winning a Helen Hayes Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Musical.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mcphee|first=Ryan|title=Ain't Too Proud Star Ephraim Sykes, Corbin Bleu, Tina Landau Among 2019 Helen Hayes Award Winners|pages=|publisher=playbill.com|date=May 2019|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/aint-too-proud-star-ephraim-sykes-corbin-bleu-tina-landau-among-2019-helen-hayes-award-winners|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, he was cast in the [[Netflix]] drama film ''[[Walk. Ride. Rodeo.]]'' (2019),{{efn|group=upper-alpha|The film about the life of a championship [[Barrel racing|barrel racer]] [[Amberley Snyder]].}} alongside [[Missi Pyle]], [[Spencer Locke]] and [[Bailey Chase]], directed by Conor Allyn.<ref>{{cite web|last1=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|title=Missi Pyle, Spencer Locke & More To Star In Netflix's 'Walk Ride Rodeo' Biopic About Paralyzed Horse Racer Amberley Snyder|url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/missi-pyle-spencer-locke-sherri-shepherd-netflix-walk-ride-rodeo-movie-1202435082/|website=Deadline|accessdate=July 27, 2018|date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> He appeared on ''Show Offs'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=BYUVPRichardson|last=O. Richardson|first=Matthew|number=1028509983984340992|title=Just watched a taping of byutv\u2019s new improve comedy program \u201cShow Offs\u201d mrgrabeel and corbinbleu joined our talented troupe for a couple of episodes.  If you enjoying laughing\u2014don\u2019t miss this program, premiering in January 2019.|date=August 11, 2018|accessdate=April 22, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Bleu played Bill Calhoun/Lucentio in the Broadway revival of ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' at the Roundabout Theatre's Studio 54. The musical originally opened on Broadway in 1948 and five years later was the basis for a liberally adapted 1953 film of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levy |first=Emanuel| url=http://emanuellevy.com/oscar/oscar-movies-kiss-me-kate/ |publisher=emanuellevy.com |title=Oscar Movies: Kiss Me Kate\u2013Cole Porter Musical of Shakespeare.|date= |accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref> The production, directed by [[Scott Ellis]],<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=| url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Breaking-Corbin-Bleu-Stephanie-Styles-More-Join-KISS-ME-KATE-on-Broadway-Amanda-Green-Will-Update-Book-20181010 |publisher=broadwayworld.com |title=Breaking: Corbin Bleu, Stephanie Styles & More Join Kiss Me, Kate on Broadway; Amanda Green Will Update Book|date= |accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref> began previewing on February 14, 2019. The limited engagement is scheduled to continue through June 30 at [[Studio 54]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Nyc |first=Roundabout |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Btg8VgVF-IX/ |publisher=[[Instagram]].com |title=In just 9 days, this fabulous Kiss Me, Kate cast will begin performances at Studio 54.|date= |accessdate=February 5, 2019}}</ref> For his performance, Bleu was nominated for the Drama Desk Award for [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical|Outstanding Featured Actor in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Mcphee |first=Ryan| url=http://www.playbill.com/article/nominations-for-the-2019-drama-desk-awards-announced-oklahoma-tootsie-rags-parkland-lead-the-pack |magazine=[[Playbill]]|title=Nominations for the 2019 Drama Desk Awards Announced; Oklahoma!, Tootsie, Rags Parkland Lead the Pack.|accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref> Bleu was also nominated for a 2019 [[Chita Rivera Awards for Dance and Choreography]], for Outstanding Male Dancer in a Broadway Show,<ref>{{cite web|last=Gordon |first=David| url=https://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/corbin-bleu-nominated-for-2019-chita-rivera_88577.html |publisher=theatermania.com |title=Corbin Bleu and More Nominated for 2019 Chita Rivera Awards.|date= |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> and for an [[Broadway.com Audience Awards|Audience Choice Awards]] for Favorite Featured Actor in a Musical.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wontorek |first=Paul| url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/195749/fan-picked-2019-broadwaycom-audience-choice-award-nominations-announced-be-more-chill-leads-with-12/ |publisher=Broadway.com |title=Fan-Picked 2019 Broadway.com Audience Choice Award Nominations Announced; Be More Chill Leads With 12.|date= |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> He was cast in a co-starring role in the Jordan Barker film ''Witches in the Woods'' (2019),{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Also known as ''Stranded''.}}{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Filming took place from March 2018 in [[Sudbury District|Sudbury]], Ontario, Canada.}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Donnelly|first=Matt |url=https://www.thewrap.com/exorcist-star-hannah-kasulka-corbin-bleu-survival-thriller-stranded/|title='Exorcist' Star Hannah Kasulka, Corbin Bleu Hit Slopes for Survival Thriller 'Stranded'|date=|publisher=thewrap.com|accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> The project also stars Hannah Kasulka, and [[Sasha Clements]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Bleu |first=Corbin |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BgwssrLh4Q5/ |publisher=[[Instagram]].com |title=When you both book a movie and it happens to be the same one \ud83d\ude0d loving working together!.|date= |accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Bleu filmed an independent movie titled ''Ovid and the Art of Love''. Filmed partially at the old St. Agnus Church in [[Michigan]],{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Filming took place from October 2015.}} the project also stars [[John Savage (actor)|John Savage]], [[Tamara Feldman]] and [[Tara Summers]].\n\n====Upcoming projects====\nBleu is working on an upcoming project, ''The Day I Died'', about the consequences of bullying.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/the-day-i-died#/|title=The Day I Died for Indiegogo |first=Michael |last=Emanuel|date=|work=indiegogo.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 17, 2014}}</ref> Bleu will star as the conman [[Frank Abagnale]], in a production of ''[[Catch Me If You Can (musical)|Catch Me If You Can]]'' at [[Arena Stage]], which will run October 23 to December 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/198470/corbin-bleu-to-star-in-catch-me-if-you-can-in-washington-dc/| title= Corbin Bleu to Star in Catch Me If You Can in Washington, D.C.|first=Diep |last=Tran|work=broadway.com|accessdate= February 18, 2020}}</ref> The musical is based on the hit film of the same name, and is created by [[Terrence McNally]], [[Scott Wittman]] and [[Marc Shaiman]]; it's about a real life conman and the detective charged with tracking him down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/arena-stage-unveils-world-premieres-from-craig-lucas-and-theresa-rebeck-a-lynn-nottage-revival-and-more| title= Arena Stage Unveils World Premieres From Craig Lucas and Theresa Rebeck, a Lynn Nottage Revival, and More|first=Olivia |last=Clement|work=playbill.com|accessdate= February 21, 2020}}</ref> The musical will be directed by Arena Stage artistic director [[Molly Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatermania.com/washington-dc-theater/news/arena-stage-2020-21-season-theresa-rebeck-craig-lucas_90609.html| title= New Theresa Rebeck, Craig Lucas Plays to Premiere at Arena Stage 2020-21 Season|first=Kenji |last=Fujishima|work=theatermania.com|accessdate= February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==''Dancing with the Stars''==\nIn September 2013, Bleu took part in the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 17)|seventeenth-season]] of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s dancing competition ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. He finished as runner-up.\n\n[[File:Corbin Bleu with Butterfly.png|thumb|235px|right|Bleu in February 2019]]\nIn the series, he partnered with professional dancer [[Karina Smirnoff]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://people.com/tv/dancing-with-the-stars-corbin-bleu-and-karina-smirnoff-blog-about-first-dance/| title=Corbin Bleu & Karina Smirnoff's ''Dancing with the Stars'' Blog: We Laugh Everyday | work=People|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> Bleu and Smirnoff were one of six couples still in the running to be crowned ''Dancing with the Stars'', seventeenth-season champions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.instyle.com/news/exclusive-dancing-stars-karina-smirnoff-her-premiere-costume-simplicity-speaks-volumes|title=Exclusive! Dancing with the Stars' Karina Smirnoff on Her Premiere Costume: \"Simplicity Speaks Volumes\" |first=Grace |last=Gavilanes |date=September 17, 2013|work=[[InStyle]]accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> Bleu wrote in his ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' blog. \"It's nice to be able to see the finish line, but it's also very motivating. We don't want to lose any moment. We really want to make sure we end strong\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/tv/corbin-bleus-dwts-blog-im-dedicating-this-weeks-dance-to-my-sisters/|title=Corbin Bleu's ''DWTS'' Blog: 'I'm Dedicating This Week's Dance to My Sisters' | work=People|date=October 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBleu danced a [[Viennese Waltz|Viennese waltz]] to the ''[[Game of Thrones Theme|Game of Thrones theme music]]'' \u2014 while dressed as the [[Dothraki]], [[Khal Drogo]]. Bleu revealed during rehearsals that ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' was his very favorite show, and his passion came through in his performance. However, while the judges liked the intense, epic feeling of the dance, Len felt there was not enough technical substance in the routine 23 Score.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEO-Corbin-Bleu-Channels-Game-of-Thrones-on-DWTS-20131022| title=Corbin Bleu Channels 'Game of Thrones' on DWTS |work=broadwayworld.com | publisher=|date=October 22, 2013}}</ref> Bleu noted the jazz dance should be \"pretty sick\" and had hints of [[Michael Jackson]] in it. Bleu also revealed it featured a little \"tap section\" at the end, and because Smirnoff had never tapped before, he was thrilled to be able to teach her something for once.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEO-Corbin-Bleu-Wows-with-Freestyle-Michael-Jackson-Classic-20131126| title=Corbin Bleu Wows with Freestyle Michael Jackson Classic|work=Broadway World|date=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2013, appeared with his professional dancer Karina Smirnoff on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', to give a fiery performance, and after taking a turn in the splash tank, he then performed a [[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-cha-cha]], [[Foxtrot]] or [[Contemporary dance|Contemporary]] routine, vying for America's vote for the first time. The partners scored high with the judges, earning a 27/30, making them the first safe couple of the night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/dancing-with-the-stars-ballroom-stunned-by-unexpected-elimination/|title=\"Dancing with the Stars\" ballroom stunned by unexpected elimination |first= |last=|date=November 12, 2013|work=ET Online|accessdate=November 12, 2013}}</ref> [[Keyshawn Johnson]] and [[Sharna Burgess]], however, were the first to be eliminated during the week, leaving 11 couples in the ballroom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/140639_Dancing_with_the_Stars_Recap_Season_17_Week_9/|title='DWTS' Ballroom Stunned by Unexpected Elimination |first=Robert |last=Pace|date=November 11, 2013|work=ET Onlike|accessdate=March 8, 2019}}</ref> Bleu and Smirnoff also won the week's \"Dance-Off Challenge\" and therefore received three bonus points.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ew.com/recap/dancing-with-the-stars-season-17-week-6/| title=Dancing with the Stars recap: Unleash the Dragons!|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 22, 2013}}</ref> Corbin and his partner made it to the finals, but became the runners-up behind [[Amber Riley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/141270_DWTS_Season_17_Backstage/| title='DWTS' Finale: Stars & Pros Look Back at Season 17|website=ET Online|date=November 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Bleu returned to [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 25)|25th season]] of the show and in Week 8,<ref>{{cite web|last=Montgomery |first=Daniel |url=http://www.goldderby.com/article/2017/dancing-with-the-stars-trio-dances-kelly-monaco-alfonso-ribeiro-news-957136248/ |title='Dancing with the Stars' trio dances will invite back Kelly Monaco, Alfonso Ribeiro, Laurie Hernandez, Corbin Bleu |website=Gold Derby|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref> he performed in a trio [[Salsa (dance)|Salsa]] with [[Jordan Fisher]] and his professional partner [[Lindsay Arnold]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Brozyna |first=Emily |url=http://www.j-14.com/posts/jordan-fisher-corbin-bleu-dancing-with-the-stars-145834 |title='Dancing with the Stars' trio dances will invite back Kelly Monaco, Alfonso Ribeiro, Laurie Hernandez, Corbin Bleu |publisher=J-14|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref> Bleu and Fisher havd some startling similarities in their personalities, so they were very excited to finally get to work together,<ref>{{cite web|last=Gans |first=Andrew |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/watch-hamiltons-jordan-fisher-and-holiday-inns-corbin-bleu-perform-on-dancing-with-the-stars |title=Watch Hamilton's Jordan Fisher and Holiday Inn's Corbin Bleu Perform on Dancing With the Stars |work=Playbill|date=November 7, 2017}}</ref> After the trio delivered their Salsa to audiences, they ended with a score of 30 from the judges,<ref>{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Natalie |url=http://people.com/tv/jordan-fisher-how-corbin-bleu-inspired-him-to-pursue-acting/ |title=Jordan Fisher Explains How Watching 'Mixed Kid' Corbin Bleu Inspired Him to Pursue Acting|work=People|date=November 6, 2017}}</ref> [[Bruno Tonioli]] said that this was \"one of the best dances in the show's history\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Streisand |first=Elizabeth |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-jordan-fisher-gets-two-perfect-scores/ |title='Dancing With the Stars' Recap: Jordan Fisher Gets Two Perfect Scores, Another Couple Goes Home |publisher=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |date= |accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Performances===\n'''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 17)|Season 17]]''' with professional partner [[Karina Smirnoff]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Week #\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Dance/song\n! colspan=\"3\"| Judges' score\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Result\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#FF6\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"| [[Carrie Ann Inaba|Inaba]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FF6\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|[[Len Goodman|Goodman]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FF6\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|[[Bruno Tonioli|Tonioli]]\n|-\n| 1 \n|[[Contemporary dance|Contemporary]] / \"[[If I Lose Myself]]\"\n|8\n|8\n|8\n|No Elimination\n|-\n|2\n|[[Jive (dance)|Jive]] / \"[[Kiss You (One Direction song)|Kiss You]]\"\n|9\n|8\n|9\n|Safe\n|-\n|3\n|[[Quickstep]] / \"Diga Diga Doo\"\n|9\n|8\n|9\n|Safe\n|-\n|4\n|[[Paso Doble]] / \"Zorongo\"\n|9\n|9*\n|9\n|Safe\n|-\n|5\n|[[Foxtrot]] / \"[[My Wish]]\"\n|9\n|9\n|10\n|Safe\n|-\n|6\n|[[Viennese Waltz]] / \"[[Game of Thrones Theme|Theme from '''Game of Thrones''']]\"<br />Switch-Up Challenge / Various\n|8<br />Awarded\n|7<br />4\n|8<br />Points\n|Not Eliminated\n|-\n|7\n|[[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-cha-cha]] / \"Pumpin Blood\"<br />Team Freestyle / \"[[The Fox (What Does the Fox Say?)]]\"\n|10<br />10\n|9<br />10\n|10<br />10\n|Safe\n|-\n|8\n|[[Argentine Tango]] / \"[[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Welcome to Burlesque]]\"<br />[[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-cha-cha]] Dance-Off / \"[[Woman's World (song)|Woman's World]]\"\n|9<br />Awarded\n|9*<br />3\n|9<br />Points\n|Safe\n|-\n|9\n|[[Waltz]] / \"[[Apologize (OneRepublic song)|Apologize]]\" <br /> [[Jazz dance|Jazz]] (Trio Challenge)* / \"[[Yeah! (Usher song)|Yeah!]]\"\n|9<br />10\n|9<br />10\n|10<br />10\n|Safe\n|-\n|10\n|[[Tango (dance)|Tango]] / \"[[My Songs Know What You Did in the Dark (Light Em Up)]]\" <br /> [[Rhumba|Rumba]] / \"My Songs Know What You Did in the Dark (Light Em Up)\" (acoustic version)\n|9<br />10\n|8/9*<br />10/10*\n|9<br />10\n|Safe\n|-\n|11\n|[[Quickstep]] / \"Diga Diga Doo\" <br /> [[Samba (ballroom dance)|Samba]] Relay / \"[[No Scrubs]]\" <br /> Freestyle / \"[[Smooth Criminal]]\" <br /> [[Cha-cha-cha (dance)|Cha-cha-cha]] & [[Foxtrot]] / \"[[All Night (Icona Pop song)|All Night]]\"\n|9<br />Awarded<br />10<br />9\n|9<br />5<br />10<br />9\n|9<br />Points<br />10<br />9\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|'''Runner Up'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#faf6f6; text-align:left;\"| <sup>1</sup>In week four, score was given by [[Julianne Hough]].<br /><sup>2</sup>In week eight, score was given by [[Cher]].<br /><sup>3</sup>The dancer Bleu and Smirnoff chose for the Trio Challenge was [[Witney Carson]].<br /><sup>4</sup>Additional score for Week 10 was awarded by guest judge [[Maksim Chmerkovskiy]].\n|}\n\n'''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 25)|Season 25]]''' with [[Jordan Fisher]] and his professional partner [[Lindsay Arnold]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Week #\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Dance/song\n! colspan=\"3\"| Judges' score\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Result\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#FF6\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"| [[Carrie Ann Inaba|Inaba]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FF6\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|[[Len Goodman|Goodman]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FF6\" width=\"10%\" align=\"center\"|[[Bruno Tonioli|Tonioli]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#FAF6F6\"|8\n|align=\"left\" bgcolor=\"#FAF6F6\"|Trio [[Salsa (dance)|Salsa]] / \"Que Viva La Vida\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FAF6F6\"|10\n|bgcolor=\"#FAF6F6\"|10\n|bgcolor=\"#FAF6F6\"|10\n|bgcolor=\"#FAF6F6\"|Safe\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#faf6f6; text-align:left;\"| <sup>1</sup>In week eight, Bleu joined [[Jordan Fisher]] and [[Lindsay Arnold]], to participate in a trio Salsa.\n|}\n\n==Music career==\n\n===2006\u20132008: ''Another Side'' and ''High School Musical''===\nBleu's first professionally recorded song was titled \"Circles\" or \"Circles in My Mind\" for his then TV show, ''[[Flight 29 Down]]''. Bleu signed a contract with [[Hollywood Records]], a [[Disney]]-owned label.{{efn|group=upper-alpha|His first single off the album, \"[[Push It to the Limit (Corbin Bleu song)|Push It to the Limit]]\", was recorded and appears on the soundtrack of ''[[It's My Turn Now|Jump In!]]''.}} His debut album ''[[Another Side (Corbin Bleu album)|Another Side]]'', was released in May 2007.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |title=(Corbin Bleu > Overview)|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p868214|pure_url=yes}} |website=AllMusic| accessdate=October 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000O1718E |title=Corbin Bleu album Another Side in may 2007 |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 36 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album charts, selling 18,000 in its first week. The album fuses rhythm and blues with hip-hop and other pop genres in an upbeat, wholesome commercial blend. Bleu, who admires [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Michael Jackson]], and [[Justin Timberlake]], cowrote five songs on the album. In 2007 he toured in support of Another Side with the teen sister duo [[Aly & AJ]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundchronicle.com/concert-news/aly-aj-corbin-bleu-and-drake-bell-launch-nextfest |title=Aly & AJ, Corbin Bleu, and Drake Bell Launch Nextfest |publisher=soundchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=June 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Corbin Bleu 5, (Cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Bleu in concert in October 2007]]\n\nBlue worked with [[Ne-Yo]] on \"I Get Lonely,\" and with other performers such as [[Matthew Gerrard]] and [[Eric Hudson]]. A music video for his first single, \"[[Push It to the Limit (Corbin Bleu song)|Push It to the Limit]]\" premiered on the [[Disney Channel]], and was used to promote the movie ''Jump In!'' \"Push It to the Limit\" reached the Top 20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and his second single, \"Deal With It\",{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"Deal With It\" did not enter the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], but peaked at number one hundred twelve on the Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles chart.}} was originally written and sung by [[Jay Sean]]. He later gave it to Corbin Bleu, whose version of the song features background vocals by Jay Sean. The song earned Jay Sean a [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI Songwriter Award]]. peaking at No. 15. He sang the duet \"Still There for Me\" with [[Vanessa Hudgens]] for his debut album ''[[Another Side (Corbin Bleu album)|Another Side]]''.\n\nBleu toured with fellow ''High School Musical'' cast members from late November 2006 to late January 2007 in ''[[High School Musical: The Concert]]'', and with [[Drake Bell]] and [[Aly & AJ]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/artist/Bleu,+Corbin/a/Corbin+Bleu.htm |title=Full Album Corbin Bleu 2007, 2009 |publisher=Cduniverse.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> performing in about 40 different cities.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jim White |url=http://blog.timesunion.com/reviews/251/251/ |title=The Nextfest Featuring Aly & AJ, Drake Bell, Corbin Bleu and Bianca Ryan, SPAC, 08/24/2007 \u2013 You Review \u2013 Capital Region concert and performance reviews \u2013 timesunion.com \u2013 Alb |publisher=Blog.timesunion.com |date=August 25, 2007 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kidsturncentral.com/topics/music/livenation.htm |title=Live Nation: Teen Tour of the Summer \u2013 2007 Music News |publisher=Kidsturncentral.com |date=May 23, 2007 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> To promote his debut album, Bleu performed at the ''Nextfest Summer Tour'' with the teen sister duo [[Aly & AJ]] and [[Drake Bell]] with Special Guest [[Bianca Ryan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/teen-tour-of-the-summer-star-studded-nextfest-to-visit-29-cities-across-north-america-58526947.html |title=Teen Tour of the Summer: Star-Studded Nextfest to Visit 29 Cities Across North America |publisher=prnewswire.com |date= |accessdate=May 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[Another Side (Corbin Bleu album)|Another Side]]'', he wrote or co-wrote five of the album's twelve songs. He wrote two songs that appear as bonus tracks on the European version. One of those tracks was titled \"Shake It Off\", an ode to the musician [[Prince (musician)|Prince]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/playbillcoms-cue-a-hollywood-bowl-hairspray-star-corbin-bleu-com-181404 |title=PLAYBILL.COM'S CUE & A: Hollywood Bowl Hairspray Star Corbin Bleu |magazine=[[Playbill]] |accessdate=August 2, 2011}}</ref> His debut single \"Run It Back Again\" was featured in the movie ''[[Minutemen (film)|Minutemen]]'', on January 22, 2008. The song is also featured on ''[[Radio Disney Jams series#Radio Disney Jams, Vol. 10|Radio Disney Jams, Vol. 10]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Nordyke |first=Kimberly |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mcqueen-clock-dis-minutemen-156509 |title=McQueen on clock for Dis' 'Minutemen' |magazine=Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=December 6, 2007}}</ref>\n\nBleu performed at the ''Crawford County Fair Grandstand'' with [[Vanessa Hudgens]], during an August 18, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/local_news/high-school-musical-stars-appearing-at-fair/article_c57d3d5e-29b4-5727-8adc-663cc13ab2d2.html |title='High School Musical' stars appearing at fair. |first=Jane |last=Smith |publisher=meadvilletribune.com |date= |accessdate=April 22, 2008}}</ref> During this time, Bleu performed at the ''[[Michigan State Fair]]'' with [[Raven-Symon\u00e9]], during an August 25, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/entertainment/flint/2008/08/ravensymone_corbin_bleu_happy.html |title=Raven-Symone, Corbin Bleu happy to be headed to the Michigan State Fair. |first=Misty |last=Gower |publisher=mlive.com |date= August 21, 2008|accessdate=August 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u2013present: ''Speed of Light'' and ''Holiday Inn''===\nHis second album ''[[Speed of Light (album)|Speed of Light]]'' was released on March 10, 2009, via [[Hollywood Records]]. In an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Bleu stated that:\n\n[[File:Corbin Bleu, 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Bleu in concert in August 2008]]\n\n{{quote| He had begun working on his follow-up album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,4925855,00.html |title=Full Album Corbin Bleu 2009 |publisher=Artistdirect.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> There will be a lot of differences with the second album. First of all, it's just more personal. I'm involved in every aspect of the writing. As far as the direction of the music, it's very different. I wanted this album to have something that was a little bit of rock, a little bit of R&B and a little bit of pop.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bonner |first=Julie |url=http://www.disneysociety.com/2008/11/17/corbin-bleu-to-release-new-album-speed-of-light/ |title=Corbin Bleu in speed-of-light album new 2009 |publisher=Disneysociety.com |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327124359/http://www.disneysociety.com/2008/11/17/corbin-bleu-to-release-new-album-speed-of-light/ |archive-date=March 27, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nThe album's first single, \"Moments That Matter\", was performed by Bleu at [[First inauguration of Barack Obama#Kids' Inaugural: \"We Are the Future\"|Kids' Inaugural: \"We Are the Future\"]].<ref name=MOMC>{{cite web|url=http://www.wusa9.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=80624&catid=158|title=Michelle Obama, Miley Cyrus: Favorites At Concert|accessdate=February 13, 2009|date=January 20, 2009|publisher=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA-TV (Washington,&nbsp;D.C.)]]|author=Cyr, Emily|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213000420/http://www.wusa9.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=80624&catid=158|archivedate=February 13, 2012}}</ref> It was released as a teaser from the music video. The song has been featured in Bleu's movie ''[[Free Style (film)|Free Style]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Coverage-First-Look-at-Corbin-Bleu-as-GODSPELLs-JESUS-20120404 |title=Photo Flash: First Look at Corbin Bleu as GODSPELL's 'JESUS'! |publisher=broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=April 4, 2012}}</ref> alongside release of a music video for the song.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044405/corbin-bleu-tunes-in-for-sophomore-album| title=Corbin Bleu Tunes in For Sophomore Album | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].com | publisher=John Benson | date =September 19, 2008 | accessdate=September 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe album failed to debut on Billboard Top 200 album charts.<ref>{{cite magazine |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=corbin bleu|chart=all}} |title=Corbin Bleu Music News & Info |magazine= Billboard.com}}</ref> Producer [[Eric Hudson]] was attached to the project, along with songwriter/lyricist [[Claude Kelly]]. Bleu performed the planned tracks \"Close\", \"Whatever It Takes\", and \"Champion\" on a summer concert tour with singer/actor Justin Stein.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/speed-of-light-album-corbin-bleu.html |title=Corbin Bleu \u2013 Speed of Light Lyrics! |publisher=Metrolyrics.com |date=March 23, 2009 |accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> According to media sources, the album sold less than 4,000 in its first week, despite promotion from [[Myspace]]. The album spawned the single \"Celebrate You\" that was released in January 2009. Bleu performed that song at [[Disneyland]] as part of the 25th anniversary of the [[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade]]. The song is the official song for the \"Year of Celebration\" at the [[Disneyland Resort]] and the \"What Will You Celebrate?\" campaign at the [[Walt Disney World]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thismustbepop.com/2009_01_01_archive.html|title=This Must Be Pop In January 2009|publisher=thismustbepop.com|date=January 31, 2009|accessdate=January 31, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119234014/http://www.thismustbepop.com/2009_01_01_archive.html|archivedate=November 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Bleu sang the duet \"[[If We Were a Movie]]\" with [[Miley Cyrus]] for the ''[[Hannah Montana 3]]'' soundtrack album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Hannah+Montana+feat.+Corbin+Bleu&titel=If+We+Were+A+Movie&cat=s|title=uk-charts.com \u2013 Hannah Montana feat. Corbin Bleu \u2013 If We Were A Movie |first= |last=|date=|work=[[UK Singles Chart|UK charts]]|publisher=|accessdate=July 7, 2009}}</ref> Bleu performed [[Michael Jackson]]'s song, \"[[Human Nature (Michael Jackson song)|Human Nature]]\" during a July 14, 2009 concert on the [[Disney Wonder]] cruise ship.<ref>{{cite web|first=Cruise |last=News |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UYPW2pslHYI |publisher= YouTube |title= Corbin Bleu sings Michael Jackson's Human Nature on the Disney Wonder cruise ship. |date= |accessdate=July 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Bleu signed a one-album recording contract with [[Sh-K-Boom Records|Ghostlight Records]] to distribute his ''[[Holiday Inn (musical)|Holiday Inn, The New Irving Berlin Musical]]'' soundtrack music,<ref name=\"ReferenceF\" /> was released digitally on June 2, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ryan |last=McPhee |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/holiday-inn-sets-cast-album-release-date|title=Holiday Inn Sets Cast Album Release Date |date=May 30, 2017|publisher=playbill.com|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref> The album featured twenty-one songs, and was produced by [[Kurt Deutsch]] with Todd Whitelock serving as coproducer and Universal Stage Productions as executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|url=http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/holiday-inn-cast-recording-broadway_79511.html|title=Broadway's Holiday Inn Musical to Receive Cast Recording |date=|publisher=theatermania.com|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBleu released his a two-album recording contract with Ghostlight Records to distribute his ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' soundtrack music,<ref>{{cite web|first=Logan|last=Culwell-Block|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/get-a-first-listen-to-corbin-bleu-singing-bianca-from-the-new-kiss-me-kate-cast-recording|title=Get a First Listen to Corbin Bleu Singing 'Bianca' from the New Kiss Me, Kate Cast Recording |date=June 6, 2019|publisher=playbill.com|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref> the 24th cast album recording for [[Roundabout Theatre Company]], since launching the musical theatre program with ''[[She Loves Me]]'' in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/recordings/Kiss-MeKate-|title=Kiss Me, Kate CD 2019 |date=|publisher=broadwayworld.com|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref> the album will be recorded on April 22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|url=https://www.ghostlightrecords.com/kiss-me-kate-2019-broadway-cast-recording.html|title=Kiss Me Kate (2019 Broadway Cast Recording) |date=|publisher=[[Sh-K-Boom Records|Ghostlight Records]].com|accessdate=June 7, 2019}}</ref> The album featured eighteen songs. produced by [[Kurt Deutsch]] and [[Lawrence Manchester]], was released digitally on June 7, 2019.<ref name=\"ReferenceK\" />\n\n===Voice and musical ability===\nIn his interview with [[Paul Wontorek]], Bleu discussed that he is naturally a [[Baritone|Lyric Baritone]].<ref name=\"youtube1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KXOB7GYu-B0 |title=Show People Interview With Paul Wontorek:Corbin Bleu |publisher= Broadway.com}}</ref> His trained voice has been described as being \"decent and pleasant which fits well into both pop and R&B\".<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/another-side-mw0000736351 |title=Another Side Album Review |publisher= Allmusic.com}}</ref> As a musical theatre performer, Bleu claimed that he is a huge fan of [[Brian d'Arcy James]] and says that he gets vocal influences from him.<ref name=\"youtube1\"/> Due to his dancing, songwriting, and dance-influenced sound, Corbin Bleu has earned comparisons to [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sasha and Corbin 2018.png|thumb|upright|Bleu with his wife [[Sasha Clements]] in January 2018]]\nIn December 2005, Bleu served Thanksgiving dinner and Christmas Eve lunch at a Los Angeles homeless shelter with [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]].<ref name=\"shineonmedia\"/>\n\nIn 2011, Bleu as a frequent volunteer worker, worked for charities such as [[Starlight Children's Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstgiving.com/corbinbleu |title=Starlight Children's Foundation \u2013 Corbin Bleu's Fundraising Page |publisher=Firstgiving.com |date= |accessdate=August 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100201105818/http://www.firstgiving.com/corbinbleu |archive-date=February 1, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0088298/news| title=Corbin Bleu Reads Children's Tale at Stellar Night Gala | work= imdb.com | publisher= Internet Movie Database| date =March 29, 2011 | accessdate=March 29, 2011 }}</ref> the [[Make-A-Wish Foundation]], and [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]], and served Thanksgiving dinner and Christmas Eve lunch at a Los Angeles homeless shelter with [[Debby Ryan]] in 2008.<ref name=\"shineonmedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shineon-media.com/2009/11/25/corbin-bleu-debby-ryan-serve-up-thanksgiving-dinner/ |title=Corbin Bleu & Debby Ryan Serve Up Thanksgiving Dinner |publisher=Shineon-media.com |date= November 26, 2009|accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> Bleu has been a supporter of [[Do Something]], hosting the sixth annual Do Something Awards in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our host Corbin Bleu at DS Awards |url=http://www.dosomething.org/blog/celebsgonegood/cgg-exclusive-corbin-bleu-ds-awards|publisher=Do Something}}</ref> In May 2011, Bleu also attended the Do Something Awards kick-off event. He teamed up with [[Aimee Teegarden]], [[Kevin Jonas]] and [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] during the event to honor the thirteen nominees for the Do Something Award that gave $100,000 in recognition of their outstanding activism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin Jonas, Aimee Teegarden & Corbin Bleu Kick Off 2011 Do Something Awards |url= http://www.cambio.com/news/kevin-jonas-aimee-teegarden-corbin-bleu-kick-off-2011-do-something-awards| website= Cambio.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Bleu began dating actress [[Sasha Clements]], whom he had first met in a Toronto grocery store.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.accesshollywood.com/corbin-bleus-dancing-with-the-stars-blog-redemption-in-the-ballroom_article_86304|title=Corbin Bleu's Dancing With The Stars Blog: Redemption In The Ballroom!|date=November 4, 2013|first=Corbin|last=Bleu|work=[[Access Hollywood]]| publisher=[[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]|accessdate=November 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.celebuzz.com/2013-11-24/new-pics-ashley-tisdale-and-fiance-christopher-french-playfully-pose-at-their-engagement-party/|title=NEW PICS: Ashley Tisdale and Fiance Christopher French Playfully Pose at Their Engagement Party|date=November 24, 2013| work= [[Celebuzz]]|publisher=[[Buzz Media]]|accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref> On October 15, 2014, he proposed to Clements in front of [[Cinderella Castle|Cinderella's Castle]] at Orlando's [[Disney World]] with an engagement ring placed inside a glass slipper. They later appeared on [[TLC (TV network)|TLC]] reality series ''[[Say Yes to the Dress]]'', which documented the bride-to-be's search for the perfect wedding gown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tlc.com/tv-shows/say-yes-to-the-dress/videos/corbin-bleu-at-kleinfeld/|title=Actor Corbin Bleu stopped by Kleinfeld to help fiance and fellow actress Sasha Clements pick out her dress for the big day|date=February 5, 2016|work=[[Say Yes to the Dress]]|publisher=[[TLC (TV network)|TLC]]|accessdate=February 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503055954/http://www.tlc.com/tv-shows/say-yes-to-the-dress/videos/corbin-bleu-at-kleinfeld/|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> They married in the presence of 160 guests at Hummingbird Nest in [[Santa Susana, California]] on July 23, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/corbin-bleu-and-sasha-clements-are-married/| title= Corbin Bleu and Sasha Clements Are Married|first=Gabrielle |last=Olya|date=July 24, 2016|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate= July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\"| Director(s)\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n!scope=row| ''[[Soldier (1998 American film)|Soldier]]''\n| 1998\n| {{sort|Johnny|Johnny}}\n| {{sort|Anderson|[[Paul W. S. Anderson]]}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/entertainment/movies/article/Soldier-1982535.php|title=Soldier|last=Westbrook|first=Bruce|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=October 23, 1998|accessdate=October 18, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row| ''Beach Movie''\n| 1998\n| Kid\n| {{sort|Quinn|John Quinn}}\n| \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/boardheads_1998/ |title=Boardheads |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=November 25, 2003}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row| ''Family Tree''\n| 1999\n| {{sort|Ricky|Ricky}}\n| {{sort|Clark|[[Duane Clark]]}}\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/From-High-School-to-the-Heights-Corbin-Bleu-to-Join-IN-THE-HEIGHTS-Jan-25-20091208 |title=From 'High School' to the 'Heights' \u2013 Corbin Bleu to Join In the Heights Jan. 25 |publisher=broadwayworld.com |da